{"title_page": "Watton-at-Stone", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{infobox UK place \n|static_image_name=Water Pump, Watton-at-Stone.jpg\n|static_image_width=240px\n|static_image_caption=Village cast iron water pump, dating from the late 19th century\n|country = England\n|official_name= Watton-at-Stone\n| population = 2,272\n| population_ref = (2011 Census including Whempstead)\n |shire_district= [[East Hertfordshire]]\n|shire_county = [[Hertfordshire]]\n|region= East of England\n|constituency_westminster= [[North East Hertfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Hertfordshire]]\n|post_town= HERTFORD\n|postcode_district = SG14\n|postcode_area= SG \n|dial_code= 01920\n|os_grid_reference= TL299194\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.8580|-0.1130|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n'''Watton-at-Stone''' is a village in the English county of [[Hertfordshire]], situated midway between the towns of [[Stevenage]] and [[Hertford]] in the valley of the [[River Beane]]. The 2011 census showed a population of 2,272 living in 946 households. Watton-at-Stone is also a [[civil parish]] in [[East Hertfordshire]] District Council.<ref>{{citation\n|last=2001 Census\n|title=Key Statistics: Parish Headcounts\n|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=795296&c=Watton-at-Stone&d=16&e=15&g=454489&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1205671918406&enc=1&dsFamilyId=779}}</ref>\n\n== Village life ==\n[[File:Watton-at-Stone Village Sign.jpg|thumb|left|175px]]\n\nThere is little employment directly within the village and it largely serves as a [[Bedroom community|dormitory]] for commuters to London or to the nearby towns with hourly trains to [[Moorgate station]].\n\nThe village has a primary school and nursery school. The co-educational [[Heath Mount School|Heath Mount]] [[Independent school (UK)|independent school]] is located on the outskirts in the private estate of the Grade II* listed [[Woodhall Park]].\n\nThe [[A602 road|A602]] formerly ran through the centre of the village between Stevenage and Hertford before a [[Bypass route|bypass]] was built in 1984 through farmland to the north-east.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/> The section of the road to Hertford was renamed the [[A119 road (England)|A119]], and the A602 then ran out of Watton-at-Stone to [[Ware, Hertfordshire|Ware]]. Watton-at-Stone is served by a [[Watton-at-Stone railway station|railway station]] on the [[Hertford Loop Line]]. The station opened for passengers on 2 June 1924, was closed on 11 September 1939 (though the line continued to run through the village), and reopened on 17 May 1982, paid for partly by public subscription.\n\nA [[war memorial]] lies in a field adjoining the church.\n\nIn the village itself there is a small convenience store, caf\u00e9 and takeaway restaurant as well as a hairdressers, newsagent and a butcher's shop.\n\n== History ==\n=== Etymology ===\nThe name '''Watton''' first appeared in writing in an 11th-century publication of 10th century [[Anglo-Saxon language|Anglo-Saxon]] wills as ''Wattun''. It was later recorded in the [[Domesday Book]] as both ''Wodtune'' and ''Watone''.<ref name=\"herts_history\">\n{{citation\n|first=William|last=Page\n|title=A History of the County of Hertford: volume 3\n|date=1912\n|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43596\n|accessdate=16 March 2008}}</ref> The origin of the word is uncertain, and is variously ascribed to [[Old English language|Old English]] ''w\u00e1d'' or [[woad]], and ''ton'' meaning small farming settlement; or ''waden'' meaning [[Ford (river)|ford]]; or from ''wa\u00e9tan'' meaning watery.\n\nThe suffix '''-at-Stone''' dates from the early 13th century and may be derived from the presence of two large examples of [[Hertfordshire puddingstone]], now situated at the former Waggon and Horses [[public house]].<ref name=ehdc>\n{{citation\n| last = East Herts Council\n| title = Watton-at-Stone\n| url = http://www.eastherts.gov.uk/index.jsp?articleid=9745\n| accessdate = 8 June 2015\n}}</ref> However, it is far more likely that the suffix refers to the [[Roman road]] (anciently described as a Stone Street) that ran from [[Verulamium]] (modern [[St Albans]]), fording the [[River Beane]] at Watton-at-Stone. The area where the bridge over the railway was built was shown on tithe maps as a common, and the fields to the east and west of this point were named Stoneyfield and Further Stoneyfield. It is deduced that the Roman Road passed through this area, and the later village took its name from the important routeway. In the 1950s, sections of the road agger, composed of large flint nodules, could still be seen at several points in the village; most obviously, the northern boundary of the grounds of Chestnut House preserves the line of the road<ref name=\"herts_landscape\">{{citation\n|title=Hertfordshire Landscape Survey: Woodhall Park and Watton-at-Stone slopes\n|last=Hertfordshire County Council Environment\n|date=October 2001\n|url=http://www.hertsdirect.org/docs/pdf/a/Area070.pdf\n|accessdate=8 June 2015\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071029231107/http://enquire.hertscc.gov.uk/landscsh/Areas/area70.htm |archivedate = 29 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Prehistoric archaeological finds ===\nArchaeological finds indicate [[prehistory|prehistoric]] activity in the Watton-at-Stone area before the village was established. The earliest finds are [[Paleolithic]] [[hand axe]]s found in the village and also at the Frogmore gravel pit, and there are traces of a [[Mesolithic]] site near the roundabout at the northern end of the bypass.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/> [[Neolithic]] pits were found off Station Road and several Neolithic or [[Bronze Age]] [[ring ditch]]es are evident in fields surrounding Watton.<ref name = \"Lockyear\"/><ref name=\"Village Guide\"/>\n\nTo the west of the village near Raffin Green is a significant late Bronze Age site and [[Iron Age]] enclosure in the Great Humphreys field.<ref name = \"Lockyear\"/> It was close to here that the Iron Age ''Aston Mirror'' was found, closer to Watton-at-Stone than to the village of [[Aston, Hertfordshire|Aston]], but technically in Aston parish due to the convoluted border. It is now kept at the [[British Museum]].<ref name=ehdc/> Another Iron Age enclosure was located by Broom Hall Farm, with an adjacent Roman farmstead and also a nearby Roman crematorium from which 27 burials were extracted.<ref name = \"Lockyear\"/><ref name=\"Village Guide\"/> A collection of possibly [[Belgae|Belgic]] armour and weaponry was discovered in the mid-19th century by workers digging a drain to the west of the village.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/>\n\n=== Roman and Anglo-Saxon origins  ===\nThe origins of Watton-at-Stone are from the construction of the Roman road, which crossed the High Street at the point of the modern [[milestone]]. Archaeological evidence suggests significant Roman activity at the roadside, with a probable Roman building near the Rectory<ref>{{cite web |url=https:www.hertfordshire.gov.uk/media-library/documents/environment-and-planning/planning/planning-applications-decisions/screening-opinions/a602-environmental-scoping-and-methodology-report-5.5.15.pdf |title=A602 Improvements |author=Hertfordshire County Council |date=5 May 2015 |website=hertfordshire.gov.uk |publisher=Hertfordshire County Council |access-date=25 January 2020 |quote=}}</ref> and Roman field boundaries off Station Road suggesting some permanent occupation.<ref name = \"Lockyear\">{{cite book |last=Lockyear |first=Kris |date=2015 |title=Archaeology In Hertfordshire - Recent Research |url= |location=Hatfield |publisher=Hertfordshire Publications |page= |isbn=978-1-909291-42-3 |author-link=}}</ref> Watton was possibly a market place trading to travellers as they slowed to cross the River Beane, and the High Street may have been a pre-existing track and therefore the new Roman road formed a crossroads here.<ref name = \"Village Guide\">{{cite book |author=Watton Conservation Society |date=2002 |title= Watton-at-Stone Village Guide|url=https://www.watton-pc.org.uk/files/web_guide_full.pdf |location=Watton-at-Stone |publisher=Watton-at-Stone Conservation Society |page= |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref>\n\n[[Anglo-Saxon]] settlers developed Watton further into a village, with evidence of early Anglo-Saxon field boundaries and a crematorium off Station Road.<ref name = \"Lockyear\"/> It is likely that the focus of the Anglo-Saxon settlement was on the high ground at Watton Green, overlooking the Roman road and river valley below.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/> There was a possible battle between the [[Danes (Germanic tribe)|Danes]] and [[Anglo-Saxons|Saxons]] which took place on a field named \"Danesfield\" to the west of the village, although the field name is the only evidence to suggest this. If a battle did occur here it would most likely to have been in 911<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/> with 1016 suggested as an alternative possible date.<ref name=\"herts_landscape\"/>\n\nThe Watton [[manor]] was anciently held by the Crown but by 1066 the Lord of Watton manor was Alwin Horne, an Anglo-Saxon [[thegn]] who owned other lands at [[Walkern]], [[Sacombe]] and [[Middlesex]].<ref name=\"Powell-Smith\">{{cite web |url=https://opendomesday.org/place/TL3018/watton/ |title=Open Domesday |last=Powell-Smith |first=Anna |date= |website= |access-date=23 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"herts_history\"/> Alwin Horne is believed to have fought at the [[Battle of Stamford Bridge]] under [[Harold Godwinson|King Harold]] in 1066 and later that year killed at the [[Battle of Hastings]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://englefieldhistory.net/owners.html/ |title=Englefield History |last=Smith |first=Richard J |date=2019 |website= |access-date=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Middle Ages and Early Modern period  ===\n[[File:Statue Of Henry FitzEylwin Holborn Viaduct.jpg|thumb|200px|Henry fitz Ailwin statue at Holborn Viaduct, London]]\nThe [[Domesday Book]] shows that the population of Watton village in 1086 was about 90, consisting of 18 households (10 villagers, 4 smallholders and 4 slaves). The manor was worth \u00a35 and it had a mill, woodland with 100 pigs and a meadow. It was jointly held by Derman (of London) and Alward (the noble),<ref name=\"Powell-Smith\"/> who were both [[moneyer|moneyers]] from London.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.academia.edu/37264685/Unequal_Partners_in_Government_Domesday_Moneyers/ |title=Unequal Partners in government? Domesday Moneyers |last=Roffe |first=David |date=2018 |website= |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>  There was an additional manor associated with Watton that had 6 households and a church, which could have been the Woodhall manor. The first mention by name of the Woodhall manor was in about 1130 when it was held by Ralph de Watton.<ref name=\"herts_history\"/>\n\nDerman's great nephew [[Henry fitz Ailwin]], the first Mayor of London, inherited the Watton manor in 1165. He built a hermitage chapel in what is now Chapel Wood and possibly built a new manor house in what is now Well Wood.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/> At about this time, perhaps as a consequence of Henry fitz Ailwin's new buildings, a new manor called Crowborough emerged from the Watton manor. Crowborough was first referenced in 1266 when it was held by Alice de Rivers.<ref name=\"herts_history\"/> Crowborough Hall stood at Watton Green and the moat which surrounded it can still be seen to this day.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/>\n\nHugh Bardolf inherited Watton manor in 1287, later it was held by [[John Bardolf, 3rd Baron Bardolf|John Bardolf]] and [[Thomas Bardolf, 5th Baron Bardolf|Thomas Bardolf]] with the Bardolf family owning the Watton and Crowborough manors at various times until 1562. During this period the house and chapel in Well Wood and Chapel Wood were abandoned, and so in circa 1520 the Watton manor was renamed Bardolf manor and the manor house moved to what is now Bardolphs Farm.<ref name=\"herts_history\"/> A new manor called Watkins Hall was created and was first known to be held by Thomas Munden in about 1540.<ref name=\"herts_history\"/>\n\nPhilip Boteler (Butler) inherited the Woodhall estate in about 1375 and later descendants to have the title included [[Philip Butler]] and [[John Boteler, 1st Baron Boteler of Brantfield|John Boteler]] who held the Watton, Woodhall and Crowborough manors. The three estates were in possession of the Botelers (Butlers) until as late as 1780.<ref name=\"herts_history\"/>\n\nIn 1662 brothers [[Maurice Thomson]] and [[William Thompson (1614-1681)|Sir William Thompson]], who had grown up in the village, founded Watton's first free school for 20 poor children.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/>\n\nAfter Woodhall was mostly destroyed by fire in 1771, from which an elderly John Boteler was able to escape, building of the new house began in 1775. The notorious [[Thomas Rumbold]] took possession of Woodhall in 1777, followed by [[Paul Benfield]] in 1793. The estate was then bought in 1801 by [[Samuel Smith (1754-1834)|Samuel Smith]] and the Smith family later combined the Watton, Woodhall and Crowborough manors into one and still holds it today.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/>\n\nIn later years, the natural springs in the area once made the village a popular [[spa town]].<ref>name=\"herts_landscape\"</ref> The village has a number of dwellings dating from early [[Tudor architecture|Tudor]], such as ''Watton Place'', through to late [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]] constructions.<ref name=\"herts_history\"/>\n\n== Church of St Mary and St Andrew ==\nThe [[parish church]] is dedicated to St Andrew and St Mary. It stands on thirteenth century foundations and dates from the early-mid fifteenth century,<ref name=\"herts_history\"/><ref name=ehdc/> and is built in the [[Perpendicular Period#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular]] style.<ref>{{citation\n| first = Herbert H. | last = Tompkins\n| title = Hertfordshire, Second Edition\n| url = http://www.gutenberg.org/files/18252/18252-8.txt\n| year = 1922}}</ref>\nA chapel was added to the north side of the church in the late fifteenth century. The building is constructed from [[flint]], and is protected by a [[Grade II* listed|Grade II*]] heritage listing.<ref>http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/101341464-church-of-st-andrew-and-st-mary-watton-at-stone#.WdifD87m5sA</ref>\n\n== Famous residents ==\nThe evangelical author and social campaigner [[Edward Bickersteth (1786\u20131850)|Edward Bickersteth]] was rector of the church for twenty years from 1830 until his death in 1850.<ref>{{Citation|last=Hylson-Smith|first=Kenneth|title=Evangelicals in the Church of England, 1734\u20131984|publisher=Continuum International |date=1989|page=144|isbn=978-0-567-29161-5|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7iSULsFN_LgC&pg=PA144}}</ref><ref name=\"Larsen\">{{Citation|last=Larsen|first=David L.|title=The Company of the Preachers|publisher=Kregel Publications|date=1998|page=463|isbn=978-0-8254-3086-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gwMTCUs62TQC&pg=PA463}}</ref> His one-time [[curate]] was the theological scholar [[Thomas Rawson Birks|Thomas Birks]].<ref name=\"Larsen\" />\n\n[[Jack Meyer (educator and cricketer)|Jack Meyer]], the Somerset cricketer and founder of [[Millfield|Millfield School]] grew up in the old Georgian red-brick rectory overlooking the cricket field, his father was the vicar of the church.<ref>Ampthill and District News, January 1911, url=https://clophillhistory.mooncarrot.org.uk/AmpthillNewsJanuary1911.php</ref>\nIn the summer of 1923, [[Alan Turing]] and his family stayed with their friends the Meyer family for six weeks at the rectory, Alan being the founder of computer science and the leading cryptologist at Bletchley Park in World War II. Andrew Hodges in his biography: ''Alan Turing: The Enigma'' tells of how a gypsy fortune teller at the church f\u00eate foretold that he would be a genius.<ref>{{cite book|last= Hodges|first= Andrew|date= 1983|title= Alan Turing: The Enigma|url= https://archive.org/details/alanturing00andr|location= |publisher= Simon & Schuster|page= [https://archive.org/details/alanturing00andr/page/20 20]|isbn= 0671492071|author-link= Andrew Hodges|url-access= registration}}</ref>\n\nThe locomotive engineer [[Sir Nigel Gresley]] lived in Watton House until his death in 1941.<ref>{{citation\n| first = Oswald S. | last = Nock\n| title = The Locomotives of Sir Nigel Gresley\n| publisher = Longmans, Green and Co\n| year = 2007\n| page = 173}}</ref>\n\nWatton-at-Stone was the childhood home of the actor [[Rupert Grint]], well-known from his role of [[Ron Weasley]] in the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' film series]].<ref>\n{{citation\n| last = filmreference.com\n| title = Rupert Grint Biography\n| url = http://www.filmreference.com/film/26/Rupert-Grint.html\n| accessdate = 4 February 2008}}</ref>\nIt was also home to the boxing promoter [[Frank Warren (promoter)|Frank Warren]].\n\nFootballer [[Harry Toffolo]] grew up in the village.<ref>Hertfordshire Life, February 2015, url=https://www.hertfordshirelife.co.uk/people/bright-young-things-1-3959167</ref>\n\n== Alternative names ==\nThe name is also spelled unhyphenated as '''Watton at Stone''' and appears in this form on [[Ordnance Survey]] maps. The County Council favours the hyphenated version. Both spellings are equally valid.\n\nLocally, the '-at-Stone' suffix is frequently dropped.<ref>{{Citation|last=Tompkins|first=H.W.|title=Hertfordshire |publisher=BiblioBazaar|date=2008|pages=182\u2013183|isbn=978-1-4375-3234-0|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9bxP3iowDuAC&pg=PA182}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n* [http://watton-pc.org.uk Parish council website]\n* [http://www.wattonatstone.herts.sch.uk/ Village primary school website]\n* [http://www.heathmount.org Heath Mount school website]\n* [http://www.hertfordshire-genealogy.co.uk/links/watton.htm Watton-at-Stone (A Guide to Old Hertfordshire)]\n* [http://www.unc.edu/celtic/design/aston/aston.html The Aston mirror]\n* [http://www.wattonatstone.info/watton_web/wattonStart.html Image gallery]\n\n{{Civil parishes of Hertfordshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:East Hertfordshire District]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{infobox UK place \n|static_image_name=Water Pump, Watton-at-Stone.jpg\n|static_image_width=240px\n|static_image_caption=Village cast iron water pump, dating from the late 19th century\n|country = England\n|official_name= Watton-at-Stone\n| population = 2,272\n| population_ref = (2011 Census including Whempstead)\n |shire_district= [[East Hertfordshire]]\n|shire_county = [[Hertfordshire]]\n|region= East of England\n|constituency_westminster= [[North East Hertfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Hertfordshire]]\n|post_town= HERTFORD\n|postcode_district = SG14\n|postcode_area= SG \n|dial_code= 01920\n|os_grid_reference= TL299194\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.8580|-0.1130|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n'''Watton-at-Stone''' is a village in the English county of [[Hertfordshire]], situated midway between the towns of [[Stevenage]] and [[Hertford]] in the valley of the [[River Beane]]. The 2011 census showed a population of 2,272 living in 946 households. Watton-at-Stone is also a [[civil parish]] in [[East Hertfordshire]] District Council.<ref>{{citation\n|last=2001 Census\n|title=Key Statistics: Parish Headcounts\n|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=795296&c=Watton-at-Stone&d=16&e=15&g=454489&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1205671918406&enc=1&dsFamilyId=779}}</ref>\n\n== Village life ==\n[[File:Watton-at-Stone Village Sign.jpg|thumb|left|175px]]\n\nThere is little employment directly within the village and it largely serves as a [[Bedroom community|dormitory]] for commuters to London or to the nearby towns with hourly trains to [[Moorgate station]].\n\nThe village has a primary school and nursery school. The co-educational [[Heath Mount School|Heath Mount]] [[Independent school (UK)|independent school]] is located on the outskirts in the private estate of the Grade II* listed [[Woodhall Park]].\n\nThe [[A602 road|A602]] formerly ran through the centre of the village between Stevenage and Hertford before a [[Bypass route|bypass]] was built in 1984 through farmland to the north-east.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/> The section of the road to Hertford was renamed the [[A119 road (England)|A119]], and the A602 then ran out of Watton-at-Stone to [[Ware, Hertfordshire|Ware]]. Watton-at-Stone is served by a [[Watton-at-Stone railway station|railway station]] on the [[Hertford Loop Line]]. The station opened for passengers on 2 June 1924, was closed on 11 September 1939 (though the line continued to run through the village), and reopened on 17 May 1982, paid for partly by public subscription.\n\nA [[war memorial]] lies in a field adjoining the church.\n\nIn the village itself there is a small convenience store, caf\u00e9 and takeaway restaurant as well as a hairdressers, newsagent and a butcher's shop.\n\n== History ==\n=== Etymology ===\nThe name '''Watton''' first appeared in writing in an 11th-century publication of 10th century [[Anglo-Saxon language|Anglo-Saxon]] wills as ''Wattun''. It was later recorded in the [[Domesday Book]] as both ''Wodtune'' and ''Watone''.<ref name=\"herts_history\">\n{{citation\n|first=William|last=Page\n|title=A History of the County of Hertford: volume 3\n|date=1912\n|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43596\n|accessdate=16 March 2008}}</ref> The origin of the word is uncertain, and is variously ascribed to [[Old English language|Old English]] ''w\u00e1d'' or [[woad]], and ''ton'' meaning small farming settlement; or ''waden'' meaning [[Ford (river)|ford]]; or from ''wa\u00e9tan'' meaning watery. The suffix '''-at-Stone''' dates from the early 13th century and may be derived from the presence of two large examples of [[Hertfordshire puddingstone]], now situated at the former Waggon and Horses [[public house]].<ref name=ehdc>\n{{citation\n| last = East Herts Council\n| title = Watton-at-Stone\n| url = http://www.eastherts.gov.uk/index.jsp?articleid=9745\n| accessdate = 8 June 2015\n}}</ref>\n\nHowever, it is far more likely that the suffix refers to the [[Roman road]] (anciently described as a Stone Street) that ran from [[Verulamium]] (modern [[St Albans]]), fording the [[River Beane]] at Watton-at-Stone. The area where the bridge over the railway was built was shown on tithe maps as a common, and the fields to the east and west of this point were named Stoneyfield and Further Stoneyfield. It is deduced that the Roman Road passed through this area, and the later village took its name from the important routeway. In the 1950s, sections of the road agger, composed of large flint nodules, could still be seen at several points in the village; most obviously, the northern boundary of the grounds of Chestnut House preserves the line of the road<ref name=\"herts_landscape\">{{citation\n|title=Hertfordshire Landscape Survey: Woodhall Park and Watton-at-Stone slopes\n|last=Hertfordshire County Council Environment\n|date=October 2001\n|url=http://www.hertsdirect.org/docs/pdf/a/Area070.pdf\n|accessdate=8 June 2015\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071029231107/http://enquire.hertscc.gov.uk/landscsh/Areas/area70.htm |archivedate = 29 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Prehistoric archaeological finds ===\nArchaeological finds indicate [[prehistory|prehistoric]] activity in the Watton-at-Stone area before the village was established. The earliest finds are [[Paleolithic]] [[hand axe]]s found in the village and also at the Frogmore gravel pit, and there are traces of a [[Mesolithic]] site near the roundabout at the northern end of the bypass.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/> [[Neolithic]] pits were found off Station Road and several Neolithic or [[Bronze Age]] [[ring ditch]]es are evident in fields surrounding Watton.<ref name = \"Lockyear\"/><ref name=\"Village Guide\"/>\n\nTo the west of the village near Raffin Green is a significant late Bronze Age site and [[Iron Age]] enclosure in the Great Humphreys field.<ref name = \"Lockyear\"/> It was close to here that the Iron Age ''Aston Mirror'' was found, closer to Watton-at-Stone than to the village of [[Aston, Hertfordshire|Aston]], but technically in Aston parish due to the convoluted border. It is now kept at the [[British Museum]].<ref name=ehdc/> Another Iron Age enclosure was located by Broom Hall Farm, with an adjacent Roman farmstead and also a nearby Roman crematorium from which 27 burials were extracted.<ref name = \"Lockyear\"/><ref name=\"Village Guide\"/> A collection of possibly [[Belgae|Belgic]] armour and weaponry was discovered in the mid-19th century by workers digging a drain to the west of the village.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/>\n\n=== Roman and Anglo-Saxon origins  ===\nThe origins of Watton-at-Stone are from the construction of the Roman road, which crossed the High Street at the point of the modern [[milestone]]. Archaeological evidence suggests significant Roman activity at the roadside, with a probable Roman building near the Rectory<ref>{{cite web |url=https:www.hertfordshire.gov.uk/media-library/documents/environment-and-planning/planning/planning-applications-decisions/screening-opinions/a602-environmental-scoping-and-methodology-report-5.5.15.pdf |title=A602 Improvements |author=Hertfordshire County Council |date=5 May 2015 |website=hertfordshire.gov.uk |publisher=Hertfordshire County Council |access-date=25 January 2020 |quote=}}</ref> and Roman field boundaries off Station Road suggesting some permanent occupation.<ref name = \"Lockyear\">{{cite book |last=Lockyear |first=Kris |date=2015 |title=Archaeology In Hertfordshire - Recent Research |url= |location=Hatfield |publisher=Hertfordshire Publications |page= |isbn=978-1-909291-42-3 |author-link=}}</ref> Watton was possibly a market place trading to travellers as they slowed to cross the River Beane, and the High Street may have been a pre-existing track and therefore the new Roman road formed a crossroads here.<ref name = \"Village Guide\">{{cite book |author=Watton Conservation Society |date=2002 |title= Watton-at-Stone Village Guide|url=https://www.watton-pc.org.uk/files/web_guide_full.pdf |location=Watton-at-Stone |publisher=Watton-at-Stone Conservation Society |page= |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref>\n\n[[Anglo-Saxon]] settlers developed Watton further into a village, with evidence of early Anglo-Saxon field boundaries and a crematorium off Station Road.<ref name = \"Lockyear\"/> It is likely that the focus of the Anglo-Saxon settlement was on the high ground at Watton Green, overlooking the Roman road and river valley below.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/> There was a possible battle between the [[Danes (Germanic tribe)|Danes]] and [[Anglo-Saxons|Saxons]] which took place on a field named \"Danesfield\" to the west of the village, although the field name is the only evidence to suggest this. If a battle did occur here it would most likely to have been in 911<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/> with 1016 suggested as an alternative possible date.<ref name=\"herts_landscape\"/>\n\nThe Watton [[manor]] was anciently held by the Crown but by 1066 the Lord of Watton manor was Alwin Horne, an Anglo-Saxon [[thegn]] who owned other lands at [[Walkern]], [[Sacombe]] and [[Middlesex]].<ref name=\"Powell-Smith\">{{cite web |url=https://opendomesday.org/place/TL3018/watton/ |title=Open Domesday |last=Powell-Smith |first=Anna |date= |website= |access-date=23 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"herts_history\"/> Alwin Horne is believed to have fought at the [[Battle of Stamford Bridge]] under [[Harold Godwinson|King Harold]] in 1066 and later that year killed at the [[Battle of Hastings]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://englefieldhistory.net/owners.html/ |title=Englefield History |last=Smith |first=Richard J |date=2019 |website= |access-date=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Middle Ages and Early Modern period  ===\n[[File:Statue Of Henry FitzEylwin Holborn Viaduct.jpg|thumb|200px|Henry fitz Ailwin statue at Holborn Viaduct, London]]\nThe [[Domesday Book]] shows that the population of Watton village in 1086 was about 90, consisting of 18 households (10 villagers, 4 smallholders and 4 slaves). The manor was worth \u00a35 and it had a mill, woodland with 100 pigs and a meadow. It was jointly held by Derman (of London) and Alward (the noble),<ref name=\"Powell-Smith\"/> who were both [[moneyer|moneyers]] from London.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.academia.edu/37264685/Unequal_Partners_in_Government_Domesday_Moneyers/ |title=Unequal Partners in government? Domesday Moneyers |last=Roffe |first=David |date=2018 |website= |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>  There was an additional manor associated with Watton that had 6 households and a church, which could have been the Woodhall manor. The first mention by name of the Woodhall manor was in about 1130 when it was held by Ralph de Watton.<ref name=\"herts_history\"/>\n\nDerman's great nephew [[Henry fitz Ailwin]], the first Mayor of London, inherited the Watton manor in 1165. He built a hermitage chapel in what is now Chapel Wood and possibly built a new manor house in what is now Well Wood.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/> At about this time, perhaps as a consequence of Henry fitz Ailwin's new buildings, a new manor called Crowborough emerged from the Watton manor. Crowborough was first referenced in 1266 when it was held by Alice de Rivers.<ref name=\"herts_history\"/> Crowborough Hall stood at Watton Green and the moat which surrounded it can still be seen to this day.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/>\n\nHugh Bardolf inherited Watton manor in 1287, later it was held by [[John Bardolf, 3rd Baron Bardolf|John Bardolf]] and [[Thomas Bardolf, 5th Baron Bardolf|Thomas Bardolf]] with the Bardolf family owning the Watton and Crowborough manors at various times until 1562. During this period the house and chapel in Well Wood and Chapel Wood were abandoned, and so in circa 1520 the Watton manor was renamed Bardolf manor and the manor house moved to what is now Bardolphs Farm.<ref name=\"herts_history\"/> A new manor called Watkins Hall was created and was first known to be held by Thomas Munden in about 1540.<ref name=\"herts_history\"/>\n\nPhilip Boteler (Butler) inherited the Woodhall estate in about 1375 and later descendants to have the title included [[Philip Butler]] and [[John Boteler, 1st Baron Boteler of Brantfield|John Boteler]] who held the Watton, Woodhall and Crowborough manors. The three estates were in possession of the Botelers (Butlers) until as late as 1780.<ref name=\"herts_history\"/>\n\nIn 1662 brothers [[Maurice Thomson]] and [[William Thompson (1614-1681)|Sir William Thompson]], who had grown up in the village, founded Watton's first free school for 20 poor children.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/>\n\nAfter Woodhall was mostly destroyed by fire in 1771, from which an elderly John Boteler was able to escape, building of the new house began in 1775. The notorious [[Thomas Rumbold]] took possession of Woodhall in 1777, followed by [[Paul Benfield]] in 1793. The estate was then bought in 1801 by [[Samuel Smith (1754-1834)|Samuel Smith]] and the Smith family later combined the Watton, Woodhall and Crowborough manors into one and still holds it today.<ref name=\"Village Guide\"/>\n\nIn later years, the natural springs in the area once made the village a popular [[spa town]].<ref>name=\"herts_landscape\"</ref> The village has a number of dwellings dating from early [[Tudor architecture|Tudor]], such as ''Watton Place'', through to late [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]] constructions.<ref name=\"herts_history\"/>\n\n== Church of St Mary and St Andrew ==\nThe [[parish church]] is dedicated to St Andrew and St Mary. It stands on thirteenth century foundations and dates from the early-mid fifteenth century,<ref name=\"herts_history\"/><ref name=ehdc/> and is built in the [[Perpendicular Period#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular]] style.<ref>{{citation\n| first = Herbert H. | last = Tompkins\n| title = Hertfordshire, Second Edition\n| url = http://www.gutenberg.org/files/18252/18252-8.txt\n| year = 1922}}</ref>\nA chapel was added to the north side of the church in the late fifteenth century. The building is constructed from [[flint]], and is protected by a [[Grade II* listed|Grade II*]] heritage listing.<ref>http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/101341464-church-of-st-andrew-and-st-mary-watton-at-stone#.WdifD87m5sA</ref>\n\n== Famous residents ==\nThe evangelical author and social campaigner [[Edward Bickersteth (1786\u20131850)|Edward Bickersteth]] was rector of the church for twenty years from 1830 until his death in 1850.<ref>{{Citation|last=Hylson-Smith|first=Kenneth|title=Evangelicals in the Church of England, 1734\u20131984|publisher=Continuum International |date=1989|page=144|isbn=978-0-567-29161-5|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7iSULsFN_LgC&pg=PA144}}</ref><ref name=\"Larsen\">{{Citation|last=Larsen|first=David L.|title=The Company of the Preachers|publisher=Kregel Publications|date=1998|page=463|isbn=978-0-8254-3086-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gwMTCUs62TQC&pg=PA463}}</ref> His one-time [[curate]] was the theological scholar [[Thomas Rawson Birks|Thomas Birks]].<ref name=\"Larsen\" />\n\n[[Jack Meyer (educator and cricketer)|Jack Meyer]], the Somerset cricketer and founder of [[Millfield|Millfield School]] grew up in the old Georgian red-brick rectory overlooking the cricket field, his father was the vicar of the church.<ref>Ampthill and District News, January 1911, url=https://clophillhistory.mooncarrot.org.uk/AmpthillNewsJanuary1911.php</ref>\nIn the summer of 1923, [[Alan Turing]] and his family stayed with their friends the Meyer family for six weeks at the rectory, Alan being the founder of computer science and the leading cryptologist at Bletchley Park in World War II. Andrew Hodges in his biography: ''Alan Turing: The Enigma'' tells of how a gypsy fortune teller at the church f\u00eate foretold that he would be a genius.<ref>{{cite book|last= Hodges|first= Andrew|date= 1983|title= Alan Turing: The Enigma|url= https://archive.org/details/alanturing00andr|location= |publisher= Simon & Schuster|page= [https://archive.org/details/alanturing00andr/page/20 20]|isbn= 0671492071|author-link= Andrew Hodges|url-access= registration}}</ref>\n\nThe locomotive engineer [[Sir Nigel Gresley]] lived in Watton House until his death in 1941.<ref>{{citation\n| first = Oswald S. | last = Nock\n| title = The Locomotives of Sir Nigel Gresley\n| publisher = Longmans, Green and Co\n| year = 2007\n| page = 173}}</ref>\n\nWatton-at-Stone was the childhood home of the actor [[Rupert Grint]], well-known from his role of [[Ron Weasley]] in the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' film series]].<ref>\n{{citation\n| last = filmreference.com\n| title = Rupert Grint Biography\n| url = http://www.filmreference.com/film/26/Rupert-Grint.html\n| accessdate = 4 February 2008}}</ref>\nIt was also home to the boxing promoter [[Frank Warren (promoter)|Frank Warren]].\n\nFootballer [[Harry Toffolo]] grew up in the village.<ref>Hertfordshire Life, February 2015, url=https://www.hertfordshirelife.co.uk/people/bright-young-things-1-3959167</ref>\n\n== Alternative names ==\nThe name is also spelled unhyphenated as '''Watton at Stone''' and appears in this form on [[Ordnance Survey]] maps. The County Council favours the hyphenated version. Both spellings are equally valid.\n\nLocally, the '-at-Stone' suffix is frequently dropped.<ref>{{Citation|last=Tompkins|first=H.W.|title=Hertfordshire |publisher=BiblioBazaar|date=2008|pages=182\u2013183|isbn=978-1-4375-3234-0|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9bxP3iowDuAC&pg=PA182}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n* [http://watton-pc.org.uk Parish council website]\n* [http://www.wattonatstone.herts.sch.uk/ Village primary school website]\n* [http://www.heathmount.org Heath Mount school website]\n* [http://www.hertfordshire-genealogy.co.uk/links/watton.htm Watton-at-Stone (A Guide to Old Hertfordshire)]\n* [http://www.unc.edu/celtic/design/aston/aston.html The Aston mirror]\n* [http://www.wattonatstone.info/watton_web/wattonStart.html Image gallery]\n\n{{Civil parishes of Hertfordshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:East Hertfordshire District]]\n", "name_user": "Tony Marshall", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEtymology:Change of paragraph start", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Watton-at-Stone"}
{"title_page": "2004 Libertarian National Convention", "text_new": "{{Infobox National Political Convention\n| year = 2004\n| party = Libertarian\n| logo =\n| image = SI-MichaelBadnarik1.JPG\n| image2 = Richard Campagna Kareokee.png\n| image_size1 =\n| image_size2 = \n| caption = Nominees <br /> Badnarik and Campagna\n| date = May 28&ndash;31, 2004\n| venue = [[Atlanta Marriott Marquis|Marriott Marquis Hotel]]\n| city = [[Atlanta Georgia]]\n| presidential_nominee = [[Michael Badnarik]]\n| presidential_nominee_state = [[Texas]]\n| vice_presidential_nominee = [[Richard Campagna]]\n| vice_presidential_nominee_state = [[Iowa]]\n| othercandidates = [[Gary Nolan (radio host)|Gary Nolan]] of [[Ohio]]<br />[[Aaron Russo]] of [[California]]\n| previous_year = 2000\n| next_year = 2008\n}}\nThe '''2004 Libertarian National Convention''' was held from May 28 to May 31, 2004 at the [[Atlanta Marriott Marquis|Marriott Marquis Hotel]] <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lp.org/archives/lpnatconv2004.pdf |title=Libertarian National Convention Minutes, 2004 |access-date=2012-05-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511110412/http://www.lp.org/archives/lpnatconv2004.pdf |archive-date=2012-05-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. The delegates at the convention, on behalf of the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|U.S. Libertarian Party]], nominated [[Michael Badnarik]] for [[President of the United States|president]] and [[Richard Campagna]] for [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]] in the [[2004 United States presidential election|2004 presidential election]]. The convention was televised nationally on [[C-SPAN]].\n\nLibertarians hold a National Convention every two years to vote on party bylaws, platform and resolutions and elect national party officers and a judicial committee. Every four years it nominates presidential and vice presidential candidates.<ref>[http://www.lp.org/organization/bylaws.shtml Libertarian Party Bylaws] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605025750/http://www.lp.org/organization/bylaws.shtml |date=2008-06-05 }}</ref>\n\n==Speakers==\nThose which attended include:\n* [[Michael Badnarik]], activist\n* [[Gary Nolan (radio host)|Gary Nolan]], radio host\n* [[Aaron Russo]], businessman and filmmaker\n* [[Ron Paul]], former Libertarian Presidential candidate and current Republican Congressman\n* [[Neal Boortz]], national syndicated [[radio talk show]] host\n* [[James Bovard]], author of ''Terrorism and Tyranny''\n* anti-[[Brady Bill]] [[Sheriff]] [[Richard Mack]]\n* [[David Nolan (Libertarian Party)|David Nolan]], co-founder of the Libertarian Party\n* [[Michael Colley]], retired [[United States Navy]] [[Vice admiral (United States)|vice admiral]]\n* [[Dean Cameron]], actor\n* [[Jim Gray (jurist)|Jim Gray]], [[judge]] of the [[Superior Court of California|Superior Court]] of [[Orange County, California]], author\n* Dr. [[Mary Ruwart]], author\n* [[Ed Thompson]], nominee for [[Governor of Wisconsin|Governor]] of [[Wisconsin]] in [[2012 Wisconsin gubernatorial election|2012]]\n* [[Jimmie Vaughan]], musician\n\n==Voting for presidential nomination==\n===First ballot===\nAfter the first round, a motion was passed to suspend the rules and allow only the top three candidates from the first round to proceed to the second ballot.\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; text-align:center;\"\n|+ '''2004 Libertarian Party National Convention total vote count: Round 1'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| Candidate\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Total votes cast\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Percent of votes cast\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"\n| [[Aaron Russo]] ||bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| 258|| 33.16%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Gold\"\n| [[Michael Badnarik]] ||bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 256|| 32.90%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Yellow\"\n| [[Gary Nolan (radio host)|Gary Nolan]] ||bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 246|| 31.62%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFF66\"\n| [[None of the Above]] ||bgcolor=\"FFFF66\"| 10|| 1.29%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFCC\"\n| [[Jeffrey Diket]] ||bgcolor=\"#FFFFCC\"| 4|| 0.51%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"LightYellow\"\n| [[Drew Carey]] ||bgcolor=\"LightYellow\"| 3|| 0.39%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"White\"\n| [[Dave Hollist]] ||bgcolor=\"White\"| 1|| 0.13%\n|-\n|-bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n|\n|colspan=\"5\"|\n{| align=\"left\"\n|'''Color key:'''\n|\n|bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| 1st place\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 2nd place\n|bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 3rd place\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF66\"| 4th place\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFFCC\"| 5th place\n|bgcolor=\"LightYellow\"| 6th place\n|bgcolor=\"White\"| 7th place\n|}\n|-\n|-\n|}\n\n===Second ballot===\nAfter the second round, [[Gary Nolan (radio host)|Gary Nolan]], not receiving the necessary votes to advance, endorsed Michael Badnarik.\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; text-align:center;\"\n|+ '''2004 Libertarian Party National Convention total vote count: Round 2'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| Candidate\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Total votes cast\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Percent of votes cast\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"\n| [[Aaron Russo]] ||bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| 285|| 36.40%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Gold\"\n| [[Michael Badnarik]] ||bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 249|| 31.80%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Yellow\"\n| [[Gary Nolan (radio host)|Gary Nolan]] ||bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 244||31.16%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFF66\"\n| [[None of the Above]] ||bgcolor=\"#FFFF66\"| 5|| 0.64%\n|-\n|-bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n|\n|colspan=\"5\"|\n{| align=\"left\"\n|'''Color key:'''\n|\n|bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| 1st place\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 2nd place\n|bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 3rd place\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF66\"| 4th place\n|}\n|-\n|-\n|}\n\n===Third ballot===\nAfter the second round of voting, Gary Nolan addressed the convention, endorsing Michael Badnarik for the 2004 nomination of the Libertarian Party.\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; text-align:center;\"\n|+ '''2004 Libertarian Party National Convention total vote count: Round 3'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| Candidate\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Total votes cast\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Percent of votes cast\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"\n| '''[[Michael Badnarik]]''' ||bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| '''423'''|| '''54.37%'''\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Gold\"\n| [[Aaron Russo]] ||bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 344|| 44.22%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Yellow\"\n| [[None of the Above]] ||bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 11|| 1.41%\n|-\n|-bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n|\n|colspan=\"5\"|\n{| align=\"left\"\n|'''Color key:'''\n|\n|bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| '''1st place'''\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 2nd place\n|bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 3rd place\n|}\n|-\n|-\n|}\n\n==Voting for vice presidential nomination==\nA separate vote was held for the vice presidential nomination.  Per convention rules, nominee Michael Badnarik addressed the crowd, however he declined to declare his preferred running mate.\n\n===First ballot===\nRichard Campagna of Iowa was nominated as vice presidential candidate on the first ballot.\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; text-align:center;\"\n|+ '''2004 Libertarian Party National Convention total vote count: Round 1'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| Candidate\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Total votes cast\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Percent of votes cast\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"\n| '''[[Richard Campagna]]''' ||bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| '''353'''|| '''56.39%'''\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Gold\"\n| [[Tamara Millay]] ||bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 220|| 35.14%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Yellow\"\n| [[Garrett Hayes]] ||bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 36|| 5.75%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"White\"\n| [[None of the Above]] ||bgcolor=\"White\"| 10|| 1.60%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"White\"\n| [[Scott Jameson]] ||bgcolor=\"White\"| 7|| 1.12%\n|-\n|-bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n|\n|colspan=\"5\"|\n{| align=\"left\"\n|'''Color key:'''\n|\n|bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| '''1st place'''\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 2nd place\n|bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 3rd place\n|bgcolor=\"White\"| 4th place\n|bgcolor=\"White\"| 5th place\n|}\n|-\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Libertarian National Convention]]\n*Other parties' [[United States presidential nominating convention|presidential nominating conventions]] of 2004:\n**[[2004 Green National Convention|Green]]\n**[[2004 Democratic National Convention|Democratic]]\n**[[2004 Republican National Convention|Republican]]\n*[[Libertarian Party of Colorado]]\n*[[U.S. presidential election, 2004]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Libertarian Party (United States)}}\n{{2004 United States presidential election}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Libertarian Party (United States) National Conventions]]\n[[Category:2004 United States presidential election|Libertarian National Convention]]\n[[Category:2004 in Georgia (U.S. state)|Libertarian National Convention]]\n[[Category:2004 in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Political conventions in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:2004 conferences]]\n[[Category:May 2004 events in the United States|Libertarian National Convention]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox National Political Convention\n| year = 2004\n| party = Libertarian\n| logo =\n| image = SI-MichaelBadnarik1.JPG\n| image2 = Richard Campagna Kareokee.png\n| image_size1 =\n| image_size2 = \n| caption = Nominees <br /> Badnarik and Campagna\n| date = May 28&ndash;31, 2004\n| venue = [[Atlanta Marriott Marquis|Marriott Marquis Hotel]]\n| city = [[Atlanta Georgia]]\n| presidential_nominee = [[Michael Badnarik]]\n| presidential_nominee_state = [[Texas]]\n| vice_presidential_nominee = [[Richard Campagna]]\n| vice_presidential_nominee_state = [[Iowa]]\n| othercandidates = [[Gary Nolan (radio host)|Gary Nolan]] of [[Ohio]]<br />[[Aaron Russo]] of [[California]]\n| previous_year = 2000\n| next_year = 2008\n}}\nThe '''2004 Libertarian National Convention''' was held from May 28 to May 31, 2004 at the [[Atlanta Marriott Marquis|Marriott Marquis Hotel]] <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lp.org/archives/lpnatconv2004.pdf |title=Libertarian National Convention Minutes, 2004 |access-date=2012-05-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511110412/http://www.lp.org/archives/lpnatconv2004.pdf |archive-date=2012-05-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. The delegates at the convention, on behalf of the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|U.S. Libertarian Party]], nominated [[Michael Badnarik]] for [[President of the United States|president]] and [[Richard Campagna]] for [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]] in the [[2004 United States presidential election|2004 presidential election]]. The convention was televised nationally on [[C-SPAN]].\n\nLibertarians hold a National Convention every two years to vote on party bylaws, platform and resolutions and elect national party officers and a judicial committee. Every four years it nominates presidential and vice presidential candidates.<ref>[http://www.lp.org/organization/bylaws.shtml Libertarian Party Bylaws] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605025750/http://www.lp.org/organization/bylaws.shtml |date=2008-06-05 }}</ref>\n\n==Speakers==\nThose which attended include:\n* [[Michael Badnarik]], activist\n* [[Gary Nolan (radio host)|Gary Nolan]], radio host\n* [[Aaron Russo]], businessman and filmmaker\n* [[Ron Paul]], former Libertarian Presidential candidate and current Republican Congressman\n* [[Neal Boortz]], national syndicated [[radio talk show]] host\n* [[James Bovard]], author of ''Terrorism and Tyranny''\n* anti-[[Brady Bill]] [[Sheriff]] [[Richard Mack]]\n* [[David Nolan (Libertarian Party)|David Nolan]], co-founder of the Libertarian Party\n* [[Michael Colley]], retired [[United States Navy]] [[Vice admiral (United States)|vice admiral]]\n* [[Dean Cameron]], actor\n* [[James P. Gray]], [[judge]] of the [[Superior Court of California|Superior Court]] of [[Orange County, California]], author\n* Dr. [[Mary Ruwart]], author\n* [[Ed Thompson]], nominee for [[Governor of Wisconsin|Governor]] of [[Wisconsin]] in [[2012 Wisconsin gubernatorial election|2012]]\n* [[Jimmie Vaughan]], musician\n\n==Voting for presidential nomination==\n===First ballot===\nAfter the first round, a motion was passed to suspend the rules and allow only the top three candidates from the first round to proceed to the second ballot.\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; text-align:center;\"\n|+ '''2004 Libertarian Party National Convention total vote count: Round 1'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| Candidate\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Total votes cast\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Percent of votes cast\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"\n| [[Aaron Russo]] ||bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| 258|| 33.16%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Gold\"\n| [[Michael Badnarik]] ||bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 256|| 32.90%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Yellow\"\n| [[Gary Nolan (radio host)|Gary Nolan]] ||bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 246|| 31.62%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFF66\"\n| [[None of the Above]] ||bgcolor=\"FFFF66\"| 10|| 1.29%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFCC\"\n| [[Jeffrey Diket]] ||bgcolor=\"#FFFFCC\"| 4|| 0.51%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"LightYellow\"\n| [[Drew Carey]] ||bgcolor=\"LightYellow\"| 3|| 0.39%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"White\"\n| [[Dave Hollist]] ||bgcolor=\"White\"| 1|| 0.13%\n|-\n|-bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n|\n|colspan=\"5\"|\n{| align=\"left\"\n|'''Color key:'''\n|\n|bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| 1st place\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 2nd place\n|bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 3rd place\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF66\"| 4th place\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFFCC\"| 5th place\n|bgcolor=\"LightYellow\"| 6th place\n|bgcolor=\"White\"| 7th place\n|}\n|-\n|-\n|}\n\n===Second ballot===\nAfter the second round, [[Gary Nolan (radio host)|Gary Nolan]], not receiving the necessary votes to advance, endorsed Michael Badnarik.\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; text-align:center;\"\n|+ '''2004 Libertarian Party National Convention total vote count: Round 2'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| Candidate\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Total votes cast\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Percent of votes cast\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"\n| [[Aaron Russo]] ||bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| 285|| 36.40%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Gold\"\n| [[Michael Badnarik]] ||bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 249|| 31.80%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Yellow\"\n| [[Gary Nolan (radio host)|Gary Nolan]] ||bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 244||31.16%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFF66\"\n| [[None of the Above]] ||bgcolor=\"#FFFF66\"| 5|| 0.64%\n|-\n|-bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n|\n|colspan=\"5\"|\n{| align=\"left\"\n|'''Color key:'''\n|\n|bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| 1st place\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 2nd place\n|bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 3rd place\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF66\"| 4th place\n|}\n|-\n|-\n|}\n\n===Third ballot===\nAfter the second round of voting, Gary Nolan addressed the convention, endorsing Michael Badnarik for the 2004 nomination of the Libertarian Party.\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; text-align:center;\"\n|+ '''2004 Libertarian Party National Convention total vote count: Round 3'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| Candidate\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Total votes cast\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Percent of votes cast\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"\n| '''[[Michael Badnarik]]''' ||bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| '''423'''|| '''54.37%'''\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Gold\"\n| [[Aaron Russo]] ||bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 344|| 44.22%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Yellow\"\n| [[None of the Above]] ||bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 11|| 1.41%\n|-\n|-bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n|\n|colspan=\"5\"|\n{| align=\"left\"\n|'''Color key:'''\n|\n|bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| '''1st place'''\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 2nd place\n|bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 3rd place\n|}\n|-\n|-\n|}\n\n==Voting for vice presidential nomination==\nA separate vote was held for the vice presidential nomination.  Per convention rules, nominee Michael Badnarik addressed the crowd, however he declined to declare his preferred running mate.\n\n===First ballot===\nRichard Campagna of Iowa was nominated as vice presidential candidate on the first ballot.\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; text-align:center;\"\n|+ '''2004 Libertarian Party National Convention total vote count: Round 1'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| Candidate\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Total votes cast\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Percent of votes cast\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"\n| '''[[Richard Campagna]]''' ||bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| '''353'''|| '''56.39%'''\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Gold\"\n| [[Tamara Millay]] ||bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 220|| 35.14%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Yellow\"\n| [[Garrett Hayes]] ||bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 36|| 5.75%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"White\"\n| [[None of the Above]] ||bgcolor=\"White\"| 10|| 1.60%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"White\"\n| [[Scott Jameson]] ||bgcolor=\"White\"| 7|| 1.12%\n|-\n|-bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n|\n|colspan=\"5\"|\n{| align=\"left\"\n|'''Color key:'''\n|\n|bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| '''1st place'''\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 2nd place\n|bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 3rd place\n|bgcolor=\"White\"| 4th place\n|bgcolor=\"White\"| 5th place\n|}\n|-\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Libertarian National Convention]]\n*Other parties' [[United States presidential nominating convention|presidential nominating conventions]] of 2004:\n**[[2004 Green National Convention|Green]]\n**[[2004 Democratic National Convention|Democratic]]\n**[[2004 Republican National Convention|Republican]]\n*[[Libertarian Party of Colorado]]\n*[[U.S. presidential election, 2004]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Libertarian Party (United States)}}\n{{2004 United States presidential election}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Libertarian Party (United States) National Conventions]]\n[[Category:2004 United States presidential election|Libertarian National Convention]]\n[[Category:2004 in Georgia (U.S. state)|Libertarian National Convention]]\n[[Category:2004 in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Political conventions in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:2004 conferences]]\n[[Category:May 2004 events in the United States|Libertarian National Convention]]\n", "name_user": "Sal2100", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSpeakers:avoiding redirect", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2004_Libertarian_National_Convention"}
{"title_page": "Mushika-vamsha", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n'''''Mushika-vamsha''''' ([[IAST]]: M\u016b\u1e63ika-va\u1e43\u015ba mah\u0101-k\u0101vyam) is a [[Sanskrit]] dynastic chronicle composed in 11th century by poet [[Atula]].<ref name=\":3\">Thapar, Romila'', The Penguin History of Early India: From the Origins to AD 1300.'' Penguin Books, 2002. 394-95.</ref><ref name=\":2\">Narayanan, M. G. S. ''Perum\u0101\u1e37s of Kerala.'' Thrissur (Kerala): CosmoBooks, 2013. 178-179.</ref>  It narrates the legendary history of the [[Mushika dynasty]], which ruled the northern part of the present-day [[Kerala]] state of India.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> The chronicle moves from mythological beginnings of the founding ancestors to more authentic genealogical history in later ''sargas.<ref name=\":3\" />''\n\nSeveral kings mentioned in the kavya, such as Validhara Vikrama Rama (c. 929 AD)<ref name=\":6\">Narayanan, M. G. S. ''Perum\u0101\u1e37s of Kerala.'' Thrissur (Kerala): CosmoBooks, 2013. 180-181.</ref>,  Jayamani<ref name=\":18\">Narayanan, M. G. S. ''Perum\u0101\u1e37s of Kerala.'' Thrissur (Kerala): CosmoBooks, 2013. 480-81.</ref> and Kantan Karivarman (Srikantha Kartha) (both c. 1020 AD)<ref name=\":62\">Narayanan, M. G. S. ''Perum\u0101\u1e37s of Kerala.'' Thrissur (Kerala): CosmoBooks, 2013. 180-181.</ref> and [[Chera dynasty|Chera]] king [[Goda Ravi|Kota Ravi Vijayaraga]] (c. 883\u2013913 AD)<ref name=\":9\">Narayanan, M. G. S. ''Perum\u0101\u1e37s of Kerala.'' Thrissur (Kerala): CosmoBooks, 2013. 97-98.</ref> can be found in the medieval inscriptions discovered from north Kerala.\n\n== Date ==\n\n''Mushika-vamsha'' is believed to have been written during the reign of the Mushika ruler Shrikantha, who is assumed to be a contemporary of the 11th century [[Chola]] ruler [[Rajendra Chola I|Rajendra I]] (see [[#Historicity|Historicity]] below). If this belief is true, ''Mushika-vamsha'' is the earliest known historical Sanskrit ''[[mahakavya]]'', pre-dating [[Kalhana]]'s ''[[Rajatarangini]]'' by a few decades.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=vi}}\n\nIndologist [[A. K. Warder]] classifies Atula's style as ''[[Vidarbha|Vaidarbhi]]'', and believes that he was influenced by the 6th century poet [[Bharavi]], among others.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=52}}\n\n== Plot ==\n\n=== Origin of the dynasty ===\n\n{{Quote box |width=25em |align=right |salign = right\n|quote=<poem>\n...you should not take your own unhappy life,\nNor yet ought you to obstruct this offspring\nleft like this in you by your husband.\n</poem>\n|source = ''Mushika-vamsha'' introductory verse, describing how the royal preceptor dissuaded the queen from committing suicide{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=33}}\n}}\n\nAtula provides a mythological origin of the Mushika dynasty, tracing its descent to a [[Heheya Kingdom|Heheya]] queen, whose family was killed during [[Parashurama]]'s slaughter of the [[Kshatriya]] rulers.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xiii}} The pregnant queen initially wanted to commit suicide, but her family preceptor dissuaded her from doing so, encouraging her not to destroy her unborn baby.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|pp=1-2}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=33}} With the help of the preceptor, the queen fled southwards, and came to the coastal region that later became the Mushika kingdom.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xiii}} There, she was attacked by a huge rat (''mushika''), who was actually the divine spirit of the Eli mountain ([[Ezhimala Hill|Ezhimala]]), and had been cursed by the sage [[Kaushika]] to become a rat. The queen burned the rat to ashes with the flame emitted from her eyes: the rat was thus redeemed, and became transformed into its original form.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|pp=xiii-xiv}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=34}}\n\n=== Rama, the dynasty's founder ===\n\nAt the request of the divine spirit, the queen started living in a cave of the mountain, protected from Parashurama.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=34}} There, she gave birth to a boy, who received education from the preceptor. By the time the prince grew up, Parashurama had wiped the Kshatriyas from the earth 21 times. Feeling sorry for their widows, he decided to perform a ritual sacrifice to absolve himself from the sin of killing the Kshatriyas at the Eli mountain. For one of the sacrificial ceremonies, he needed a Kshatriya prince.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=34}} The divine spirit of the mountain brought to him the Heheya prince, who belonged to the [[lunar dynasty]].{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=35}} After the end of Parashurama's ceremony, the prince was crowned as a king, and thus, became the founder of the Mushika dynasty. Since Parashurama performed his consecration with the holy water from a ''ghata'' (earthen pot), the king came to be known as Rama-ghata-mushika.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xiv}}\n\nThe first six cantos deal with the exploits of Rama. He established a council of ministers, and his favourite minister was Mahanavika (\"great sailor\"), a member of the trading class (''Shreshti'') of [[Mahishmati]].{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xiv}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=35}} Rama also established the fortified city of Kolam, and the Mushika rulers came to be known as Kolabhupas.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xiv}} Once, he visited the hermitage of Parashurama, who gave him an invincible bow called ''Ajita'' and several divine missiles. Meanwhile, he received the news that his ancestral Heheya kingdom had been conquered by the [[Magadha]]s. Rama wanted to march against Magadha, but his ministers advised him to subjugated the southern kingdoms first.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xv}} After consolidating his rule in southern India, Rama crossed the [[Vindhyas|Vindhya mountain]], and asked the Magadha ruler Suvarman to hand over the former Heheya territory to him. When Suvarman refused, the two kings fought a battle in which Suvarman used divine missiles, but Rama could counter him without use of Parashurama's divine missiles. Ultimately, Rama defeated and killed him in a duel.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|pp=xv-xvi}} The vassals of Magadha accepted his suzerainty. He married Suvarman's daughter, and restored the Magadha territory to Suvarman's son.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xvi}}\n\nGradually, Rama conquered the entire [[Names of India|Bharata]] (India) and \"the islands\", and became a [[Chakravartin]] (universal emperor).{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=38}} He appointed his elder son Vatu as the ruler of the Heheya kingdom, and returned to Kola with his younger son Nandana.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xvi}} At Kola, he performed a [[ashvamedha|horse sacrifice]], and after a long time, [[sannyasa|retired to penance]], crowning Nandana as the new king of the Mushika kingdom.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xvi}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=38}}\n\n=== Nandana and his successors ===\n\n{{Quote box |width=30em |align=left |salign = left\n|quote=<poem>\nThe very skilful girl friend, having understood the emotion\nof the playful one whose mind was besieged by Love,\nOn the pretext of a spray she could pick with her own hand,\nled the beloved to a deserted creeper-house.\n</poem>\n|source = ''Mushika-vamsha'' 7.65, describing an incident during Nandana's stay with young women in a mountain forest{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=40}}\n}}\n\nThe Cantos 7-10 describe the \"amorous exploits\" of Nandana: the poet describes him as a mighty and glorious monarch, but does not describe his achievements as a king. Nandana was succeeded by Ugra; Canto 11 lists the names of the next 51 rulers (all patrilineal descendants).{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxi}}\n\nUgrasena, the sixth successor of Nandana, repulsed an invasion from the [[Kerala Kingdom]]. His successor Chitrasena was killed by a lion during a hunting expedition. The next ruler Shatasoma, described as a descendant of the [[solar dynasty]], performed a hundred [[ashvamedha|horse sacrifices]]. On the advice of sage [[Agastya]], he visited [[Mount Kailash|Kailasha]] and brought a sacred idol of the god [[Shiva]]. This idol was installed in a [[Rajarajeshwara Temple|newly-constructed shrine]] at Celera (also known as Cellura, [[Taliparamba]] or Lakshmipura).{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxiii}}\n\nShatasoma's descendant Sharmadatta obtained the boon of living as long as he wished from Shiva, for himself and his 20 descendants. His descendant Vatukavarman built the large [[Vadeshwaram Temple|Vatukeshvara Shiva temple]] at Alashuddhi. His successor Ahirana built the Ahiraneshvara Shiva temple on the western bank of the P\u1e5bthana river{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=42}} (identified as [[Valapattanam River|Valapattanam]]).{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxiii}} Ahirana's son Ranabhara was attracted some girls while chasing elephants in the [[Sahyadri|Sahya]] mountains. He followed them into a big cave, spent some days with a thousand cave girls, and then brought them to his kingdom using an [[elixir]]. After the birth of his son Aryagupta, he entered the cave once again, accompanied by many women.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=42}}{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxiv}}\t\n\nAryagupta's son Achala built the city of Achalapattana on the Eli mountain. His younger son Vikramasena ascended the throne after expelling the elder son Ashvasena from the kingdom. Vikramasena's son Vinayavarman ruled by ''[[dharma]]'', and the next ruler Rajavarman built a Buddhist monastery ([[vihara]]) called Rajavihara.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=43}}\n\nAshvasena's son Jayamanin I became the next ruler with the help of an army from the [[Pandya kingdom]]. Jayamanin's grandson Udayavarman patronized [[Brahmin]]s. The next ruler Virochana I killed a [[Pallava dynasty|Pallava]] king, and married his daughter Harini. Two of his descendants - Shashidatta and Janavrata - killed each other in order to seize the throne. Nothing is known about the last 38 kings mentioned in the Canto 11, except their names.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=43}}\n\n=== Kunchivarman and Ishanavarman ===\n{{Quote box |width=30em |align=right |salign = right\n|quote=<poem>\nWhere (in Kola) the totality of deities live together\nlike the species of animals of the forest who have found a place\nIn a hermitage of successful ascetics,\nperceived in the world as extremely contradictory.\n</poem>\n|source = ''Mushika-vamsha'' 12.112, describing the tolerance for different faiths in the Mushika kingdom{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=52}}\n}}\n\nCanto 12 begins with the reign of Kunchivarman, whose daughter married the ruler of the neighbouring [[Kerala Kingdom]].\n{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxiv}} His son Ishanavarman married Nandini, the daughter of a [[Chedi Kingdom|Chedi]] king who had been dethroned. Ishanavarman led an army to Chedi, and restored the throne to his father-in-law.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxv}} Upon his return to the Mushika kingdom, he faced an invasion from the [[Kerala Kingdom|Kerala]] king Jayaraga.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=44}} The warring kings decided to engage in a personal combat, but the Kerala prince Goda and Ishanavarman's nephew negotiated a peace treaty between the two kingdoms.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxvi}} Ishanavarman and Nandini did not have any children, so he married a [[Chola]] princess, with whom he had a son named Nrparama (or Nrpavarman).{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxvi}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=45}}\n\n=== Nandini's descendants ===\n\nAn upset Nandini prayed to the goddess [[Bhadrakali]] (or Chandika),{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=44}} and obtained a boon that the Mushika throne would be passed on to the sons of the female members of her family.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxvi}} (The manuscript is mutilated here, but it is clear that the Goddess says something about women: the editor theorized that the goddess talks about matrilineal descent, which is what effectively happens in the subsequent portions of the text.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=47}}) Sometime later, she gave birth to a son named Palaka, and a daughter named Nandini (II).{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxvi}} To avoid a war of succession between Nrparama and Palaka, Ishanavarman sent Palaka to the Chedi kingdom. Ishanavarman patronized scholars, and built several Shiva temples. Towards the end of his life, he suffered from a severe fever, and died after performing a ''[[sixteen great gifts|Mahadana]]'' (\"Great Donation\") ceremony.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxvii}}\n\nThe ministers then appointed Nrparama as the new king,{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=45}} whose infant son Chandravarman became the titular ruler after his death. Taking advantage of this situation, the Kerala king invaded the Mushika kingdom, whose ministers recalled Palaka from Chedi. Palaka repulsed the invasion, slaughtered the enemies on the battlefield, and became the king. He was succeeded by Validhara, the son of his sister.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxvii}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=46}}\n\nValidhara defended his kingdom against the [[Western Ganga dynasty|Ganga]] invaders, and was succeeded by his maternal nephews, first Ripurama, and then Vikramarama. Vikramarama build a huge wall of large rocks to prevent a Buddha (''Jina'') shrine from being swalloed by the [[Arabian Sea]].{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxviii}} (This temple remains unidentified, and was probably lost to the sea in the later years.){{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=47}} His successors were Janamani, Samghavarman (or Shankhavarman), Jayamani (Jayamanin II), and Valabha I.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxviii-xxix}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=44}}\n\n{{Quote box |width=35em |align=left |salign = left\n|quote=<poem>\nExcellent women emerged from the houses because of the threshing fire, \ntheir children hanging on to them in the danger;\nTheir very unsteady hands\nwaving to the dancing of their braids of hair.\n</poem>\n|source = ''Mushika-vamsha'' 13.34, describing the burning of Manapura by Gambhira's forces{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=48}}\n}}\n\nValabha I, described in Canto 13, was a powerful warrior king, who subjugated the chieftain of Bhatasthali, and made his relative Nrparama the in-charge of that territory. His younger brother and successor Kundavarman built the Narayananapura city and a [[Vishnu]] temple in that city. The next ruler Palaka was a son of a sister of Kundavarman. At the time of his death, Palaka did not have an adult younger brother or a maternal nephew. He was succeeded by Ripurama, a chieftain of Bhatasthali. After a glorious reign, Ripurama was succeeded by Gambhira, a son of Palaka's sister. Gambhira was a strong ruler, who crushed a revolt by the subordinate chief of Marupura, and burnt down that city.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxix}}\n\n=== Vallabha II ===\n\nJayamani (Jayamanin III), the successor and younger brother of Gambhira, became a renowned ruler. During the last years of his reign, he was assisted in administration by his nephew, the crown prince Valabha II.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxix}} Valabha II, said to be an [[avatar|incarnation]], partially that of [[Shiva]] and partially that of [[Vishnu]], made grants to the Vedic ''[[agrahara]]'' of Cellura. This ''agrahara'' is described as a hermitage with a variety of trees.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=48}}\n\nAt Cellura, there were two head [[brahmins|brahmanas]] (priests) named Bhava and Nandin, said to have descended from the heavens. They are compared to [[Shukra]] and [[Brihaspati]] (the teachers of the [[Asura]] and [[Deva (Hinduism)|Devas]] respectively, in Hindu mythology). Vallabha visited the \"cities\" (shrines) of [[Vishnu]] and [[Shiva]], the latter of which had been built by the earlier king Shatasoma, and paid obeisance to the deities. He commissioned repairs to these two temples, which had decayed with age, and gave benedictions to the brahmanas before leaving.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=49}}\n\nJayamani made Vallabha his [[heir apparent]], and then asked him to march to aid the [[Kerala Kingdom|Kerala]] king, who was preparing to attack the [[Chola]] king. Vallabha had to abandon the march midway, when a loyal subject told him that Jayamani had died, and an enemy named Ramavikrama had usurped the throne. Vallabha sent an envoy to the Kerala king, and then turned back towards the Mushika capital. On the way back, he visited the [[Sri Mulavasam|Mulavasa]] shrine, and paid obeisance to the [[Buddha]].{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=49}}\n\n{{Quote box |width=30em |align=right |salign = right\n|quote=<poem>\nHis belly rent by a sharp sword,\nthough fallen on the ground unconscious,\nThe enemy soldier slowly regained consciousness\nthrough the breeze from the wings of a bird violently dragging out his intestines\n</poem>\n|source = ''Mushika-vamsha'' 14.33, describing the battle between Vallabha and Ramavikrama{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=50}}\n}}\n\nVallabha's army defeated Ramavikrama's forces in a fierce battle.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=49}} Vallabha punished the surviving dissidents, and took control of the Mushika kingdom. The poet describes his coronation and construction activities in detail. Vallabha built the city of [[Madayi|Marahi]], an international commercial port, at the mouth of the [[Kuppam River|Killa]] river. He also built the [[Valapattanam|Vallabhapatnam]] fort, named after himself. He installed a statue of [[Shiva]] at the Vatukeshvara temple. His army crossed the ocean, and conquered many islands.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=50}}\n\n=== Shrikantha ===\n\nVallabha II was succeeded by his younger brother Shrikantha ([[IAST]]: \u015ar\u012bka\u1e47\u1e6dha) alias Rajavarman. He commissioned restoration of the Vatukeshvara, Kharavana, and Ahiraneshvara temples. He restored the wealth that the enemies had plundered from the temples, and paid obeisance to [[Shiva]]. The extant text breaks off after a description of the Shiva worship and rituals.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=51}}\n\n== Historicity ==\n\nThe poet Atula was primarily focused on eulogizing the dynasty's rulers, rather than on describing their reign based on the historical facts.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xviii}} The first six cantos, which are about the dynasty's founder Rama, describe an ideal ruler rather than a historical figure. There is no evidence that a ruler from present-day Kerala conquered Magadha or other regions of northern India.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xix}}\n\nAlthough the text's description of the dynasty's origin is purely legendary, some historians, such as [[M. G. S. Narayanan]], believe that it indicates northern origins of the dynasty. Narayanan theorizes that the Mushika family may have migrated from the [[Heheya Kingdom|Heheya]] kingdom of Cenral India to Kerala at the beginning of the [[Maurya Empire|Mauryan rule]].{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xvi-xvii}}\n\nNandana of Atula's text may be same as Nannan, a king described in the [[Tamil language|Tamil]] [[Sangam literature]], but this cannot be said with certainty. According to the Sangam literature, Nannan ruled Ezhilmalai (Eli mountain), and fought many battles against the neighbouring rulers. However, Atula does not credit Nandana with any military achievements.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=39}}\n\nIndologist [[A. K. Warder]] notes that the story of Shiva's boon (of living as long as they wished) to Sharmadatta and his 20 successors solves the chronological inconsistencies arising from dating the dynasty's origin to [[Parashurama]]'s time, by allowing as much as hundred years for the kings' lifespans. All of these kings appear to be imaginary.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=42}}\n\nCanto 12 onwards, the text describes rulers who can be identified as historical figures.\n{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxiv}} However, not all of the events described in this and subsequent cantos are historical. For example, Ishanavarman's purported march to Chedi is of doubtful historicity,{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxv}} although his conflict with the Kerala king seems to have some historical basis.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=44}}\n\nShrikantha is identified with king Kandan (Kantan) Karivarman mentioned in the [[Eramam]] inscription, which records the ''Samayasanketam'' ceremony conducted at the [[Chalappuram, Kozhikode|Chalappuram]] temple during Kandan's reign. The inscription also mentions ''Rajendra-chola Samayasenapati'' of Kadappappalli, who is identified as the 11th century [[Chola]] king [[Rajendra Chola I|Rajendra]].{{sfn|K. Maheswaran Nair|1972|p=49}} The ''Mushika-vamsha'' mentions that Shrikantha restored the temples that had been plundered by the enemies, and then ends abruptly after describing the worship rituals at the restored temples. It appears that the Chola king Rajendra successfully invaded Kerala around 1020, and Atula has omitted this fact to avoid spoiling his glorious description of Vallabha's reign. Shrikantha seems to have restored the temples in the aftermath of this first Chola invasion, as described in the Mushika-vamsha and the Eramam inscription. The Kerala kingdom subsequently rebelled against Rajendra's overlordship, leading to a second Chola invasion around 1028, in which both the Kerala king and Kandan were killed.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=51}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{ref begin}}\n* {{cite book |author=A. K. Warder |author-link=Anthony Kennedy Warder |title=Indian K\u0101vya Literature |volume=6: The Art of Storytelling |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fl0l5ZTkNxIC&pg=PA42 |year=1992 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-0615-3 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |editor=K. Maheswaran Nair |title=Epigraphia Malabarica |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IrABAAAAMAAJ |year=1972 |publisher=Kerala Historical Society |oclc=1695063 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |author=K. P. A. Menon |title=M\u016b\u1e63ikava\u1e43\u015bamah\u0101k\u0101vyam |series=Classical Sanskrit Literature of Kerala (Volume 8) |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Us1jAAAAMAAJ |year=1999 |publisher=Nag |isbn=978-81-7081-508-2 |ref=harv }}\n{{ref end}}\n\n[[Category:Epic poems in Sanskrit]]\n[[Category:11th-century Indian books]]\n[[Category:Works about monarchs]]\n[[Category:History of Kerala]]\n[[Category:History books about India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n'''''Mushika-vamsha''''' ([[IAST]]: M\u016b\u1e63ika-va\u1e43\u015ba mah\u0101-k\u0101vyam) is a [[Sanskrit]] dynastic chronicle composed in 11th century by poet [[Atula]].<ref name=\":3\">Thapar, Romila'', The Penguin History of Early India: From the Origins to AD 1300.'' Penguin Books, 2002. 394-95.</ref><ref name=\":2\">Narayanan, M. G. S. ''Perum\u0101\u1e37s of Kerala.'' Thrissur (Kerala): CosmoBooks, 2013. 178-179.</ref>  It narrates the legendary history of the [[Mushika dynasty]], which ruled the northern part of the present-day [[Kerala]] state of India.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> The chronicle moves from mythological beginnings of the founding ancestors to more authentic genealogical history in later ''sargas.<ref name=\":3\" />''\n\nSeveral kings mentioned in the kavya, such as Validhara Vikrama Rama (c. 929 AD)<ref name=\":6\">Narayanan, M. G. S. ''Perum\u0101\u1e37s of Kerala.'' Thrissur (Kerala): CosmoBooks, 2013. 180-181.</ref>,  Jayamani<ref name=\":18\">Narayanan, M. G. S. ''Perum\u0101\u1e37s of Kerala.'' Thrissur (Kerala): CosmoBooks, 2013. 480-81.</ref> and Kantan Karivarman (Srikantha Kartha) (both c. 1020 AD)<ref name=\":62\">Narayanan, M. G. S. ''Perum\u0101\u1e37s of Kerala.'' Thrissur (Kerala): CosmoBooks, 2013. 180-181.</ref> and [[Chera dynasty|Chera]] king [[Goda Ravi|Kota Ravi Vijayaraga]] (c. 883\u2013913 AD)<ref name=\":9\">Narayanan, M. G. S. ''Perum\u0101\u1e37s of Kerala.'' Thrissur (Kerala): CosmoBooks, 2013. 97-98.</ref> can be found in the medieval inscriptions discovered from north Kerala.\n\n== Date ==\n\n''Mushika-vamsha'' is believed to have been written during the reign of the Mushika ruler Shrikantha, who is assumed to be a contemporary of the 11th century [[Chola]] ruler [[Rajendra Chola I|Rajendra I]] (see [[#Historicity|Historicity]] below). If this belief is true, ''Mushika-vamsha'' is the earliest known historical Sanskrit ''[[mahakavya]]'', pre-dating [[Kalhana]]'s ''[[Rajatarangini]]'' by a few decades.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=vi}}\n\nIndologist [[A. K. Warder]] classifes Atula's style as ''[[Vidarbha|Vaidarbhi]]'', and believes that he was influenced by the 6th century poet [[Bharavi]], among others.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=52}}\n\n== Plot ==\n\n=== Origin of the dynasty ===\n\n{{Quote box |width=25em |align=right |salign = right\n|quote=<poem>\n...you should not take your own unhappy life,\nNor yet ought you to obstruct this offspring\nleft like this in you by your husband.\n</poem>\n|source = ''Mushika-vamsha'' introductory verse, describing how the royal preceptor dissuaded the queen from committing suicide{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=33}}\n}}\n\nAtula provides a mythological origin of the Mushika dynasty, tracing its descent to a [[Heheya Kingdom|Heheya]] queen, whose family was killed during [[Parashurama]]'s slaughter of the [[Kshatriya]] rulers.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xiii}} The pregnant queen initially wanted to commit suicide, but her family preceptor dissuaded her from doing so, encouraging her not to destroy her unborn baby.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|pp=1-2}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=33}} With the help of the preceptor, the queen fled southwards, and came to the coastal region that later became the Mushika kingdom.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xiii}} There, she was attacked by a huge rat (''mushika''), who was actually the divine spirit of the Eli mountain ([[Ezhimala Hill|Ezhimala]]), and had been cursed by the sage [[Kaushika]] to become a rat. The queen burned the rat to ashes with the flame emitted from her eyes: the rat was thus redeemed, and became transformed into its original form.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|pp=xiii-xiv}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=34}}\n\n=== Rama, the dynasty's founder ===\n\nAt the request of the divine spirit, the queen started living in a cave of the mountain, protected from Parashurama.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=34}} There, she gave birth to a boy, who received education from the preceptor. By the time the prince grew up, Parashurama had wiped the Kshatriyas from the earth 21 times. Feeling sorry for their widows, he decided to perform a ritual sacrifice to absolve himself from the sin of killing the Kshatriyas at the Eli mountain. For one of the sacrificial ceremonies, he needed a Kshatriya prince.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=34}} The divine spirit of the mountain brought to him the Heheya prince, who belonged to the [[lunar dynasty]].{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=35}} After the end of Parashurama's ceremony, the prince was crowned as a king, and thus, became the founder of the Mushika dynasty. Since Parashurama performed his consecration with the holy water from a ''ghata'' (earthen pot), the king came to be known as Rama-ghata-mushika.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xiv}}\n\nThe first six cantos deal with the exploits of Rama. He established a council of ministers, and his favourite minister was Mahanavika (\"great sailor\"), a member of the trading class (''Shreshti'') of [[Mahishmati]].{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xiv}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=35}} Rama also established the fortified city of Kolam, and the Mushika rulers came to be known as Kolabhupas.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xiv}} Once, he visited the hermitage of Parashurama, who gave him an invincible bow called ''Ajita'' and several divine missiles. Meanwhile, he received the news that his ancestral Heheya kingdom had been conquered by the [[Magadha]]s. Rama wanted to march against Magadha, but his ministers advised him to subjugated the southern kingdoms first.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xv}} After consolidating his rule in southern India, Rama crossed the [[Vindhyas|Vindhya mountain]], and asked the Magadha ruler Suvarman to hand over the former Heheya territory to him. When Suvarman refused, the two kings fought a battle in which Suvarman used divine missiles, but Rama could counter him without use of Parashurama's divine missiles. Ultimately, Rama defeated and killed him in a duel.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|pp=xv-xvi}} The vassals of Magadha accepted his suzerainty. He married Suvarman's daughter, and restored the Magadha territory to Suvarman's son.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xvi}}\n\nGradually, Rama conquered the entire [[Names of India|Bharata]] (India) and \"the islands\", and became a [[Chakravartin]] (universal emperor).{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=38}} He appointed his elder son Vatu as the ruler of the Heheya kingdom, and returned to Kola with his younger son Nandana.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xvi}} At Kola, he performed a [[ashvamedha|horse sacrifice]], and after a long time, [[sannyasa|retired to penance]], crowning Nandana as the new king of the Mushika kingdom.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xvi}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=38}}\n\n=== Nandana and his successors ===\n\n{{Quote box |width=30em |align=left |salign = left\n|quote=<poem>\nThe very skilful girl friend, having understood the emotion\nof the playful one whose mind was besieged by Love,\nOn the pretext of a spray she could pick with her own hand,\nled the beloved to a deserted creeper-house.\n</poem>\n|source = ''Mushika-vamsha'' 7.65, describing an incident during Nandana's stay with young women in a mountain forest{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=40}}\n}}\n\nThe Cantos 7-10 describe the \"amorous exploits\" of Nandana: the poet describes him as a mighty and glorious monarch, but does not describe his achievements as a king. Nandana was succeeded by Ugra; Canto 11 lists the names of the next 51 rulers (all patrilineal descendants).{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxi}}\n\nUgrasena, the sixth successor of Nandana, repulsed an invasion from the [[Kerala Kingdom]]. His successor Chitrasena was killed by a lion during a hunting expedition. The next ruler Shatasoma, described as a descendant of the [[solar dynasty]], performed a hundred [[ashvamedha|horse sacrifices]]. On the advice of sage [[Agastya]], he visited [[Mount Kailash|Kailasha]] and brought a sacred idol of the god [[Shiva]]. This idol was installed in a [[Rajarajeshwara Temple|newly-constructed shrine]] at Celera (also known as Cellura, [[Taliparamba]] or Lakshmipura).{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxiii}}\n\nShatasoma's descendant Sharmadatta obtained the boon of living as long as he wished from Shiva, for himself and his 20 descendants. His descendant Vatukavarman built the large [[Vadeshwaram Temple|Vatukeshvara Shiva temple]] at Alashuddhi. His successor Ahirana built the Ahiraneshvara Shiva temple on the western bank of the P\u1e5bthana river{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=42}} (identified as [[Valapattanam River|Valapattanam]]).{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxiii}} Ahirana's son Ranabhara was attracted some girls while chasing elephants in the [[Sahyadri|Sahya]] mountains. He followed them into a big cave, spent some days with a thousand cave girls, and then brought them to his kingdom using an [[elixir]]. After the birth of his son Aryagupta, he entered the cave once again, accompanied by many women.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=42}}{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxiv}}\t\n\nAryagupta's son Achala built the city of Achalapattana on the Eli mountain. His younger son Vikramasena ascended the throne after expelling the elder son Ashvasena from the kingdom. Vikramasena's son Vinayavarman ruled by ''[[dharma]]'', and the next ruler Rajavarman built a Buddhist monastery ([[vihara]]) called Rajavihara.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=43}}\n\nAshvasena's son Jayamanin I became the next ruler with the help of an army from the [[Pandya kingdom]]. Jayamanin's grandson Udayavarman patronized [[Brahmin]]s. The next ruler Virochana I killed a [[Pallava dynasty|Pallava]] king, and married his daughter Harini. Two of his descendants - Shashidatta and Janavrata - killed each other in order to seize the throne. Nothing is known about the last 38 kings mentioned in the Canto 11, except their names.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=43}}\n\n=== Kunchivarman and Ishanavarman ===\n{{Quote box |width=30em |align=right |salign = right\n|quote=<poem>\nWhere (in Kola) the totality of deities live together\nlike the species of animals of the forest who have found a place\nIn a hermitage of successful ascetics,\nperceived in the world as extremely contradictory.\n</poem>\n|source = ''Mushika-vamsha'' 12.112, describing the tolerance for different faiths in the Mushika kingdom{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=52}}\n}}\n\nCanto 12 begins with the reign of Kunchivarman, whose daughter married the ruler of the neighbouring [[Kerala Kingdom]].\n{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxiv}} His son Ishanavarman married Nandini, the daughter of a [[Chedi Kingdom|Chedi]] king who had been dethroned. Ishanavarman led an army to Chedi, and restored the throne to his father-in-law.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxv}} Upon his return to the Mushika kingdom, he faced an invasion from the [[Kerala Kingdom|Kerala]] king Jayaraga.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=44}} The warring kings decided to engage in a personal combat, but the Kerala prince Goda and Ishanavarman's nephew negotiated a peace treaty between the two kingdoms.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxvi}} Ishanavarman and Nandini did not have any children, so he married a [[Chola]] princess, with whom he had a son named Nrparama (or Nrpavarman).{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxvi}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=45}}\n\n=== Nandini's descendants ===\n\nAn upset Nandini prayed to the goddess [[Bhadrakali]] (or Chandika),{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=44}} and obtained a boon that the Mushika throne would be passed on to the sons of the female members of her family.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxvi}} (The manuscript is mutilated here, but it is clear that the Goddess says something about women: the editor theorized that the goddess talks about matrilineal descent, which is what effectively happens in the subsequent portions of the text.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=47}}) Sometime later, she gave birth to a son named Palaka, and a daughter named Nandini (II).{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxvi}} To avoid a war of succession between Nrparama and Palaka, Ishanavarman sent Palaka to the Chedi kingdom. Ishanavarman patronized scholars, and built several Shiva temples. Towards the end of his life, he suffered from a severe fever, and died after performing a ''[[sixteen great gifts|Mahadana]]'' (\"Great Donation\") ceremony.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxvii}}\n\nThe ministers then appointed Nrparama as the new king,{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=45}} whose infant son Chandravarman became the titular ruler after his death. Taking advantage of this situation, the Kerala king invaded the Mushika kingdom, whose ministers recalled Palaka from Chedi. Palaka repulsed the invasion, slaughtered the enemies on the battlefield, and became the king. He was succeeded by Validhara, the son of his sister.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxvii}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=46}}\n\nValidhara defended his kingdom against the [[Western Ganga dynasty|Ganga]] invaders, and was succeeded by his maternal nephews, first Ripurama, and then Vikramarama. Vikramarama build a huge wall of large rocks to prevent a Buddha (''Jina'') shrine from being swalloed by the [[Arabian Sea]].{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxviii}} (This temple remains unidentified, and was probably lost to the sea in the later years.){{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=47}} His successors were Janamani, Samghavarman (or Shankhavarman), Jayamani (Jayamanin II), and Valabha I.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxviii-xxix}}{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=44}}\n\n{{Quote box |width=35em |align=left |salign = left\n|quote=<poem>\nExcellent women emerged from the houses because of the threshing fire, \ntheir children hanging on to them in the danger;\nTheir very unsteady hands\nwaving to the dancing of their braids of hair.\n</poem>\n|source = ''Mushika-vamsha'' 13.34, describing the burning of Manapura by Gambhira's forces{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=48}}\n}}\n\nValabha I, described in Canto 13, was a powerful warrior king, who subjugated the chieftain of Bhatasthali, and made his relative Nrparama the in-charge of that territory. His younger brother and successor Kundavarman built the Narayananapura city and a [[Vishnu]] temple in that city. The next ruler Palaka was a son of a sister of Kundavarman. At the time of his death, Palaka did not have an adult younger brother or a maternal nephew. He was succeeded by Ripurama, a chieftain of Bhatasthali. After a glorious reign, Ripurama was succeeded by Gambhira, a son of Palaka's sister. Gambhira was a strong ruler, who crushed a revolt by the subordinate chief of Marupura, and burnt down that city.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxix}}\n\n=== Vallabha II ===\n\nJayamani (Jayamanin III), the successor and younger brother of Gambhira, became a renowned ruler. During the last years of his reign, he was assisted in administration by his nephew, the crown prince Valabha II.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxix}} Valabha II, said to be an [[avatar|incarnation]], partially that of [[Shiva]] and partially that of [[Vishnu]], made grants to the Vedic ''[[agrahara]]'' of Cellura. This ''agrahara'' is described as a hermitage with a variety of trees.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=48}}\n\nAt Cellura, there were two head [[brahmins|brahmanas]] (priests) named Bhava and Nandin, said to have descended from the heavens. They are compared to [[Shukra]] and [[Brihaspati]] (the teachers of the [[Asura]] and [[Deva (Hinduism)|Devas]] respectively, in Hindu mythology). Vallabha visited the \"cities\" (shrines) of [[Vishnu]] and [[Shiva]], the latter of which had been built by the earlier king Shatasoma, and paid obeisance to the deities. He commissioned repairs to these two temples, which had decayed with age, and gave benedictions to the brahmanas before leaving.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=49}}\n\nJayamani made Vallabha his [[heir apparent]], and then asked him to march to aid the [[Kerala Kingdom|Kerala]] king, who was preparing to attack the [[Chola]] king. Vallabha had to abandon the march midway, when a loyal subject told him that Jayamani had died, and an enemy named Ramavikrama had usurped the throne. Vallabha sent an envoy to the Kerala king, and then turned back towards the Mushika capital. On the way back, he visited the [[Sri Mulavasam|Mulavasa]] shrine, and paid obeisance to the [[Buddha]].{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=49}}\n\n{{Quote box |width=30em |align=right |salign = right\n|quote=<poem>\nHis belly rent by a sharp sword,\nthough fallen on the ground unconscious,\nThe enemy soldier slowly regained consciousness\nthrough the breeze from the wings of a bird violently dragging out his intestines\n</poem>\n|source = ''Mushika-vamsha'' 14.33, describing the battle between Vallabha and Ramavikrama{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=50}}\n}}\n\nVallabha's army defeated Ramavikrama's forces in a fierce battle.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=49}} Vallabha punished the surviving dissidents, and took control of the Mushika kingdom. The poet describes his coronation and construction activities in detail. Vallabha built the city of [[Madayi|Marahi]], an international commercial port, at the mouth of the [[Kuppam River|Killa]] river. He also built the [[Valapattanam|Vallabhapatnam]] fort, named after himself. He installed a statue of [[Shiva]] at the Vatukeshvara temple. His army crossed the ocean, and conquered many islands.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=50}}\n\n=== Shrikantha ===\n\nVallabha II was succeeded by his younger brother Shrikantha ([[IAST]]: \u015ar\u012bka\u1e47\u1e6dha) alias Rajavarman. He commissioned restoration of the Vatukeshvara, Kharavana, and Ahiraneshvara temples. He restored the wealth that the enemies had plundered from the temples, and paid obeisance to [[Shiva]]. The extant text breaks off after a description of the Shiva worship and rituals.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=51}}\n\n== Historicity ==\n\nThe poet Atula was primarily focused on eulogizing the dynasty's rulers, rather than on describing their reign based on the historical facts.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xviii}} The first six cantos, which are about the dynasty's founder Rama, describe an ideal ruler rather than a historical figure. There is no evidence that a ruler from present-day Kerala conquered Magadha or other regions of northern India.{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xix}}\n\nAlthough the text's description of the dynasty's origin is purely legendary, some historians, such as [[M. G. S. Narayanan]], believe that it indicates northern origins of the dynasty. Narayanan theorizes that the Mushika family may have migrated from the [[Heheya Kingdom|Heheya]] kingdom of Cenral India to Kerala at the beginning of the [[Maurya Empire|Mauryan rule]].{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xvi-xvii}}\n\nNandana of Atula's text may be same as Nannan, a king described in the [[Tamil language|Tamil]] [[Sangam literature]], but this cannot be said with certainty. According to the Sangam literature, Nannan ruled Ezhilmalai (Eli mountain), and fought many battles against the neighbouring rulers. However, Atula does not credit Nandana with any military achievements.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=39}}\n\nIndologist [[A. K. Warder]] notes that the story of Shiva's boon (of living as long as they wished) to Sharmadatta and his 20 successors solves the chronological inconsistencies arising from dating the dynasty's origin to [[Parashurama]]'s time, by allowing as much as hundred years for the kings' lifespans. All of these kings appear to be imaginary.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=42}}\n\nCanto 12 onwards, the text describes rulers who can be identified as historical figures.\n{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxiv}} However, not all of the events described in this and subsequent cantos are historical. For example, Ishanavarman's purported march to Chedi is of doubtful historicity,{{sfn|K. P. A. Menon|1999|p=xxv}} although his conflict with the Kerala king seems to have some historical basis.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=44}}\n\nShrikantha is identified with king Kandan (Kantan) Karivarman mentioned in the [[Eramam]] inscription, which records the ''Samayasanketam'' ceremony conducted at the [[Chalappuram, Kozhikode|Chalappuram]] temple during Kandan's reign. The inscription also mentions ''Rajendra-chola Samayasenapati'' of Kadappappalli, who is identified as the 11th century [[Chola]] king [[Rajendra Chola I|Rajendra]].{{sfn|K. Maheswaran Nair|1972|p=49}} The ''Mushika-vamsha'' mentions that Shrikantha restored the temples that had been plundered by the enemies, and then ends abruptly after describing the worship rituals at the restored temples. It appears that the Chola king Rajendra successfully invaded Kerala around 1020, and Atula has omitted this fact to avoid spoiling his glorious description of Vallabha's reign. Shrikantha seems to have restored the temples in the aftermath of this first Chola invasion, as described in the Mushika-vamsha and the Eramam inscription. The Kerala kingdom subsequently rebelled against Rajendra's overlordship, leading to a second Chola invasion around 1028, in which both the Kerala king and Kandan were killed.{{sfn|A. K. Warder|1992|p=51}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{ref begin}}\n* {{cite book |author=A. K. Warder |author-link=Anthony Kennedy Warder |title=Indian K\u0101vya Literature |volume=6: The Art of Storytelling |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fl0l5ZTkNxIC&pg=PA42 |year=1992 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-0615-3 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |editor=K. Maheswaran Nair |title=Epigraphia Malabarica |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IrABAAAAMAAJ |year=1972 |publisher=Kerala Historical Society |oclc=1695063 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |author=K. P. A. Menon |title=M\u016b\u1e63ikava\u1e43\u015bamah\u0101k\u0101vyam |series=Classical Sanskrit Literature of Kerala (Volume 8) |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Us1jAAAAMAAJ |year=1999 |publisher=Nag |isbn=978-81-7081-508-2 |ref=harv }}\n{{ref end}}\n\n[[Category:Epic poems in Sanskrit]]\n[[Category:11th-century Indian books]]\n[[Category:Works about monarchs]]\n[[Category:History of Kerala]]\n[[Category:History books about India]]\n", "name_user": "Woodlot", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mushika-vamsha"}
{"title_page": "Bailee Madison", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Bailee Madison\n| image              = Bailee Madison 2015 TV Critics Association Tour (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Madison in January 2015\n| birth_name         = <!--- Only include if different from article name --->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1999|10|15|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 2006\u2013present\n| relatives          = [[Kaitlin Vilasuso]] (sister)\n}}\n\n'''Bailee Madison''' (born October 15, 1999)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.no/detail/news-photo/bailee-madison-celebrates-her-13th-birthday-on-october-20-news-photo/154489850|title=Bailee Madison celebrates her 13th birthday on October 20, 2012 in...|website=Getty Images}}</ref> is an American actress. She first gained acclaim for her role as [[May Belle Aarons]] in the fantasy drama film ''[[Bridge to Terabithia (2007 film)|Bridge to Terabithia]]'' (2007). Madison received further recognition for her starring roles as Isabelle in the war drama film ''[[Brothers (2009 film)|Brothers]]'' (2009), Sally Hurst in the horror film ''[[Don't Be Afraid of the Dark (2010 film)|Don't Be Afraid of the Dark]]'' (2010), Maggie in the romantic comedy film ''[[Just Go with It]]'' (2011), Harper Simmons in the comedy film ''[[Parental Guidance (film)|Parental Guidance]]'' (2012), Clementine in the fantasy film ''[[Northpole (film)|Northpole]]'' (2014), and Kinsey in the slasher horror film ''[[The Strangers: Prey at Night]]'' (2018).\n\nOn television, she appeared as the super annoying [[Maxine Russo]] with her ugly face in the fantasy sitcom ''[[Wizards of Waverly Place]]'' (2011), young [[Snow White]] in the fantasy drama series ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]'' (2012\u201316), Hillary Harrison in the sitcom ''[[Trophy Wife (TV series)|Trophy Wife]]'' (2013\u201314), and Sophia Quinn in the drama series ''[[The Fosters (2013 TV series)|The Fosters]]'' (2014\u201316). From 2015 to 2019, Madison starred as Grace Russell in the [[Hallmark Channel]] comedy-drama series ''[[Good Witch (TV series)|Good Witch]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nMadison was born in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]],<ref name=\"issue\">{{Cite magazine | title = Bailee Madison | url = https://issuemagazine.com/bailee_madison/ | magazine = Issue Magazine | access-date = October 10, 2019 |quote=Where are you from? I was born in Fort Lauderdale, Florida! I grew up in a town called Lauderdale by the Sea, and I still go home whenever I can.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fortlauderdaledaily.com/features/fort-lauderdale-native-and-actress-bailee-madison-talks-us-about-growing-south-florida-her|title=Bailee Madison Talks To Us About Growing Up In South Florida, Her Career And More|website=Fort Lauderdale Daily|language=en|access-date=August 20, 2019}}</ref> the youngest of seven children. She has four brothers and two sisters. Her older sister, [[Kaitlin Riley]], is also an actress. Her mother is Patricia Riley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.childreninfilm.com/Fame-Success-Stories-Bailee.aspx |title=Children in Film |publisher=|date= |accessdate=March 12, 2014}}</ref> She began her career when she was two weeks old, appearing in an [[Office Depot]] commercial. Since then, she has appeared in several national commercials for major companies including [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]], [[SeaWorld]], and [[Cadillac]]. She also serves as a national youth spokesperson for the childhood-cancer charity [[Alex's Lemonade Stand|Alex's Lemonade Stand Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelguidemagblog.com/index.php/2011/12/09/bailee-madison-returns-to-the-hubs-haunting-hour-with-scarecrow/|author=Stacey Harrison|title=Bailee Madison returns to The Hub's \"Haunting Hour\" with \"Scarecrow\"|work=channelguidemag.com|accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z-o7nu1fTi0|author=I Am Second|title=I Am Second Bailee Madison \u2013 Child Actress|work=youtube.com|accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2006\u20132012: Early career and breakthrough===\nMadison made her major motion picture debut in the movie ''[[Lonely Hearts (2006 film)|Lonely Hearts]]'', in which she plays Rainelle, a girl thrown into the midst of a world of crime. Madison also has a significant role in the [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] movie ''[[Bridge to Terabithia (2007 film)|Bridge to Terabithia]]'', based on the children's book. She plays May Belle Aarons, the younger sister of the lead male character played by [[Josh Hutcherson]]. She also appears in the [[independent film]] ''[[Look (2007 film)|Look]]'' as Megan, a girl who is being watched and followed by a kidnapper.\n[[File:Bailee Madison.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Madison at the Faith and Values Awards Gala in 2008]]\n\nMadison had a small role in ''[[Terminator: The Sarah Connor Chronicles]]'' during the season 1 finale \"What He Beheld\" as a girl who becomes part of a short-lived hostage situation. In the DVD extras it is said that they thought about changing the role slightly because of its violent nature, but she insisted that they not. Madison appeared in [[Nickelodeon]]'s made-for-TV movie, ''[[The Last Day of Summer (2007 film)|The Last Day of Summer]]''. She plays a girl who helps a friend during a difficult time. Another Nickelodeon production she had a role in was the television Christmas special ''[[Merry Christmas, Drake & Josh]]''. She played a girl who lived with a foster family.\n\nMadison is seen in a featured supporting role in the 2009 film ''[[Brothers (2009 film)|Brothers]]'' as Isabelle Cahill, the older daughter of Captain Sam Cahill ([[Tobey Maguire]]) and Grace Cahill ([[Natalie Portman]]). For her portrayal in the movie, she was nominated for both a [[Saturn Award]] and a [[BFCA|BFCA Critics' Choice Award]]. In 2010, Madison was in the movie ''[[Letters to God]]'', where she portrayed Samantha Perryfield, best friend of the lead character who is fighting cancer.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nShe is seen in ''[[Conviction (2010 film)|Conviction]]'' playing the younger version of [[Hilary Swank|Hilary Swank's]] character, Betty Anne Waters. She can be seen in the episode \"Locum\" from ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' as Mackenzie Burton, a girl who was adopted and feels like she is only filling the place of her parents' older daughter who was abducted years ago. She appeared in three episodes of the children's horror series, ''[[R.L. Stine's The Haunting Hour]]''.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nIn 2011, Madison had a recurring role in the [[Disney Channel]] [[List of Disney Channel series|Original Series]] ''[[Wizards of Waverly Place]]'' as Maxine, the girl form of [[Max Russo]]. She also appeared in ''[[Just Go with It]]'', alongside [[Adam Sandler]] and [[Jennifer Aniston]], as Maggie Murphy, a young girl who wants to become an actress. Madison can be seen in the drama film, ''[[An Invisible Sign]]'' as the younger version of [[Jessica Alba|Jessica Alba's]] character Mona Gray. She starred in her first leading role in the [[horror film]], ''[[Don't Be Afraid of the Dark (2011 film)|Don't Be Afraid of the Dark]]'', alongside [[Katie Holmes]] and [[Guy Pearce]] where she portrayed Sally Hurst, a lonely withdrawn child who is sent to live with her father and his new girlfriend.\n\nIn 2012, Madison appeared in the [[Hallmark]] film ''A Taste of Romance'' alongside [[Teri Polo]] and [[James Patrick Stuart]]. She also had a guest role as the younger version of [[Ginnifer Goodwin]]'s character [[Snow White]] in the TV series ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]''. She also could be seen as the main character in the film ''[[Cowgirls n' Angels]]'' where she played the feisty and rebellious Ida Clayton who has fantasies of finding her father, a rodeo rider. Madison appeared in another Hallmark film entitled ''Smart Cookie'' as Daisy, an eager girl hoping to prove herself as a Girl Scout. In December, she appeared in the family comedy film ''[[Parental Guidance (film)|Parental Guidance]]'', alongside [[Billy Crystal]] and [[Bette Midler]].\n\n===2013\u2013present: Continued success===\n[[File:Bailee Madison 2012.jpg|thumb|upright|Madison at the Golden Globes Gift Lounge on January 14, 2012]]\nIn 2013, Madison began playing Hillary on the TV sitcom ''[[Trophy Wife (TV series)|Trophy Wife]]'', replacing Gianna LePera who played the character in the pilot.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bailee Madison Trophy Wife|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2013/09/09/trophy-wife-pilot-review|publisher=IGN|accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, she began playing the recurring role of Sophia Quinn in the [[ABC Family]] drama ''[[The Fosters (2013 TV series)|The Fosters]]''. In 2015, she began playing Grace Russell, the daughter of Cassie Nightingale, in the Hallmark series ''[[Good Witch (TV series)|Good Witch]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018Good Witch\u2019 Star Bailee Madison Teases Spellbinding Season 2|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/good-witch-star-bailee-madison-teases-season-2-drama-mysterious-newcomers-her-2354624|website=International Business Times|accessdate=October 8, 2016|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref> Madison continued in the role until the end of the fifth season in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2019/07/03/good-witch-bailee-madison-leaving-grace-season-6/|title=Good Witch Twist: Bailee Madison Exits Ahead of Just-Ordered Season 6|first1=Michael|last1=Ausiello|first2=Michael|last2=Ausiello|date=July 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, it was announced that Madison would star in an adaptation of Rachel Bateman's novel ''[[Someone Else's Summer]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Bailee Madison to Star in \u2018Someone Else\u2019s Summer\u2019 Movie Adaptation (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/bailee-madison-someone-elses-summer-movie-1202410698/|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Madison portrayed the role of Kinsey, a rebellious child in slasher horror film ''[[The Strangers: Prey at Night]].'' She starred alongside [[Christina Hendricks]] and [[Martin Henderson]], as her parents. The film received a mixed response from critics and was relatively successful at the box office.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2018/03/09/strangers-prey-night-review/|title=Review \u2013 Strangers: Prey at Night is Why Some Films Don't Need Sequels|date=March 9, 2018|work=Bleeding Cool News And Rumors|access-date=March 10, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/03/film-review-the-strangers-prey-at-night-is-a-quick-bloody-slasher-throwback/|title=Film Review: The Strangers: Prey at Night is a Quick, Bloody Slasher Throwback|date=March 8, 2018|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=March 10, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\nMadison has worked in [[voice-over|voice over]], with such projects as ''Breathe Bible''.<ref>[http://breathebible.com/voices/bailee-madison \"Bailee Madison, The Voice of Young Mary\"], BreatheBible.com; retrieved September 19, 2017.</ref>\n\nMadison has served as the national youth spokesperson for [[Alex's Lemonade Stand Foundation]] since 2010, an organization that encourages kids to fundraise and spread awareness of pediatric cancer by running their own lemonade stands.<ref name=\"foxnews\">[http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/06/12/young-actress-bailee-madison-sells-lemonade-for-charity-celebrates-girl-scouts \"Young actress Bailee Madison sells lemonade for charity, celebrates Girl Scouts 100th anniversary with new role\"], FoxNews.com, June 12, 2012.</ref> In January 2018, Madison's first novel was published, ''Losing Brave'', a [[Young adult fiction|Young-Adult]] Mystery which was co-written with Stefne Miller.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/34460488-losing-brave|title=Losing Brave|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref> Since November 2018, she has co-hosted the podcast ''Just Between Us'' with her sister [[Kaitlin Vilasuso]].<ref>{{cite web |title=PodcastOne: Just Between Us with Bailee Madison & Kaitlin Vilasuso |url=https://www.podcastone.com/just-between-us |publisher=[[PodcastOne]] |accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe dated YouTuber and model [[Alex Lange]] from September 2016 to December 2018.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-ug0KhxViGs</ref> Neither Lange nor Madison spoke about the break up, but AwesomenessTV put out a YouTube video to announce this.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_ZFczmN0_To</ref>\n\nSince around April 2019, she has been in a relationship with [[New Hope Club]] band member and lead singer Blake Richardson.<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B01LiqhnA3J/</ref> It is uncertain when exactly they started dating, however several [[Instagram]] posts from both, (the earliest ones in May<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/Bx7ZLI_jlbC/</ref> and June<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/ByS9KbGHRtg/</ref>) and the YouTube video on New Hope Club's channel filmed in April hints at their relationship.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D6hnqut2_VY</ref>\n\nMadison posts frequently about him on her Instagram stories, [[Twitter]] and main Instagram feed, generally in support of his work but also sharing sweet moments with him.<ref>https://www.instagram.com/baileemadison/</ref> <ref>https://twitter.com/BaileeMadison</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Lonely Hearts (2006 film)|Lonely Hearts]]'' || Rainelle Downing ||\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Bridge to Terabithia (2007 film)|Bridge to Terabithia]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://disney.go.com/disneyvideos/liveaction/bridgetoterabithia/ |title=Bridge to Terabithia official site |publisher=Disney.go.com |date= |accessdate=January 28, 2012}}</ref> || May Belle Aarons ||\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Look (2007 film)|Look]]'' || Megan ||\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Saving Sarah Cain]]'' || Hannah Cottrell ||\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[The Last Day of Summer (2007 film)|The Last Day of Summer]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nick.com/shows/specials/lastdayofsummer/ |title=The Last Day Of Summer official site |publisher=Nick.com |accessdate=January 28, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006092836/http://www.nick.com/shows/specials/lastdayofsummer/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012  }}</ref> || Maxine ||\n|-\n| 2007 || ''Judy's Got a Gun'' || Brenna Lemen || Television Movie \n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Phoebe in Wonderland]]'' || Olivia Lichten ||\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Merry Christmas, Drake & Josh]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nick.com/merry/ |title=Merry Christmas, Drake & Josh official site |publisher=Nick.com |date= |accessdate=January 28, 2012}}</ref> || Mary Alice Johansson || Television Movie\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Brothers (2009 film)|Brothers]]'' || Isabelle Cahill ||\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[An Invisible Sign]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.j2tv.com/invisible3.html |title=J2 Pictures / J2TV official web site |publisher=J2tv.com |date= |accessdate=January 28, 2012}}</ref>|| Young Mona Gray ||\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Conviction (2010 film)|Conviction]]'' || Young Betty Anne Waters ||\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Letters to God]]'' || Samantha Perryfield ||\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Don't Be Afraid of the Dark (2010 film)|Don't Be Afraid of the Dark]]'' || Sally Hurst ||\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Just Go With It]]'' || Maggie Murphy (Kiki Dee) ||\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[25 Hill]]'' || Kate Slater || Cameo\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Parental Guidance (film)|Parental Guidance]]'' || Harper Simmons ||\n|-\n| 2012 || ''Monica'' || Monica (voice) || Short film\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Cowgirls 'n Angels]]'' || Ida Clayton || <ref>{{cite news|url=https