e\n|32||1||0||0||1||0||11{{efn|name=UCL}}||0||colspan=2|\u2014||44||1\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Liverpool F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=sb1920>{{soccerbase season|49999|2019|accessdate=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|25||3||0||0||0||0||6{{efn|name=UCL}}||0||4{{efn|One appearance in [[FA Community Shield]], one appearance in [[UEFA Super Cup]], two appearances in [[FIFA Club World Cup]]|name=|group=}}||0||35||3\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!264||25||18||0||22||1||51||2||4||0||359||28\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!345||30||24||0||27||2||51||2||4||0||451||34\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|match played 14 October 2019}}<ref>{{NFT player |id=40555 |name=Henderson, Jordan |accessdate=14 October 2019}}<br />{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49929616 |title=Czech Republic 2\u20131 England |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=11 October 2019 |accessdate=11 October 2019}}<br />{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49955900 |title=Bulgaria 0\u20136 England |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=14 October 2019 |accessdate=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by national team and year\n|-\n!National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=9|[[England national football team|England]]\n|2010||1||0\n|-\n|2012||4||0\n|-\n|2013||2||0\n|-\n|2014||11||0\n|-\n|2015||4||0\n|-\n|2016||10||0\n|-\n|2017||4||0\n|-\n|2018||12||0\n|-\n|2019||7||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total||55||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Liverpool'''\n*[[Football League Cup]]: [[2011\u201312 Football League Cup|2011\u201312]];<ref name=2012LC/> runner-up: [[2015\u201316 Football League Cup|2015\u201316]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35624164 |title=Liverpool 1\u20131 Manchester City |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=28 February 2016 |accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Champions League]]: [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League|2018\u201319]];<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48368443 |title=Tottenham Hotspur 0\u20132 Liverpool |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=1 June 2019 |accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref> runner-up: [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League|2017\u201318]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44258022 |title=Real Madrid 3\u20131 Liverpool |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=26 May 2018 |accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[2019 UEFA Super Cup|2019]]<ref name=2019UEFASuperCup/>\n*[[FIFA Club World Cup]]: [[2019 FIFA Club World Cup|2019]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50869633 |title=Liverpool 1\u20130 Flamengo |first=Harry |last=Poole |website=BBC Sport |date=21 December 2019 |accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref>\n*[[FA Cup]] runner-up: [[2011\u201312 FA Cup|2011\u201312]]<ref name=2012FAC/>\n*[[UEFA Europa League]] runner-up: [[2015\u201316 UEFA Europa League|2015\u201316]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36254631 |title=Liverpool 1\u20133 Sevilla |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=18 May 2016 |accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''England'''\n*[[UEFA Nations League]] third place: [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48191915 |title=Switzerland 0\u20130 England |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=9 June 2019 |accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[Premier League Goal of the Month]]: [[2016\u201317 Premier League#Monthly awards|September 2016]]<ref name=goalofmonth/>\n*[[England Player of the Year#England Men's U21 Player of the Year|England U21 Player of the Year Award]]: [[The FA England Awards|2012]]<ref name=u21p/>\n*[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool Young Player of the Year Award]]: [[2011\u201312 Liverpool F.C. season|2011\u201312]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carson |first1=Liam |title=Jordan Henderson: Future England Captain? |url=http://www.sport.co.uk/football/jordan-henderson-future-england-captain/3684362/#dFhc1jvQiHMKpK2g.97 |website=sport.co.uk |accessdate=12 April 2015 |date=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] Young Player of the Year Award: [[2009\u201310 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2009\u201310]],<ref name=poy10/> [[2010\u201311 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2010\u201311]]<ref name=poy11/>\n*[[UEFA Club Football Awards|UEFA Midfielder of the Season]] third place: 2018\u201319<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/amp/newsid=2618590.html |title=UEFA Champions League Midfielder of the Season 2018/19 |date=29 August 2019 |publisher=UEFA |accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n*[[The FA England Awards#Senior Men's Player of the Year|England Senior Men's Player of the Year]]: 2019<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2020/jan/14/england-2019-players-of-the-year-revealed-140120 |title=The Votes Have Been Counted and Winners Named For The 2019 BT England POTY Awards |date=14 January 2020 |publisher=The FA |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.liverpoolfc.com/team/first-team/player/jordan-henderson Profile] at the Liverpool F.C. website\n*[http://www.thefa.com/england/mens-seniors/squad/jordan-henderson Profile] at the Football Association website\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Liverpool F.C. squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = England squads\n| bg = white\n| fg = #2B0B3F\n| bordercolor = #0B0B3F\n| list1 = \n{{England squad UEFA Euro 2012}}\n{{England squad 2014 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{England squad UEFA Euro 2016}}\n{{England squad 2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{England Player of the Year}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henderson, Jordan}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sunderland, Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Coventry City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:England under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2012 players]]\n[[Category:2014 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2016 players]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup players]]\n", "name_user": "Kosack", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClub captain and European success:Condense", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jordan_Henderson"}
{"title_page": "French horn", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=January 2010}}\n{{Infobox instrument\n|name=French horn\n|names=Horn<br />[[German language|de:]]&nbsp;''Horn, Waldhorn, Ventilhorn''<br />[[Spanish language|es:]]&nbsp;''trompa'' or ''corno''<br />[[French language|fr:]]&nbsp;''cor (d'harmonie)''<br />[[Italian language|it:]]&nbsp;''corno''\n|image=French horn front.png\n|image_capt=French (German double) horn\n|background=brass\n|classification=[[Aerophone]]<br />[[Wind instrument|Wind]]<br />[[Brass instrument|Brass]]\n|hornbostel_sachs=423.232\n|hornbostel_sachs_desc=Valved aerophone sounded by lip movement\n|range=[[File:Range_of_horn.png|200px|center]]in F: sounds a [[perfect fifth]] lower than written. Nonetheless, in older music, bass-clef notes are written one octave lower (thus sounding a [[perfect fourth]] higher than written).<ref name=\"Walter\">{{Cite book |title=Orchestration |last=Piston |first= Walter |date=1955 |publisher=Norton |isbn=978-0393097405 |edition=1st |location=New York |oclc=300471}}</ref>\n|related=* [[Tenor horn|Tenor horn (alto horn)]]\n* [[Baritone horn]]\n* [[German horn]]\n* [[Mellophone]]\n* [[Natural horn]]\n* [[Post horn]]\n* [[Saxhorn]]\n* [[Vienna horn]]\n* [[Wagner tuba]]\n|musicians=* [[List of horn players]]\n|builders=*[[List of horn makers]]\n|midi=060/061 (French Horn)\n|articles=* [[List of horn techniques]]\n* [[List of compositions for horn]]\n}}\n{{Brass}}\nThe '''French horn''' (since the 1930s known simply as the \"horn\" in professional music circles) is a [[brass instrument]] commonly referred to as a big round swirly thingy that you sometimes put your hand in, made of tubing wrapped into a coil with a flared bell. The '''double horn in F/B{{music|flat}}''' (technically a variety of [[German horn]]) is the horn most often used by players in professional orchestras and bands. A musician who plays a horn is known as a [[list of horn players|horn player]] or hornist.\n\nPitch is controlled through the combination of the following factors: speed of air through the instrument (controlled by the player's lungs and [[thoracic diaphragm]]); diameter and tension of lip aperture (by the player's lip muscles\u2014the [[embouchure]]) in the mouthpiece; plus, in a modern horn, the operation of [[Brass instrument valve|valves]] by the left hand, which route the air into extra sections of tubing. Most horns have lever-operated [[rotary valve]]s, but some, especially older horns, use [[piston valve]]s (similar to a [[trumpet]]'s) and the [[Vienna horn]] uses double-piston valves, or [[Brass instrument valve#Double-piston valve|pumpenvalves]]. The backward-facing orientation of the bell relates to the perceived desirability to create a subdued sound in concert situations, in contrast to the more piercing quality of the trumpet.  A horn without valves is known as a natural horn, changing pitch along the natural [[harmonics]] of the instrument (similar to a [[bugle (instrument)|bugle]]). Pitch may also be controlled by the position of the hand in the bell, in effect reducing the bell's diameter. The pitch of any note can easily be raised or lowered by adjusting the hand position in the bell.<ref name=\"Whitener\">{{Cite book |title=A complete guide to brass : instruments and pedagogy |last=Whitener |first=Scott and Cathy L. |publisher=Schirmer Books |year=1990 |isbn=978-0028728612 |location=New York |pages=40, 44 |oclc=19128016}}</ref> The key of a natural horn can be changed by adding different crooks of different lengths.\n\nThree valves control the flow of air in the ''single horn'', which is tuned to F or less commonly B{{music|flat}}. The more common ''double horn'' has a fourth, trigger valve, usually operated by the thumb, which routes the air to one set of tubing tuned to F or another tuned to B{{music|flat}} which expands the horn range to over four [[octaves]] and blends with flutes or [[clarinet]]s in a [[woodwind ensemble]]. Triple horns with five valves are also made, usually tuned in F, B{{music|flat}}, and a [[descant]] E{{music|flat}} or F. There are also double horns with five valves tuned in B{{music|flat}}, descant E{{music|flat}} or F, and a stopping valve, which greatly simplifies the complicated and difficult hand-stopping technique,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://poperepair.com/alexander-107-descant-w-stopping-valve-7800 |title=Alexander 107 Descant w/Stopping Valve - $7800 |last=Pope |first=Ken |website=Pope Instrument Repair |language=en |access-date=2018-02-22}}</ref> though these are rarer. Also common are ''descant'' doubles, which typically provide B{{music|flat}} and alto F branches.\n\nA crucial element in playing the horn deals with the mouthpiece. Most of the time, the mouthpiece is placed in the exact center of the lips, but, because of differences in the formation of the lips and teeth of different players, some tend to play with the mouthpiece slightly off center.<ref name=\"AOFHP\">{{Cite book |title=The art of French horn playing : a treatise on the problems and techniques of French Horn playing \u2026 |last=Farkas |first=Philip |date=1956 |publisher=Summy-Birchard  |isbn=978-0874870213 |location=Evanston, Il. |pages=6, 21, 65 |oclc=5587694}}</ref> Although the exact side-to-side placement of the mouthpiece varies for most horn players, the up-and-down placement of the mouthpiece is generally two-thirds on the upper lip and one-third on the lower lip.<ref name=\"AOFHP\" /> When playing higher notes, the majority of players exert a small degree of additional pressure on the lips using the mouthpiece. However, this is undesirable from the perspective of both endurance and tone: excessive mouthpiece pressure makes the horn sound forced and harsh, and decreases player's stamina due to the resulting constricted flow of blood to the lips and lip muscles.<ref name=\"AOFHP\" />\n\n==Name==\nThe name \"French horn\" is found only in English, first coming into use in the late 17th century.  At that time, French makers were preeminent in the manufacture of hunting horns, and were credited with creating the now-familiar, circular \"hoop\" shape of the instrument. As a result, these instruments were often called, even in English, by their French names: ''trompe de chasse'' or ''cor de chasse'' (the clear modern distinction between ''trompes'', trumpets, and ''cors'', horns, did not exist at that time).<ref name=\"Beakes\" />\n\nGerman makers first devised ''crooks'' to make such horns playable in different keys\u2014so musicians came to use \"French\" and \"German\" to distinguish the simple hunting horn from the newer horn with crooks, which in England was also called by the Italian name ''corno cromatico'' (chromatic horn).<ref name=\"Beakes\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=zpOAnQEACAAJ |title=The Horn Parts in Handel's Operas and Oratorios and the Horn Players who Performed in These Works |last=Beakes |first=Jennifer |date=2007 |publisher=City University of New York |pages=50, 116\u201318, 176, 223\u201325, 439\u201340, 444\u201345 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nMore recently, \"French horn\" is often used colloquially, though the adjective has normally been avoided when referring to the European orchestral horn, ever since the German horn began replacing the French-style instrument in British orchestras around 1930.<ref name=\"Del Mar\">{{Cite book |title=Anatomy of the orchestra |last=Del Mar |first= Norman |date=1983 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0520045002 |edition=2nd print., with revisions |location=Berkeley |pages=215 |oclc=10561390}}</ref> The [[International Horn Society]] has recommended since 1971 that the instrument be simply called the ''horn''.<ref name=\"Meek1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hornsociety.org/home/ihs-news/26-people/honorary/61-harold-meek-1914-1998 |title=Harold Meek (1914\u20131998) |last=Meek |first=Harold |website=International Horn Society |access-date=2018-09-04 |quote=Harold Meek is described by everyone as a gentleman, a perfectionist, and one who loved the horn. He was the first editor of ''The Horn Call'' and was responsible for this statement in every issue, 'The International Horn Society recommends that HORN be recognized as the correct name for our instrument in the English language.'}}</ref><ref name=\"Meek2\">{{Cite journal |last=Meek |first=Harold |date=February 1971 |title=The Horn! |journal=The Horn Call |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201320 |quote=Meek strongly advocates using the term 'horn' rather than 'French horn.'}}</ref>\n\nThere is also a more specific use of \"French horn\" to describe a particular horn type, differentiated from the [[German horn]] and [[Vienna horn]]. In this sense, \"French horn\" refers to a narrow-bore instrument ({{cvt|10.8|-|11.0|mm|in|disp=sqbr}}) with three P\u00e9rinet (piston) valves. It retains the narrow bell-throat and mouthpipe crooks of the orchestral hand horn of the late 18th century, and most often has an \"ascending\" third valve. This is a whole-tone valve arranged so that with the valve in the \"up\" position the valve loop is engaged, but when the valve is pressed the loop is cut out, raising the pitch by a whole tone.<ref name=\"Baines\">{{Cite book |title=Brass instruments : their history and development |last=Baines |first=Anthony |date=1976 |publisher=Scribner |isbn=978-0684152295 |location=New York |pages=221\u201323 |oclc=3795926}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|Horn (instrument)}}\n[[File:French-horn.png|left|thumb|250px|Horn with three [[piston valve|Perinet valves]]]]\n[[File:How to shout and blow Horns Fac simile of a Miniature in the Manuscript of Phoebus Fifteenth Century.png|thumb|right|\"How to shout and blow horns.\"\u2014Facsimile of a miniature in a manuscript of the hunting manual of [[Gaston III of Foix-B\u00e9arn|Gaston Phoebus]] (15th century)]]\n\nAs the name indicates, humans originally used to blow on the actual [[Horn (anatomy)|horn]]s of animals before starting to emulate them in metal. This original usage survives in the [[shofar]], a ram's horn, which plays an important role in [[Judaism|Jewish religious rituals]].\n\nEarly metal horns were less complex than modern horns, consisting of brass tubes with a slightly flared opening (the bell) wound around a few times. These early \"hunting\" horns were originally played on a hunt, often while mounted, and the sound they produced was called a recheat. Change of pitch was controlled entirely by the lips (the horn not being equipped with valves until the 19th century). Without valves, only the notes within the [[harmonic series (music)|harmonic series]] are available.  By combining a long length with a narrow bore, the French horn's design allows the player to easily reach the higher overtones which differ by whole tones or less, thus making it capable of playing melodies before valves were invented.<ref name=\"AOFHP\" />\n\nEarly horns were commonly pitched in B{{music|flat}} alto, A, A{{music|flat}}, G, F, E, E{{music|flat}}, D, C, and B{{music|flat}} basso. Since the only notes available were those on the harmonic series of one of those pitches, they had no ability to play in different keys. The remedy for this limitation was the use of [[Crook (music)|crooks]], i.e., sections of tubing of differing length that, when inserted, altered the length of the instrument, and thus its pitch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://omeka1.grinnell.edu/MusicalInstruments/items/show/193|title=Grinell College Musical|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-18th century, horn players began to insert the right hand into the bell to change the length of the instrument, adjusting the tuning up to the distance between two adjacent harmonics depending on how much of the opening was covered.\n\nIn 1818 the German makers [[Heinrich St\u00f6lzel]] and Friedrich Bl\u00fcmel patented the first valved horn, using rotary valves. Piston valves were introduced in France about 1839 by Fran\u00e7ois P\u00e9rinet.<ref name=\"Meek3\">{{Cite book |title=Horn and conductor : reminiscences of a practitioner with a few words of advice |last=Meek |first=Harold L. |date=1997 |publisher=University of Rochester Press |isbn=978-1878822833 |location=Rochester, NY |pages=33 |oclc=35636932}}</ref> Valves were initially intended to overcome problems associated with changing crooks during a performance. Valves' unreliability, musical taste, and players' distrust, among other reasons, slowed their adoption into mainstream. Many traditional conservatories and players refused to use them at first, claiming that the valveless horn, or ''natural horn'', was a better instrument. Some musicians who specialize in period instruments use a natural horn to play in original performance styles, to try to recapture the sound of an older piece's original performances.<ref>See, e.g., the performance of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]'s ''[[Mass in B Minor]]'' as performed by the [[Proms]] of London in the movement from 45:40 onward in {{cite web\n|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7F7TVM8m95Y\n|title = Mass in B Minor\n|magazine = You Tube\n|date = 2012\n|accessdate = 2013-11-29\n}}</ref>\n\nThe use of [[brass instrument valve|valves]], however, opened up a great deal more flexibility in playing in different keys; in effect, the horn became an entirely different instrument, fully chromatic for the first time. Valves were originally used primarily as a means to play in different keys without crooks, not for harmonic playing. That is reflected in compositions for horns, which only began to include chromatic passages in the late 19th century.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018|Speculation=The extremely high horn playing from the baroque and early classical periods would allow the horn to play almost completely chromatically due to the tiny differences in harmonics. This may have caused the name to develop as nobody was to know then that true chromaticism would happen in the next century. Examples include anything in a high register from that period, e.g. the horn solo from Bach's B-Minor Mass}}<!--If this is true, then what was the \"corno chromatico\" of the late 18th century, and why was it so called?-->  When valves were invented, generally, the French made smaller horns with piston valves and the Germans made larger horns with rotary valves.{{Clarify|reason=German brass players had (and many still have) a preference towards rotary valves. This is commonly seen as a holdover today as a huge amount of German and Austrian orchestras use rotary trumpets, while the majority of the rest of the world use piston trumpets. An example is seen at the very start of this performance by the Berlin Philharmonic https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bwQumQpug_E|date=February 2018}}<!--What, like horns in F, as opposed to horns in B-flat basso or alto?-->\n\n==Types==\nHorns may be classified in single horn, double horn, compensating double horn, and triple horn as well as the versatility of detachable bells.\n[[File:Yamaha Horn YHR-314II.tif|thumb|250px|right|Single horn in F, student model.]]\n\n===Single horn===\nSingle horns use a single set of tubes connected to the valves. This allows for simplicity of use and a much lighter weight. They are usually in the keys of F or B{{music|flat}}, although many F horns have longer slides to tune them to E{{music|flat}}, and almost all B{{music|flat}} horns have a valve to put them in the key of A. The problem with single horns is the inevitable choice between accuracy or tone \u2013 while the F horn has the \"typical\" horn sound, above third-space C accuracy is a concern for the majority of players because, by its nature, one plays high in the horn's harmonic series where the overtones are closer together. This led to the development of the B{{music|flat}} horn, which, although easier to play accurately, has a less desirable sound in the mid and especially the low register where it is not able to play all of the notes.  The solution has been the development of the double horn, which combines the two into one horn with a single lead pipe and bell.  Both main types of single horns are still used today as student models because they are cheaper and lighter than double horns.  In addition, the single B{{music|flat}} horns are sometimes used in solo and chamber performances and the single F survives orchestrally as the Vienna horn. Additionally, single F alto and B{{music|flat}} alto descants are used in the performance of some baroque horn concertos and F, B{{music|flat}} and F alto singles are occasionally used by [[jazz]] performers.\n\n[[Dennis Brain]]'s benchmark recordings of the Mozart Horn Concerti were made on a single B{{music|flat}} instrument by [[Gebr. Alexander]], now on display at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in London.\n\n===Double horn===\n[[File:French horn detail.jpg|frame|right|The [[rotary valve|valves]] of a [[Conn-Selmer|Conn]] 6D double horn. The three lever keys (above the large valves) can be depressed toward the large outer tube. The thumb key (''near the left-most valve'') moves inward toward the three finger keys.]]\n[[File:French Horn back.svg|thumb|right|Scheme of a double horn (''view from underneath'')\n{{ordered list\n| [[Mouthpiece (brass)|Mouthpiece]]\n| [[Leadpipe]], where the mouthpiece is placed\n| Adjustable handrest\n| [[Water key]] (also called a spit valve)\n| Fourth valve to change between F and B{{music|flat}} pitches\n| Valve levers, operated with the left hand\n| [[Brass instrument valve#Rotary valve|Rotary valves]]\n| [[Slide (wind instrument)|Slides]], for tuning each valve\n| Long tubing for F pitch with slide\n| General slide\n| Short tubing for B{{music|flat}} pitch with slide\n| Bellpipe\n| [[Bell (wind instrument)|Bell]]; the right hand is cupped inside this\n}}]]\nDespite the introduction of valves, the single F horn proved difficult for use in the highest range, where the partials grew closer and closer, making accuracy a great challenge. An early solution was simply to use a horn of higher pitch\u2014usually B{{music|flat}}. The use of the F versus the B{{music|flat}} horn was extensively debated among horn players of the late 19th century, until the German horn maker Ed. Kruspe (namesake of [[Ed. Kruspe|his family's brass instrument firm]]) produced a prototype of the \"double horn\" in 1897.\n\nThe double horn also combines two instruments into a single frame: the original horn in F, and a second, higher horn keyed in B{{music|flat}}. By using a fourth valve (usually operated by the thumb), the horn player can quickly switch from the deep, warm tones of the F horn to the higher, brighter tones of the B{{music|flat}} horn, or vice versa, as the horn player may choose to have the horn set into B{{music|flat}} by default by making a simple adjustment to the valves. The two sets of tones are commonly called \"sides\" of the horn. Using the fourth valve not only changes the basic length (and thus the harmonic series and pitch) of the instrument, it also causes the three main valves to use proportionate slide lengths.<ref>Backus, John, ''The Acoustical Foundations of Music'', 2nd ed. (New York: W. W. Norton, 1977),{{Page needed|date=June 2015}} {{ISBN|0-393-09096-5}}.</ref>\n\nIn the US, the two most common styles (\"wraps\") of double horns are named Kruspe and Geyer/Knopf, after the first instrument makers who developed and standardized them. The Kruspe wrap locates the B{{music|flat}} change valve above the first valve, near the thumb. The Geyer wrap has the change valve behind the third valve, near the little finger (although the valve's trigger is still played with the thumb). In effect, the air flows in a completely different direction on the other model. Kruspe wrap horns tend to be larger in the bell throat than the Geyer wrap horns. Typically, Kruspe models are constructed from [[nickel silver]] (also called German silver, an alloy of copper, nickel and zinc, containing no actual silver) while Geyer horns tend to be of yellow brass. Both models have their own strengths and weaknesses, and while the choice of instrument is very personal, an orchestral horn section is usually found to have either one or the other, owing to the differences in tone color, response, and projection of the two different styles.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nIn Europe the most popular horns are arguably those made by Gebr. Alexander, of Mainz (particularly the Alexander 103), and those made by [[Paxman Musical Instruments|Paxman]] in London. In Germany and the [[Benelux]] countries, the Alex 103 is extremely popular. These horns do not fit strictly into the Kruspe or Knopf camps, but have features of both. Alexander prefers the traditional medium bell size, which they have produced for many years, whereas Paxman do offer their models in a range of bell throat sizes. In the United States, the [[Conn-Selmer|Conn]] 8D, a mass-produced instrument based on the Kruspe design, has been extremely popular in many areas (New York, Los Angeles, Cleveland, Philadelphia). Since roughly the early 1990s, however, for reasons ranging from changing tastes to a general dislike of Conn's newer 8Ds, orchestras have been moving away from the popular Conn 8D. Geyer model horns (by Carl Geyer, Karl Hill, Keith Berg, Steve Lewis, Jerry Lechniuk, [[Daniel Rauch|Dan Rauch]], and Ricco-Kuhn) are used in other areas (San Francisco, Chicago, Pittsburgh, Boston, Houston). The CF Schmidt double, with its unique piston change valve, is occasionally found in sections playing Geyer/Knopf model equipment.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n===Detachable bell===\nThe horn, although not large, is awkward in its shape and does not lend itself well to transport where space is shared or limited, especially on planes. To compensate, horn makers can make the bell detachable; this allows for smaller and more manageable horn cases.\n\n==Related horns==\n{{Main|Horn (instrument)}}\nThe variety in horn history necessitates consideration of the natural horn, Vienna horn, mellophone, marching horn, and Wagner tuba.\n\n===Natural horn===\n[[File:Natural Horn (instrument).JPG|left|thumb|A natural horn has no valves, but can be tuned to a different key by inserting different tubing, as during a rest period.]]\n{{Main|Natural horn}}\nThe [[natural horn]] is the ancestor of the modern horn. It is essentially descended from hunting horns, with its pitch controlled by air speed, aperture (opening of the lips through which air passes) and the use of the right hand moving around, as well as in and out of the bell. Although a few recent composers have written specifically for the natural horn (e.g., [[Gy\u00f6rgy Ligeti]]'s ''[[Hamburg Concerto]]''), today it is played primarily as a [[Historically informed performance|period instrument]]. The natural horn can only play from a single harmonic series at a time because there is only one length of tubing available to the horn player. A proficient player can indeed alter the pitch by partially muting the bell with the right hand, thus enabling the player to reach some notes that are not part of the instrument's natural harmonic series \u2013 of course this technique also affects the quality of the tone. The player has a choice of key by using crooks to change the length of tubing.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Musical instruments of the world|last=Diagram Group.|date=1976|publisher=Published for Unicef by Facts On File|isbn=0871963205|location=|pages=68|oclc=223164947}}</ref>{{Verify source|date=June 2019}}<!--It seems unlikely that a book of this nature would mention everything in this paragraph (especially Ligeti's use of the instrument).-->\n\n===Vienna horn===\n[[File:Viennese horn.jpg|thumb|300px|Vienna horn]]\n{{Main|Vienna horn}}\nThe [[Vienna horn]] is a special horn used primarily in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]]. Instead of using [[rotary valve]]s or [[piston valve]]s, it uses the pumpenvalve (or Vienna valve), which is a double-piston operating inside the valve slides, and usually situated on the opposite side of the corpus from the player's left hand, and operated by a long pushrod. Unlike the modern horn, which has grown considerably larger internally (for a bigger, broader, and louder tone), and considerably heavier (with the addition of valves and tubing in the case of the double horn) the Vienna horn very closely mimics the size and weight of the natural horn, (although the valves do add some weight, they are lighter than rotary valves) even using crooks in the front of the horn, between the mouthpiece and the instrument. Although instead of the full range of keys, Vienna horn players usually use an F crook and it is looked down upon to use others, though switching to an A or B{{music|flat}} crook for higher pitched music does happen on occasion. Vienna horns are often used with funnel shaped mouthpieces similar to those used on the natural horn, with very little (if any) backbore and a very thin rim. The Viennese horn requires very specialized technique and can be quite challenging to play, even for accomplished players of modern horns. The Vienna horn has a warmer, softer sound than the modern horn. Its pumpenvalves facilitate a continuous transition between notes ([[glissando]]); conversely, a more precise operating of the valves is required to avoid notes that sound out of tune.\n\n===Mellophone===\n{{Main|Mellophone}}\nTwo instruments are called a ''mellophone''. The first is an instrument shaped somewhat like a horn, in that it is formed in a circle. It has piston valves and is played with the right hand on the valves. Manufacturing of this instrument sharply decreased in the middle of the 20th century, and this mellophone (or mellophonium) rarely appears today.\n\nThe second instrument is used in modern brass bands and marching bands, and is more accurately called a \"marching mellophone\" or mellophone. A derivative of the F [[alto horn]], it is keyed in F. It is shaped like a flugelhorn, with piston valves played with the right hand and a forward-pointing bell. These horns are generally considered better [[marching instrument]]s than regular horns because their position is more stable on the mouth, they project better, and they weigh less. It is primarily used as the middle voice of [[drum and bugle corps (modern)|drum and bugle corps]]. Though they are usually played with a V-cup cornet-like mouthpiece, their range overlaps the common playing range of the horn. This mouthpiece switch makes the mellophone louder, less mellow, and more brassy and brilliant, making it more appropriate for marching bands. Often now with the use of converters, traditional conical horn mouthpieces are used to achieve the more mellow sound of a horn to make the marching band sound more like a concert band.\n\nAs they are pitched in F or G and their range overlaps that of the horn, mellophones can be used in place of the horn in brass and marching band settings. Mellophones are, however, sometimes unpopular with horn players because the mouthpiece change can be difficult and requires a different [[embouchure]]. Mouthpiece adapters are available so that a horn mouthpiece can fit into the mellophone lead pipe, but this does not compensate for the many differences that a horn player must adapt to. The \"feel\" of the mellophone can be foreign to a horn player. Another unfamiliar aspect of the mellophone is that it is designed to be played with the right hand instead of the left (though it can be played with the left). Intonation can also be an issue with the mellophone.{{Why|date=July 2016}}\n\nWhile horn players may be asked to play the mellophone, it is unlikely that the instrument was ever intended as a substitute for the horn, mainly because of the fundamental differences described.<ref>{{cite web | title= The History of the Mellophone | url= http://www.alsmiddlebrasspages.com/mellophone/history.html | last= Monks | first= Greg | date= 2006-01-06 | publisher= Al's Mellophone Page | accessdate= 2008-07-29}}</ref> As an instrument it compromises between the ability to sound like a horn, while being used like a trumpet or flugelhorn, a tradeoff that sacrifices acoustic properties for ergonomics.\n\n===Marching horn===\nThe marching horn is quite similar to the mellophone in shape and appearance, but is pitched in the key of B{{music|flat}}, the same as the B{{music|flat}} side of a double horn. It is also available in F alto, one octave above the F side of a double horn. The marching horn is also played with a horn mouthpiece (unlike the mellophone, which needs an adapter to fit the horn mouthpiece). These instruments are primarily used in marching bands so the sound comes from a forward-facing bell, as dissipation of the sound from the backward-facing bell becomes a concern in open-air environments. Many college marching bands and drum corps, however, use mellophones instead, which, with many marching bands, better balance the tone of the other brass instruments; additionally, mellophones require less special training of trumpeters, who considerably outnumber horn players.<ref>Mellophones, as indicated, use the same fingering as trumpets and are operated by the right hand.</ref>\n\n===Wagner tuba===\n{{Main|Wagner tuba}}\nThe Wagner tuba is a rare brass instrument that is essentially a horn modified to have a larger bell throat and a vertical bell. Despite its name, it is generally not considered part of the [[tuba]] family. Invented for [[Richard Wagner]] specifically for his work ''[[Der Ring des Nibelungen]]'', it has since been written for by various other composers, including [[Bruckner]], [[Stravinsky]] and [[Richard Strauss]]. It uses a horn mouthpiece and is available as a single tuba in B{{music|flat}} or F, or, more recently, as a double tuba similar to the double horn. Its common range is similar to that of the [[euphonium]], but its possible range is the same as that of the horn, extending from low F{{music|sharp}}, below the bass clef staff to high C above the treble staff when read in F. These low pedals are substantially easier to play on the Wagner tuba than on the horn. Wagner viewed the regular horn as a woodwind rather than a brass instrument, evidenced by his placing of the horn parts in his orchestral scores in the woodwind group and not in their usual place above the trumpets in the brass section.\n\n==Repertoire==\n[[File:Paxman-horns.jpg|thumb|left|Paxman horns]]\n{{See also|List of compositions for horn}}\n\nDiscussion of the repertoire of horns must recognize the different needs of orchestras and concert bands in contrast to marching bands, as above, but also the use of horns in a wide variety of music, including chamber music and jazz.\n\n===Orchestra and concert band===\nThe horn is most often used as an orchestral and concert band instrument, with its singular tone being employed by composers to achieve specific effects. [[Leopold Mozart]], for example, used horns to signify the hunt, as in his ''[[Jagdsinfonie]]'' (hunting symphony). [[Georg Philipp Telemann|Telemann]] wrote much for the horn, and it features prominently in the work of [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]] and in [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]'s ''Brandenburg Concerto no. 1''. Once the technique of [[hand-stopping]] had been developed, allowing fully chromatic playing, composers began to write seriously for the horn. [[Gustav Mahler]] made great use of the horn's uniquely haunting and distant sound in his symphonies, notably the famous ''Nachtmusik'' (serenade) section of his [[Symphony No. 7 (Mahler)|Symphony No. 7]].\n\nMany composers have written works that have become favorites in the horn repertoire. These include [[Francis Poulenc|Poulenc]] (''Elegie'') and [[Camille Saint-Sa\u00ebns|Saint-Sa\u00ebns]] (''Morceau de Concert for horn and orchestra'', op. 94 and ''Romance'', op. 36). Others, particularly [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]], whose friend [[Joseph Leutgeb]] was a noted horn player, wrote extensively for the instrument, including [[concerto|concerti]] and other solo works. Mozart's ''[[A Musical Joke]]'' satirizes the limitations of contemporary horn playing, including the risk of selecting the wrong crook by mistake.\n\nThe development of the valve horn was exploited by romantic composers such as [[Anton Bruckner|Bruckner]], [[Mahler]], and [[Richard Strauss]], whose father was a well-known professional horn player. Strauss's ''[[Till Eulenspiegel's Merry Pranks]]'' contains one of the best known horn solos from this period, relying on the chromatic facility of the valved horn. [[Robert Schumann|Schumann]]'s ''Konzertst\u00fcck'' for four horns and orchestra is a notable three-movement work. Brahms had a lifelong love-affair with the instrument, with many prominently featured parts throughout his four symphonies. However players today typically play Brahms on modern valved instruments.\n\n===Chamber music===\nThere is an abundance of chamber music repertoire for horn. It is a standard member of the [[wind quintet]] and [[brass quintet]], and often appears in other configurations, such as Brahms' [[Horn Trio (Brahms)|Horn Trio]] for violin, horn and piano (for which, however, Brahms specified the natural horn). Also, the horn can be used by itself in a horn ensemble or \"horn choir\". The horn choir is especially practical because the extended range of the horn provides the composer or arranger with more possibilities, registerally, sonically, and contrapuntally.\n\n==Orchestral and concert band horns==\n[[File:DSC 8763 (7084102945).jpg|thumb|300px|A horn section in a military [[concert band]]]]\nA classical orchestra usually has at least two French horn players. Typically, the first horn played a high part and the second horn played a low part. Composers from [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]] (early 1800s) onwards commonly used four horns. Here, the first and second horns played as a pair (first horn being high, second horn being low), and the third and fourth horns played as another pair (third horn being high, fourth horn being low).\n\nMusic written for the modern horn follows a similar pattern with the first and third horns being high and the second and fourth horns being low. This configuration serves multiple purposes. It is easier to play high when the adjacent player is playing low and vice versa. Pairing makes it easier to write for horns, as the third and fourth horns can take over from the first and second horns or play contrasting material. For example, if the piece is in C minor, the first and second horns might be in C, the tonic major key, which could get most of the notes, and the third and fourth horns might be in E{{music|flat}}, the relative major key, to fill in the gaps.\n\nMany orchestral horn sections in the 2010s also have an assistant<ref>Ericson, John. [http://hornmatters.com/2010/03/horn-sections-with-and-without-an-associate-principal/ \"Horn Sections With and Without an Associate Principal\"] 28 March 2010. Retrieved 14 January 2012</ref> who doubles the first horn part for selected passages, joining in loud parts, playing instead of the principal if there is a first horn solo approaching, or alternating with the principal if the part is tiring to play.<ref>Bacon, Thomas. [http://www.hornplanet.com/hornpage/museum/articles/associate.html \"The Horn Section\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304081850/http://www.hornplanet.com/hornpage/museum/articles/associate.html |date=March 4, 2016 }} Retrieved 14 January 2012</ref> Often the assistant is asked to play a passage after resting a long time. Also, he or she may be asked to enter in the middle of a passage, exactly matching the sound, articulation, and overall interpretation of the principal, thus enabling the principal horn to rest a bit.\n\n==In jazz==\n{{See also|Category:Jazz horn players|French horn in jazz}}\nThe French horn was at first rarely used in [[jazz]] music (Note that colloquially in jazz, the word \"horn\" refers to any wind instrument). Notable exponents, however, began including French horn in jazz pieces and ensembles. These include composer/arranger [[Gil Evans]] who included the French horn as an ensemble instrument from the 1940s, first in [[Claude Thornhill]]'s groups, and later with the pioneering [[cool jazz]] nonet (nine-piece group) led by trumpeter [[Miles Davis]], and in many other projects that sometimes also featured Davis, as well as [[Don Ellis]], a trumpet player from [[Stan Kenton]]'s jazz band. Notable works of Ellis' jazz French horn include \"Strawberry Soup\" and other songs on the album ''[[Tears of Joy (album)|Tears of Joy]]''. Notable improvising horn players in jazz include [[Julius Watkins]], [[Willie Ruff]], [[John Graas]], [[David Amram]], [[John Clark (musician)|John Clark]], [[Vincent Chancey]], Giovanni Hoffer, [[Arkady Shilkloper]], Adam Unsworth, and [[Tom Varner]].\n\n==Notable horn players==\n{{See also|List of horn players}}\n<!-- We do not need any more examples on this page. If you want to add more, please do so on the List of horn players article. At the very minimum, people on this list must have an article on the English Wikipedia. -->\n*[[Hermann Baumann (musician)|Hermann Baumann]] \u2013 1964 winner of the [[ARD International Music Competition]] and former principal horn in various orchestras, including the [[Stuttgart Radio Symphony Orchestra]]\n*[[Radek Babor\u00e1k]] \u2013 famous Czech horn player, former principal horn in [[Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra]], 1994 winner of the [[ARD International Music Competition]], winner of the [[Concertino Praga]] in 1988 and 1990, holder of a [[Grammy Award]] (1995)\n*[[Aubrey Brain]] \u2013 celebrated British horn player, father of Dennis Brain and a champion of the French style of instrument\n*[[Dennis Brain]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]] and the [[Philharmonia Orchestra]], with whom [[Herbert von Karajan]] made well-known recordings of [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]]'s [[Horn Concertos (Mozart)|horn concertos]]\n*[[Alan Civil]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Philharmonia Orchestra]], the [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]], and the BBC Symphony Orchestra\n*[[John Cerminaro]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Seattle Symphony]], [[New York Philharmonic]], and [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]]\n*[[Dale Clevenger]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]] (1966\u20132013)\n*[[Vincent DeRosa]] \u2013 former principal horn for a number of [[Hollywood, Los Angeles, California|Hollywood]] studios and composers including [[John Williams]]\n*[[Stefan Dohr]] \u2013 current principal horn, [[Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n*[[Richard Dunbar]] \u2013 a player of the French horn, playing in the free jazz scene\n*[[Philip Farkas]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]], developer of the [[Holton-Farkas]] horn and author of several books on horn and brass playing\n*[[Douglas Hill (musician)|Douglas Hill]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Madison Symphony Orchestra]], notable teacher and composer\n*[[Stefan de Leval Jezierski]] \u2013 longest serving horn, [[Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n*[[Philip Myers]] \u2013 principal horn of the [[New York Philharmonic]] since 1980\n*[[Jeff Nelsen]] \u2013 [[Canadian Brass]] hornist 2000\u20132004, 2007\u20132010; [[Indiana University Jacobs School of Music]] horn faculty since 2006\n*[[Giovanni Punto]] \u2013 horn virtuoso and [[hand-stopping]] pioneer, after whom the International Horn Society's annual horn playing award is named, also a violinist, concertmaster, and composer\n*[[David Pyatt]] \u2013 winner of the [[BBC Young Musician of the Year]] competition in 1988 and current principal horn of the [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n*[[Gunther Schuller]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra]] and [[Metropolitan Opera|Metropolitan Opera Orchestra]], and played with [[Miles Davis]]\n*[[Barry Tuckwell]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] and author of several books on horn playing\n*[[William VerMeulen]] \u2013 horn soloist and former principal horn of [[Honolulu Symphony Orchestra]] current principal Horn of the [[Houston Symphony Orchestra]] and professor at [[Rice University]]\n*[[Radovan Vlatkovi\u0107]] \u2013 1983 winner of the [[ARD International Music Competition]], former principal horn and soloist of the [[Berlin Radio Symphony Orchestra (East Berlin)|Berlin Radio Symphony Orchestra]], and professor at the [[Mozarteum University of Salzburg]]\n*[[Sarah Willis (hornist)|Sarah Willis]] \u2013 first female brass-player in the Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra, US-born, British ambassador for the horn and classical music through television programs such as ''Sarah's Music'' on [[Deutsche Welle]].\n\nPeople who are more notable for their other achievements, but also play the horn, include actors [[Ewan McGregor]] and [[David Ogden Stiers]], comedian and television host [[Jon Stewart]], journalist [[Chuck Todd]], [[The Who]] bassist and singer [[John Entwistle]], and rapper and record producer [[B.o.B]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = A Devil to Play|last = Rees|first = Jasper|publisher = HarperCollins|year = 2009|isbn = |location = }}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:French horn.jpg|<center>A modern full double horn</center>\nFile:Viennese horn.jpg|<center>A [[Vienna horn]]</center>\nFile:Hunting horn 3.jpg|<center>A hunting horn</center>\nFile:Omnitonic horn 2.jpg|<center>A French Omnitonic horn</center>\nFile:Natural Horn (instrument).JPG|<center>A [[natural horn]] at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]]</center>\nFile:Stanford Natural Horn.JPG|<center>A replica of a Mozart-era natural horn</center>\nFile:cordechasse.png|<center>A hunting horn in E{{music|flat}}</center>\nFile:Cor_naturel.JPG|<center>A natural horn</center>\nFile:Three valves horn.jpg|<center>An older, French-made ''cor \u00e0 pistons'' in E{{music|flat}}</center>\nFile:Brain-raoux.jpg|<center>A French-made horn with piston valves</center>\nFile:Dennis-brain-alex.jpg|<center>A horn by Alexander, once owned by Dennis Brain</center>\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of compositions for horn]]\n* [[List of horn makers]]\n* [[List of horn techniques]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikibooks|Horn/Repertoire}}\n{{wikibooks|Horn}}<!-- COMMENT: The {{wikibookspar|horn}} template was screwed up as of the date of this edit. Redirecting [[Wikibooks:Horn (instrument)]] to [[Wikibooks:Horn]] for the time being -->\n<!-- Please think twice about putting links to non-English language Horn societies; those should go on the pages of their respective languages! -->\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Horn (class of wind instruments)}}\n*[http://www.hornsociety.org/ Homepage of the International Horn Society], one of the largest organizations of horn players in the world.\n*[http://www.british-horn.org/ British Horn Society], UK-based organisation for horn playing\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120510062528/http://www.finkehorns.de/Bilder/first-steps.mov First steps of making a horn by hand] (QuickTime Movie) at Finke Horns\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140712070243/http://www.cosmos-club.org/web/journals/1999/bowles.html From mines to music: The venerable valve], by musicologist Edmund A. Bowles\n*[http://www.paxman.co.uk/pages/index.html?http%3A//www.paxman.co.uk/pages/horncentre/hornmaintenance.html Horn maintenance] at Paxman, compiled with the assistance of [[Simon de Souza]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924013143/http://www.finkehorns.de/English/ServiceVentile.html How to dismantle a valve] at Finke Horns\n*[http://www.hornetudes.com Horn Etudes] -  List of horn etudes\n\n{{Musical instruments |state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:French horn}}\n[[Category:Brass instruments]]\n[[Category:F instruments]]\n[[Category:German musical instruments]]\n[[Category:Horns]]\n[[Category:Orchestral instruments]]\n[[Category:Western Classical music instruments]]\n[[Category:Jazz instruments]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=January 2010}}\n{{Infobox instrument\n|name=French horn\n|names=Horn<br />[[German language|de:]]&nbsp;''Horn, Waldhorn, Ventilhorn''<br />[[Spanish language|es:]]&nbsp;''trompa'' or ''corno''<br />[[French language|fr:]]&nbsp;''cor (d'harmonie)''<br />[[Italian language|it:]]&nbsp;''corno''\n|image=French horn front.png\n|image_capt=French (German double) horn\n|background=brass\n|classification=[[Aerophone]]<br />[[Wind instrument|Wind]]<br />[[Brass instrument|Brass]]\n|hornbostel_sachs=423.232\n|hornbostel_sachs_desc=Valved aerophone sounded by lip movement\n|range=[[File:Range_of_horn.png|200px|center]]in F: sounds a [[perfect fifth]] lower than written. Nonetheless, in older music, bass-clef notes are written one octave lower (thus sounding a [[perfect fourth]] higher than written).<ref name=\"Walter\">{{Cite book |title=Orchestration |last=Piston |first= Walter |date=1955 |publisher=Norton |isbn=978-0393097405 |edition=1st |location=New York |oclc=300471}}</ref>\n|related=* [[Tenor horn|Tenor horn (alto horn)]]\n* [[Baritone horn]]\n* [[German horn]]\n* [[Mellophone]]\n* [[Natural horn]]\n* [[Post horn]]\n* [[Saxhorn]]\n* [[Vienna horn]]\n* [[Wagner tuba]]\n|musicians=* [[List of horn players]]\n|builders=*[[List of horn makers]]\n|midi=060/061 (French Horn)\n|articles=* [[List of horn techniques]]\n* [[List of compositions for horn]]\n}}\n{{Brass}}\nThe '''French horn''' (since the 1930s known simply as the \"horn\" in professional music circles) is a [[brass instrument]] made of tubing wrapped into a coil with a flared bell. The '''double horn in F/B{{music|flat}}''' (technically a variety of [[German horn]]) is the horn most often used by players in professional orchestras and bands. A musician who plays a horn is known as a [[list of horn players|horn player]] or hornist.\n\nPitch is controlled through the combination of the following factors: speed of air through the instrument (controlled by the player's lungs and [[thoracic diaphragm]]); diameter and tension of lip aperture (by the player's lip muscles\u2014the [[embouchure]]) in the mouthpiece; plus, in a modern horn, the operation of [[Brass instrument valve|valves]] by the left hand, which route the air into extra sections of tubing. Most horns have lever-operated [[rotary valve]]s, but some, especially older horns, use [[piston valve]]s (similar to a [[trumpet]]'s) and the [[Vienna horn]] uses double-piston valves, or [[Brass instrument valve#Double-piston valve|pumpenvalves]]. The backward-facing orientation of the bell relates to the perceived desirability to create a subdued sound in concert situations, in contrast to the more piercing quality of the trumpet.  A horn without valves is known as a natural horn, changing pitch along the natural [[harmonics]] of the instrument (similar to a [[bugle (instrument)|bugle]]). Pitch may also be controlled by the position of the hand in the bell, in effect reducing the bell's diameter. The pitch of any note can easily be raised or lowered by adjusting the hand position in the bell.<ref name=\"Whitener\">{{Cite book |title=A complete guide to brass : instruments and pedagogy |last=Whitener |first=Scott and Cathy L. |publisher=Schirmer Books |year=1990 |isbn=978-0028728612 |location=New York |pages=40, 44 |oclc=19128016}}</ref> The key of a natural horn can be changed by adding different crooks of different lengths.\n\nThree valves control the flow of air in the ''single horn'', which is tuned to F or less commonly B{{music|flat}}. The more common ''double horn'' has a fourth, trigger valve, usually operated by the thumb, which routes the air to one set of tubing tuned to F or another tuned to B{{music|flat}} which expands the horn range to over four [[octaves]] and blends with flutes or [[clarinet]]s in a [[woodwind ensemble]]. Triple horns with five valves are also made, usually tuned in F, B{{music|flat}}, and a [[descant]] E{{music|flat}} or F. There are also double horns with five valves tuned in B{{music|flat}}, descant E{{music|flat}} or F, and a stopping valve, which greatly simplifies the complicated and difficult hand-stopping technique,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://poperepair.com/alexander-107-descant-w-stopping-valve-7800 |title=Alexander 107 Descant w/Stopping Valve - $7800 |last=Pope |first=Ken |website=Pope Instrument Repair |language=en |access-date=2018-02-22}}</ref> though these are rarer. Also common are ''descant'' doubles, which typically provide B{{music|flat}} and alto F branches.\n\nA crucial element in playing the horn deals with the mouthpiece. Most of the time, the mouthpiece is placed in the exact center of the lips, but, because of differences in the formation of the lips and teeth of different players, some tend to play with the mouthpiece slightly off center.<ref name=\"AOFHP\">{{Cite book |title=The art of French horn playing : a treatise on the problems and techniques of French Horn playing \u2026 |last=Farkas |first=Philip |date=1956 |publisher=Summy-Birchard  |isbn=978-0874870213 |location=Evanston, Il. |pages=6, 21, 65 |oclc=5587694}}</ref> Although the exact side-to-side placement of the mouthpiece varies for most horn players, the up-and-down placement of the mouthpiece is generally two-thirds on the upper lip and one-third on the lower lip.<ref name=\"AOFHP\" /> When playing higher notes, the majority of players exert a small degree of additional pressure on the lips using the mouthpiece. However, this is undesirable from the perspective of both endurance and tone: excessive mouthpiece pressure makes the horn sound forced and harsh, and decreases player's stamina due to the resulting constricted flow of blood to the lips and lip muscles.<ref name=\"AOFHP\" />\n\n==Name==\nThe name \"French horn\" is found only in English, first coming into use in the late 17th century.  At that time, French makers were preeminent in the manufacture of hunting horns, and were credited with creating the now-familiar, circular \"hoop\" shape of the instrument. As a result, these instruments were often called, even in English, by their French names: ''trompe de chasse'' or ''cor de chasse'' (the clear modern distinction between ''trompes'', trumpets, and ''cors'', horns, did not exist at that time).<ref name=\"Beakes\" />\n\nGerman makers first devised ''crooks'' to make such horns playable in different keys\u2014so musicians came to use \"French\" and \"German\" to distinguish the simple hunting horn from the newer horn with crooks, which in England was also called by the Italian name ''corno cromatico'' (chromatic horn).<ref name=\"Beakes\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=zpOAnQEACAAJ |title=The Horn Parts in Handel's Operas and Oratorios and the Horn Players who Performed in These Works |last=Beakes |first=Jennifer |date=2007 |publisher=City University of New York |pages=50, 116\u201318, 176, 223\u201325, 439\u201340, 444\u201345 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nMore recently, \"French horn\" is often used colloquially, though the adjective has normally been avoided when referring to the European orchestral horn, ever since the German horn began replacing the French-style instrument in British orchestras around 1930.<ref name=\"Del Mar\">{{Cite book |title=Anatomy of the orchestra |last=Del Mar |first= Norman |date=1983 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0520045002 |edition=2nd print., with revisions |location=Berkeley |pages=215 |oclc=10561390}}</ref> The [[International Horn Society]] has recommended since 1971 that the instrument be simply called the ''horn''.<ref name=\"Meek1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hornsociety.org/home/ihs-news/26-people/honorary/61-harold-meek-1914-1998 |title=Harold Meek (1914\u20131998) |last=Meek |first=Harold |website=International Horn Society |access-date=2018-09-04 |quote=Harold Meek is described by everyone as a gentleman, a perfectionist, and one who loved the horn. He was the first editor of ''The Horn Call'' and was responsible for this statement in every issue, 'The International Horn Society recommends that HORN be recognized as the correct name for our instrument in the English language.'}}</ref><ref name=\"Meek2\">{{Cite journal |last=Meek |first=Harold |date=February 1971 |title=The Horn! |journal=The Horn Call |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201320 |quote=Meek strongly advocates using the term 'horn' rather than 'French horn.'}}</ref>\n\nThere is also a more specific use of \"French horn\" to describe a particular horn type, differentiated from the [[German horn]] and [[Vienna horn]]. In this sense, \"French horn\" refers to a narrow-bore instrument ({{cvt|10.8|-|11.0|mm|in|disp=sqbr}}) with three P\u00e9rinet (piston) valves. It retains the narrow bell-throat and mouthpipe crooks of the orchestral hand horn of the late 18th century, and most often has an \"ascending\" third valve. This is a whole-tone valve arranged so that with the valve in the \"up\" position the valve loop is engaged, but when the valve is pressed the loop is cut out, raising the pitch by a whole tone.<ref name=\"Baines\">{{Cite book |title=Brass instruments : their history and development |last=Baines |first=Anthony |date=1976 |publisher=Scribner |isbn=978-0684152295 |location=New York |pages=221\u201323 |oclc=3795926}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|Horn (instrument)}}\n[[File:French-horn.png|left|thumb|250px|Horn with three [[piston valve|Perinet valves]]]]\n[[File:How to shout and blow Horns Fac simile of a Miniature in the Manuscript of Phoebus Fifteenth Century.png|thumb|right|\"How to shout and blow horns.\"\u2014Facsimile of a miniature in a manuscript of the hunting manual of [[Gaston III of Foix-B\u00e9arn|Gaston Phoebus]] (15th century)]]\n\nAs the name indicates, humans originally used to blow on the actual [[Horn (anatomy)|horn]]s of animals before starting to emulate them in metal. This original usage survives in the [[shofar]], a ram's horn, which plays an important role in [[Judaism|Jewish religious rituals]].\n\nEarly metal horns were less complex than modern horns, consisting of brass tubes with a slightly flared opening (the bell) wound around a few times. These early \"hunting\" horns were originally played on a hunt, often while mounted, and the sound they produced was called a recheat. Change of pitch was controlled entirely by the lips (the horn not being equipped with valves until the 19th century). Without valves, only the notes within the [[harmonic series (music)|harmonic series]] are available.  By combining a long length with a narrow bore, the French horn's design allows the player to easily reach the higher overtones which differ by whole tones or less, thus making it capable of playing melodies before valves were invented.<ref name=\"AOFHP\" />\n\nEarly horns were commonly pitched in B{{music|flat}} alto, A, A{{music|flat}}, G, F, E, E{{music|flat}}, D, C, and B{{music|flat}} basso. Since the only notes available were those on the harmonic series of one of those pitches, they had no ability to play in different keys. The remedy for this limitation was the use of [[Crook (music)|crooks]], i.e., sections of tubing of differing length that, when inserted, altered the length of the instrument, and thus its pitch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://omeka1.grinnell.edu/MusicalInstruments/items/show/193|title=Grinell College Musical|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-18th century, horn players began to insert the right hand into the bell to change the length of the instrument, adjusting the tuning up to the distance between two adjacent harmonics depending on how much of the opening was covered.\n\nIn 1818 the German makers [[Heinrich St\u00f6lzel]] and Friedrich Bl\u00fcmel patented the first valved horn, using rotary valves. Piston valves were introduced in France about 1839 by Fran\u00e7ois P\u00e9rinet.<ref name=\"Meek3\">{{Cite book |title=Horn and conductor : reminiscences of a practitioner with a few words of advice |last=Meek |first=Harold L. |date=1997 |publisher=University of Rochester Press |isbn=978-1878822833 |location=Rochester, NY |pages=33 |oclc=35636932}}</ref> Valves were initially intended to overcome problems associated with changing crooks during a performance. Valves' unreliability, musical taste, and players' distrust, among other reasons, slowed their adoption into mainstream. Many traditional conservatories and players refused to use them at first, claiming that the valveless horn, or ''natural horn'', was a better instrument. Some musicians who specialize in period instruments use a natural horn to play in original performance styles, to try to recapture the sound of an older piece's original performances.<ref>See, e.g., the performance of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]'s ''[[Mass in B Minor]]'' as performed by the [[Proms]] of London in the movement from 45:40 onward in {{cite web\n|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7F7TVM8m95Y\n|title = Mass in B Minor\n|magazine = You Tube\n|date = 2012\n|accessdate = 2013-11-29\n}}</ref>\n\nThe use of [[brass instrument valve|valves]], however, opened up a great deal more flexibility in playing in different keys; in effect, the horn became an entirely different instrument, fully chromatic for the first time. Valves were originally used primarily as a means to play in different keys without crooks, not for harmonic playing. That is reflected in compositions for horns, which only began to include chromatic passages in the late 19th century.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018|Speculation=The extremely high horn playing from the baroque and early classical periods would allow the horn to play almost completely chromatically due to the tiny differences in harmonics. This may have caused the name to develop as nobody was to know then that true chromaticism would happen in the next century. Examples include anything in a high register from that period, e.g. the horn solo from Bach's B-Minor Mass}}<!--If this is true, then what was the \"corno chromatico\" of the late 18th century, and why was it so called?-->  When valves were invented, generally, the French made smaller horns with piston valves and the Germans made larger horns with rotary valves.{{Clarify|reason=German brass players had (and many still have) a preference towards rotary valves. This is commonly seen as a holdover today as a huge amount of German and Austrian orchestras use rotary trumpets, while the majority of the rest of the world use piston trumpets. An example is seen at the very start of this performance by the Berlin Philharmonic https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bwQumQpug_E|date=February 2018}}<!--What, like horns in F, as opposed to horns in B-flat basso or alto?-->\n\n==Types==\nHorns may be classified in single horn, double horn, compensating double horn, and triple horn as well as the versatility of detachable bells.\n[[File:Yamaha Horn YHR-314II.tif|thumb|250px|right|Single horn in F, student model.]]\n\n===Single horn===\nSingle horns use a single set of tubes connected to the valves. This allows for simplicity of use and a much lighter weight. They are usually in the keys of F or B{{music|flat}}, although many F horns have longer slides to tune them to E{{music|flat}}, and almost all B{{music|flat}} horns have a valve to put them in the key of A. The problem with single horns is the inevitable choice between accuracy or tone \u2013 while the F horn has the \"typical\" horn sound, above third-space C accuracy is a concern for the majority of players because, by its nature, one plays high in the horn's harmonic series where the overtones are closer together. This led to the development of the B{{music|flat}} horn, which, although easier to play accurately, has a less desirable sound in the mid and especially the low register where it is not able to play all of the notes.  The solution has been the development of the double horn, which combines the two into one horn with a single lead pipe and bell.  Both main types of single horns are still used today as student models because they are cheaper and lighter than double horns.  In addition, the single B{{music|flat}} horns are sometimes used in solo and chamber performances and the single F survives orchestrally as the Vienna horn. Additionally, single F alto and B{{music|flat}} alto descants are used in the performance of some baroque horn concertos and F, B{{music|flat}} and F alto singles are occasionally used by [[jazz]] performers.\n\n[[Dennis Brain]]'s benchmark recordings of the Mozart Horn Concerti were made on a single B{{music|flat}} instrument by [[Gebr. Alexander]], now on display at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in London.\n\n===Double horn===\n[[File:French horn detail.jpg|frame|right|The [[rotary valve|valves]] of a [[Conn-Selmer|Conn]] 6D double horn. The three lever keys (above the large valves) can be depressed toward the large outer tube. The thumb key (''near the left-most valve'') moves inward toward the three finger keys.]]\n[[File:French Horn back.svg|thumb|right|Scheme of a double horn (''view from underneath'')\n{{ordered list\n| [[Mouthpiece (brass)|Mouthpiece]]\n| [[Leadpipe]], where the mouthpiece is placed\n| Adjustable handrest\n| [[Water key]] (also called a spit valve)\n| Fourth valve to change between F and B{{music|flat}} pitches\n| Valve levers, operated with the left hand\n| [[Brass instrument valve#Rotary valve|Rotary valves]]\n| [[Slide (wind instrument)|Slides]], for tuning each valve\n| Long tubing for F pitch with slide\n| General slide\n| Short tubing for B{{music|flat}} pitch with slide\n| Bellpipe\n| [[Bell (wind instrument)|Bell]]; the right hand is cupped inside this\n}}]]\nDespite the introduction of valves, the single F horn proved difficult for use in the highest range, where the partials grew closer and closer, making accuracy a great challenge. An early solution was simply to use a horn of higher pitch\u2014usually B{{music|flat}}. The use of the F versus the B{{music|flat}} horn was extensively debated among horn players of the late 19th century, until the German horn maker Ed. Kruspe (namesake of [[Ed. Kruspe|his family's brass instrument firm]]) produced a prototype of the \"double horn\" in 1897.\n\nThe double horn also combines two instruments into a single frame: the original horn in F, and a second, higher horn keyed in B{{music|flat}}. By using a fourth valve (usually operated by the thumb), the horn player can quickly switch from the deep, warm tones of the F horn to the higher, brighter tones of the B{{music|flat}} horn, or vice versa, as the horn player may choose to have the horn set into B{{music|flat}} by default by making a simple adjustment to the valves. The two sets of tones are commonly called \"sides\" of the horn. Using the fourth valve not only changes the basic length (and thus the harmonic series and pitch) of the instrument, it also causes the three main valves to use proportionate slide lengths.<ref>Backus, John, ''The Acoustical Foundations of Music'', 2nd ed. (New York: W. W. Norton, 1977),{{Page needed|date=June 2015}} {{ISBN|0-393-09096-5}}.</ref>\n\nIn the US, the two most common styles (\"wraps\") of double horns are named Kruspe and Geyer/Knopf, after the first instrument makers who developed and standardized them. The Kruspe wrap locates the B{{music|flat}} change valve above the first valve, near the thumb. The Geyer wrap has the change valve behind the third valve, near the little finger (although the valve's trigger is still played with the thumb). In effect, the air flows in a completely different direction on the other model. Kruspe wrap horns tend to be larger in the bell throat than the Geyer wrap horns. Typically, Kruspe models are constructed from [[nickel silver]] (also called German silver, an alloy of copper, nickel and zinc, containing no actual silver) while Geyer horns tend to be of yellow brass. Both models have their own strengths and weaknesses, and while the choice of instrument is very personal, an orchestral horn section is usually found to have either one or the other, owing to the differences in tone color, response, and projection of the two different styles.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nIn Europe the most popular horns are arguably those made by Gebr. Alexander, of Mainz (particularly the Alexander 103), and those made by [[Paxman Musical Instruments|Paxman]] in London. In Germany and the [[Benelux]] countries, the Alex 103 is extremely popular. These horns do not fit strictly into the Kruspe or Knopf camps, but have features of both. Alexander prefers the traditional medium bell size, which they have produced for many years, whereas Paxman do offer their models in a range of bell throat sizes. In the United States, the [[Conn-Selmer|Conn]] 8D, a mass-produced instrument based on the Kruspe design, has been extremely popular in many areas (New York, Los Angeles, Cleveland, Philadelphia). Since roughly the early 1990s, however, for reasons ranging from changing tastes to a general dislike of Conn's newer 8Ds, orchestras have been moving away from the popular Conn 8D. Geyer model horns (by Carl Geyer, Karl Hill, Keith Berg, Steve Lewis, Jerry Lechniuk, [[Daniel Rauch|Dan Rauch]], and Ricco-Kuhn) are used in other areas (San Francisco, Chicago, Pittsburgh, Boston, Houston). The CF Schmidt double, with its unique piston change valve, is occasionally found in sections playing Geyer/Knopf model equipment.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n===Detachable bell===\nThe horn, although not large, is awkward in its shape and does not lend itself well to transport where space is shared or limited, especially on planes. To compensate, horn makers can make the bell detachable; this allows for smaller and more manageable horn cases.\n\n==Related horns==\n{{Main|Horn (instrument)}}\nThe variety in horn history necessitates consideration of the natural horn, Vienna horn, mellophone, marching horn, and Wagner tuba.\n\n===Natural horn===\n[[File:Natural Horn (instrument).JPG|left|thumb|A natural horn has no valves, but can be tuned to a different key by inserting different tubing, as during a rest period.]]\n{{Main|Natural horn}}\nThe [[natural horn]] is the ancestor of the modern horn. It is essentially descended from hunting horns, with its pitch controlled by air speed, aperture (opening of the lips through which air passes) and the use of the right hand moving around, as well as in and out of the bell. Although a few recent composers have written specifically for the natural horn (e.g., [[Gy\u00f6rgy Ligeti]]'s ''[[Hamburg Concerto]]''), today it is played primarily as a [[Historically informed performance|period instrument]]. The natural horn can only play from a single harmonic series at a time because there is only one length of tubing available to the horn player. A proficient player can indeed alter the pitch by partially muting the bell with the right hand, thus enabling the player to reach some notes that are not part of the instrument's natural harmonic series \u2013 of course this technique also affects the quality of the tone. The player has a choice of key by using crooks to change the length of tubing.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Musical instruments of the world|last=Diagram Group.|date=1976|publisher=Published for Unicef by Facts On File|isbn=0871963205|location=|pages=68|oclc=223164947}}</ref>{{Verify source|date=June 2019}}<!--It seems unlikely that a book of this nature would mention everything in this paragraph (especially Ligeti's use of the instrument).-->\n\n===Vienna horn===\n[[File:Viennese horn.jpg|thumb|300px|Vienna horn]]\n{{Main|Vienna horn}}\nThe [[Vienna horn]] is a special horn used primarily in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]]. Instead of using [[rotary valve]]s or [[piston valve]]s, it uses the pumpenvalve (or Vienna valve), which is a double-piston operating inside the valve slides, and usually situated on the opposite side of the corpus from the player's left hand, and operated by a long pushrod. Unlike the modern horn, which has grown considerably larger internally (for a bigger, broader, and louder tone), and considerably heavier (with the addition of valves and tubing in the case of the double horn) the Vienna horn very closely mimics the size and weight of the natural horn, (although the valves do add some weight, they are lighter than rotary valves) even using crooks in the front of the horn, between the mouthpiece and the instrument. Although instead of the full range of keys, Vienna horn players usually use an F crook and it is looked down upon to use others, though switching to an A or B{{music|flat}} crook for higher pitched music does happen on occasion. Vienna horns are often used with funnel shaped mouthpieces similar to those used on the natural horn, with very little (if any) backbore and a very thin rim. The Viennese horn requires very specialized technique and can be quite challenging to play, even for accomplished players of modern horns. The Vienna horn has a warmer, softer sound than the modern horn. Its pumpenvalves facilitate a continuous transition between notes ([[glissando]]); conversely, a more precise operating of the valves is required to avoid notes that sound out of tune.\n\n===Mellophone===\n{{Main|Mellophone}}\nTwo instruments are called a ''mellophone''. The first is an instrument shaped somewhat like a horn, in that it is formed in a circle. It has piston valves and is played with the right hand on the valves. Manufacturing of this instrument sharply decreased in the middle of the 20th century, and this mellophone (or mellophonium) rarely appears today.\n\nThe second instrument is used in modern brass bands and marching bands, and is more accurately called a \"marching mellophone\" or mellophone. A derivative of the F [[alto horn]], it is keyed in F. It is shaped like a flugelhorn, with piston valves played with the right hand and a forward-pointing bell. These horns are generally considered better [[marching instrument]]s than regular horns because their position is more stable on the mouth, they project better, and they weigh less. It is primarily used as the middle voice of [[drum and bugle corps (modern)|drum and bugle corps]]. Though they are usually played with a V-cup cornet-like mouthpiece, their range overlaps the common playing range of the horn. This mouthpiece switch makes the mellophone louder, less mellow, and more brassy and brilliant, making it more appropriate for marching bands. Often now with the use of converters, traditional conical horn mouthpieces are used to achieve the more mellow sound of a horn to make the marching band sound more like a concert band.\n\nAs they are pitched in F or G and their range overlaps that of the horn, mellophones can be used in place of the horn in brass and marching band settings. Mellophones are, however, sometimes unpopular with horn players because the mouthpiece change can be difficult and requires a different [[embouchure]]. Mouthpiece adapters are available so that a horn mouthpiece can fit into the mellophone lead pipe, but this does not compensate for the many differences that a horn player must adapt to. The \"feel\" of the mellophone can be foreign to a horn player. Another unfamiliar aspect of the mellophone is that it is designed to be played with the right hand instead of the left (though it can be played with the left). Intonation can also be an issue with the mellophone.{{Why|date=July 2016}}\n\nWhile horn players may be asked to play the mellophone, it is unlikely that the instrument was ever intended as a substitute for the horn, mainly because of the fundamental differences described.<ref>{{cite web | title= The History of the Mellophone | url= http://www.alsmiddlebrasspages.com/mellophone/history.html | last= Monks | first= Greg | date= 2006-01-06 | publisher= Al's Mellophone Page | accessdate= 2008-07-29}}</ref> As an instrument it compromises between the ability to sound like a horn, while being used like a trumpet or flugelhorn, a tradeoff that sacrifices acoustic properties for ergonomics.\n\n===Marching horn===\nThe marching horn is quite similar to the mellophone in shape and appearance, but is pitched in the key of B{{music|flat}}, the same as the B{{music|flat}} side of a double horn. It is also available in F alto, one octave above the F side of a double horn. The marching horn is also played with a horn mouthpiece (unlike the mellophone, which needs an adapter to fit the horn mouthpiece). These instruments are primarily used in marching bands so the sound comes from a forward-facing bell, as dissipation of the sound from the backward-facing bell becomes a concern in open-air environments. Many college marching bands and drum corps, however, use mellophones instead, which, with many marching bands, better balance the tone of the other brass instruments; additionally, mellophones require less special training of trumpeters, who considerably outnumber horn players.<ref>Mellophones, as indicated, use the same fingering as trumpets and are operated by the right hand.</ref>\n\n===Wagner tuba===\n{{Main|Wagner tuba}}\nThe Wagner tuba is a rare brass instrument that is essentially a horn modified to have a larger bell throat and a vertical bell. Despite its name, it is generally not considered part of the [[tuba]] family. Invented for [[Richard Wagner]] specifically for his work ''[[Der Ring des Nibelungen]]'', it has since been written for by various other composers, including [[Bruckner]], [[Stravinsky]] and [[Richard Strauss]]. It uses a horn mouthpiece and is available as a single tuba in B{{music|flat}} or F, or, more recently, as a double tuba similar to the double horn. Its common range is similar to that of the [[euphonium]], but its possible range is the same as that of the horn, extending from low F{{music|sharp}}, below the bass clef staff to high C above the treble staff when read in F. These low pedals are substantially easier to play on the Wagner tuba than on the horn. Wagner viewed the regular horn as a woodwind rather than a brass instrument, evidenced by his placing of the horn parts in his orchestral scores in the woodwind group and not in their usual place above the trumpets in the brass section.\n\n==Repertoire==\n[[File:Paxman-horns.jpg|thumb|left|Paxman horns]]\n{{See also|List of compositions for horn}}\n\nDiscussion of the repertoire of horns must recognize the different needs of orchestras and concert bands in contrast to marching bands, as above, but also the use of horns in a wide variety of music, including chamber music and jazz.\n\n===Orchestra and concert band===\nThe horn is most often used as an orchestral and concert band instrument, with its singular tone being employed by composers to achieve specific effects. [[Leopold Mozart]], for example, used horns to signify the hunt, as in his ''[[Jagdsinfonie]]'' (hunting symphony). [[Georg Philipp Telemann|Telemann]] wrote much for the horn, and it features prominently in the work of [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]] and in [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]'s ''Brandenburg Concerto no. 1''. Once the technique of [[hand-stopping]] had been developed, allowing fully chromatic playing, composers began to write seriously for the horn. [[Gustav Mahler]] made great use of the horn's uniquely haunting and distant sound in his symphonies, notably the famous ''Nachtmusik'' (serenade) section of his [[Symphony No. 7 (Mahler)|Symphony No. 7]].\n\nMany composers have written works that have become favorites in the horn repertoire. These include [[Francis Poulenc|Poulenc]] (''Elegie'') and [[Camille Saint-Sa\u00ebns|Saint-Sa\u00ebns]] (''Morceau de Concert for horn and orchestra'', op. 94 and ''Romance'', op. 36). Others, particularly [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]], whose friend [[Joseph Leutgeb]] was a noted horn player, wrote extensively for the instrument, including [[concerto|concerti]] and other solo works. Mozart's ''[[A Musical Joke]]'' satirizes the limitations of contemporary horn playing, including the risk of selecting the wrong crook by mistake.\n\nThe development of the valve horn was exploited by romantic composers such as [[Anton Bruckner|Bruckner]], [[Mahler]], and [[Richard Strauss]], whose father was a well-known professional horn player. Strauss's ''[[Till Eulenspiegel's Merry Pranks]]'' contains one of the best known horn solos from this period, relying on the chromatic facility of the valved horn. [[Robert Schumann|Schumann]]'s ''Konzertst\u00fcck'' for four horns and orchestra is a notable three-movement work. Brahms had a lifelong love-affair with the instrument, with many prominently featured parts throughout his four symphonies. However players today typically play Brahms on modern valved instruments.\n\n===Chamber music===\nThere is an abundance of chamber music repertoire for horn. It is a standard member of the [[wind quintet]] and [[brass quintet]], and often appears in other configurations, such as Brahms' [[Horn Trio (Brahms)|Horn Trio]] for violin, horn and piano (for which, however, Brahms specified the natural horn). Also, the horn can be used by itself in a horn ensemble or \"horn choir\". The horn choir is especially practical because the extended range of the horn provides the composer or arranger with more possibilities, registerally, sonically, and contrapuntally.\n\n==Orchestral and concert band horns==\n[[File:DSC 8763 (7084102945).jpg|thumb|300px|A horn section in a military [[concert band]]]]\nA classical orchestra usually has at least two French horn players. Typically, the first horn played a high part and the second horn played a low part. Composers from [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]] (early 1800s) onwards commonly used four horns. Here, the first and second horns played as a pair (first horn being high, second horn being low), and the third and fourth horns played as another pair (third horn being high, fourth horn being low).\n\nMusic written for the modern horn follows a similar pattern with the first and third horns being high and the second and fourth horns being low. This configuration serves multiple purposes. It is easier to play high when the adjacent player is playing low and vice versa. Pairing makes it easier to write for horns, as the third and fourth horns can take over from the first and second horns or play contrasting material. For example, if the piece is in C minor, the first and second horns might be in C, the tonic major key, which could get most of the notes, and the third and fourth horns might be in E{{music|flat}}, the relative major key, to fill in the gaps.\n\nMany orchestral horn sections in the 2010s also have an assistant<ref>Ericson, John. [http://hornmatters.com/2010/03/horn-sections-with-and-without-an-associate-principal/ \"Horn Sections With and Without an Associate Principal\"] 28 March 2010. Retrieved 14 January 2012</ref> who doubles the first horn part for selected passages, joining in loud parts, playing instead of the principal if there is a first horn solo approaching, or alternating with the principal if the part is tiring to play.<ref>Bacon, Thomas. [http://www.hornplanet.com/hornpage/museum/articles/associate.html \"The Horn Section\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304081850/http://www.hornplanet.com/hornpage/museum/articles/associate.html |date=March 4, 2016 }} Retrieved 14 January 2012</ref> Often the assistant is asked to play a passage after resting a long time. Also, he or she may be asked to enter in the middle of a passage, exactly matching the sound, articulation, and overall interpretation of the principal, thus enabling the principal horn to rest a bit.\n\n==In jazz==\n{{See also|Category:Jazz horn players|French horn in jazz}}\nThe French horn was at first rarely used in [[jazz]] music (Note that colloquially in jazz, the word \"horn\" refers to any wind instrument). Notable exponents, however, began including French horn in jazz pieces and ensembles. These include composer/arranger [[Gil Evans]] who included the French horn as an ensemble instrument from the 1940s, first in [[Claude Thornhill]]'s groups, and later with the pioneering [[cool jazz]] nonet (nine-piece group) led by trumpeter [[Miles Davis]], and in many other projects that sometimes also featured Davis, as well as [[Don Ellis]], a trumpet player from [[Stan Kenton]]'s jazz band. Notable works of Ellis' jazz French horn include \"Strawberry Soup\" and other songs on the album ''[[Tears of Joy (album)|Tears of Joy]]''. Notable improvising horn players in jazz include [[Julius Watkins]], [[Willie Ruff]], [[John Graas]], [[David Amram]], [[John Clark (musician)|John Clark]], [[Vincent Chancey]], Giovanni Hoffer, [[Arkady Shilkloper]], Adam Unsworth, and [[Tom Varner]].\n\n==Notable horn players==\n{{See also|List of horn players}}\n<!-- We do not need any more examples on this page. If you want to add more, please do so on the List of horn players article. At the very minimum, people on this list must have an article on the English Wikipedia. -->\n*[[Hermann Baumann (musician)|Hermann Baumann]] \u2013 1964 winner of the [[ARD International Music Competition]] and former principal horn in various orchestras, including the [[Stuttgart Radio Symphony Orchestra]]\n*[[Radek Babor\u00e1k]] \u2013 famous Czech horn player, former principal horn in [[Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra]], 1994 winner of the [[ARD International Music Competition]], winner of the [[Concertino Praga]] in 1988 and 1990, holder of a [[Grammy Award]] (1995)\n*[[Aubrey Brain]] \u2013 celebrated British horn player, father of Dennis Brain and a champion of the French style of instrument\n*[[Dennis Brain]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]] and the [[Philharmonia Orchestra]], with whom [[Herbert von Karajan]] made well-known recordings of [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]]'s [[Horn Concertos (Mozart)|horn concertos]]\n*[[Alan Civil]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Philharmonia Orchestra]], the [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]], and the BBC Symphony Orchestra\n*[[John Cerminaro]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Seattle Symphony]], [[New York Philharmonic]], and [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]]\n*[[Dale Clevenger]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]] (1966\u20132013)\n*[[Vincent DeRosa]] \u2013 former principal horn for a number of [[Hollywood, Los Angeles, California|Hollywood]] studios and composers including [[John Williams]]\n*[[Stefan Dohr]] \u2013 current principal horn, [[Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n*[[Richard Dunbar]] \u2013 a player of the French horn, playing in the free jazz scene\n*[[Philip Farkas]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]], developer of the [[Holton-Farkas]] horn and author of several books on horn and brass playing\n*[[Douglas Hill (musician)|Douglas Hill]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Madison Symphony Orchestra]], notable teacher and composer\n*[[Stefan de Leval Jezierski]] \u2013 longest serving horn, [[Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n*[[Philip Myers]] \u2013 principal horn of the [[New York Philharmonic]] since 1980\n*[[Jeff Nelsen]] \u2013 [[Canadian Brass]] hornist 2000\u20132004, 2007\u20132010; [[Indiana University Jacobs School of Music]] horn faculty since 2006\n*[[Giovanni Punto]] \u2013 horn virtuoso and [[hand-stopping]] pioneer, after whom the International Horn Society's annual horn playing award is named, also a violinist, concertmaster, and composer\n*[[David Pyatt]] \u2013 winner of the [[BBC Young Musician of the Year]] competition in 1988 and current principal horn of the [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n*[[Gunther Schuller]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra]] and [[Metropolitan Opera|Metropolitan Opera Orchestra]], and played with [[Miles Davis]]\n*[[Barry Tuckwell]] \u2013 former principal horn of the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] and author of several books on horn playing\n*[[William VerMeulen]] \u2013 horn soloist and former principal horn of [[Honolulu Symphony Orchestra]] current principal Horn of the [[Houston Symphony Orchestra]] and professor at [[Rice University]]\n*[[Radovan Vlatkovi\u0107]] \u2013 1983 winner of the [[ARD International Music Competition]], former principal horn and soloist of the [[Berlin Radio Symphony Orchestra (East Berlin)|Berlin Radio Symphony Orchestra]], and professor at the [[Mozarteum University of Salzburg]]\n*[[Sarah Willis (hornist)|Sarah Willis]] \u2013 first female brass-player in the Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra, US-born, British ambassador for the horn and classical music through television programs such as ''Sarah's Music'' on [[Deutsche Welle]].\n\nPeople who are more notable for their other achievements, but also play the horn, include actors [[Ewan McGregor]] and [[David Ogden Stiers]], comedian and television host [[Jon Stewart]], journalist [[Chuck Todd]], [[The Who]] bassist and singer [[John Entwistle]], and rapper and record producer [[B.o.B]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = A Devil to Play|last = Rees|first = Jasper|publisher = HarperCollins|year = 2009|isbn = |location = }}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:French horn.jpg|<center>A modern full double horn</center>\nFile:Viennese horn.jpg|<center>A [[Vienna horn]]</center>\nFile:Hunting horn 3.jpg|<center>A hunting horn</center>\nFile:Omnitonic horn 2.jpg|<center>A French Omnitonic horn</center>\nFile:Natural Horn (instrument).JPG|<center>A [[natural horn]] at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]]</center>\nFile:Stanford Natural Horn.JPG|<center>A replica of a Mozart-era natural horn</center>\nFile:cordechasse.png|<center>A hunting horn in E{{music|flat}}</center>\nFile:Cor_naturel.JPG|<center>A natural horn</center>\nFile:Three valves horn.jpg|<center>An older, French-made ''cor \u00e0 pistons'' in E{{music|flat}}</center>\nFile:Brain-raoux.jpg|<center>A French-made horn with piston valves</center>\nFile:Dennis-brain-alex.jpg|<center>A horn by Alexander, once owned by Dennis Brain</center>\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of compositions for horn]]\n* [[List of horn makers]]\n* [[List of horn techniques]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikibooks|Horn/Repertoire}}\n{{wikibooks|Horn}}<!-- COMMENT: The {{wikibookspar|horn}} template was screwed up as of the date of this edit. Redirecting [[Wikibooks:Horn (instrument)]] to [[Wikibooks:Horn]] for the time being -->\n<!-- Please think twice about putting links to non-English language Horn societies; those should go on the pages of their respective languages! -->\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Horn (class of wind instruments)}}\n*[http://www.hornsociety.org/ Homepage of the International Horn Society], one of the largest organizations of horn players in the world.\n*[http://www.british-horn.org/ British Horn Society], UK-based organisation for horn playing\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120510062528/http://www.finkehorns.de/Bilder/first-steps.mov First steps of making a horn by hand] (QuickTime Movie) at Finke Horns\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140712070243/http://www.cosmos-club.org/web/journals/1999/bowles.html From mines to music: The venerable valve], by musicologist Edmund A. Bowles\n*[http://www.paxman.co.uk/pages/index.html?http%3A//www.paxman.co.uk/pages/horncentre/hornmaintenance.html Horn maintenance] at Paxman, compiled with the assistance of [[Simon de Souza]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924013143/http://www.finkehorns.de/English/ServiceVentile.html How to dismantle a valve] at Finke Horns\n*[http://www.hornetudes.com Horn Etudes] -  List of horn etudes\n\n{{Musical instruments |state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:French horn}}\n[[Category:Brass instruments]]\n[[Category:F instruments]]\n[[Category:German musical instruments]]\n[[Category:Horns]]\n[[Category:Orchestral instruments]]\n[[Category:Western Classical music instruments]]\n[[Category:Jazz instruments]]\n", "name_user": "24.146.187.232", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_horn"}
{"title_page": "Tom Ridge", "text_new": "{{other people|Thomas Ridge}}\n{{short description|American politician, Pennsylvania governor and Secretary of Homeland Security}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Tom Ridge\n|image        = Tom Ridge.jpg{{!}}border\n|office       = 1st [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security]]\n|president    = [[George W. Bush]]\n|term_start   = January 24, 2003\n|term_end     = February 1, 2005\n|predecessor  = Position established\n|successor    = [[Michael Chertoff]]\n|office1      = 1st [[United States Homeland Security Advisor]]\n|president1   = [[George W. Bush]]\n|term_start1  = September 20, 2001\n|term_end1    = January 24, 2003\n|predecessor1 = Position established\n|successor1   = [[John A. Gordon]]\n|order2       = 43rd [[List of governors of Pennsylvania|Governor of Pennsylvania]]\n|lieutenant2  = Mark Schweiker <!-- Don't add link per MOS:OVERLINK. -->\n|term_start2  = January 17, 1995\n|term_end2    = October 5, 2001\n|predecessor2 = [[Bob Casey Sr.]]\n|successor2   = [[Mark Schweiker]]\n|state3       = [[Pennsylvania]]\n|district3    = {{ushr|PA|21|21st}}\n|term_start3  = January 3, 1983\n|term_end3    = January 3, 1995\n|predecessor3 = [[Donald A. Bailey|Donald Bailey]]\n|successor3   = [[Phil English]]\n|birth_name   = Thomas Joseph Ridge\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1945|8|26|mf=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Munhall, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Michele Ridge\n|children     = 2\n|education    = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|AB]])<br />[[Penn State Dickinson Law]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{army|United States}}\n|rank         = [[File:Army-USA-OR-06.svg|18px|link=|alt=]] [[Staff sergeant]]\n|unit         = Bravo Company, [[20th Infantry Regiment (United States)|1st Battalion, 20th Infantry Regiment]], [[11th Infantry Brigade (United States)|11th Infantry Brigade]], [[23rd Infantry Division (United States)|23rd Infantry Division]]\n|battles      = [[Vietnam War]]\n|mawards      = [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]] (with [[\"V\" device|valor]])<br />\n[[Vietnam Gallantry Cross|Republic of Vietnam Gallantry Cross with Palm]]\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Joseph Ridge''' (born August 26, 1945) is an American politician and author who served as the [[Assistant to the President for Homeland Security]] from 2001 to 2003, and the first [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security]] from 2003 to 2005. Prior to this, Ridge was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1983 to 1995 and the [[List of governors of Pennsylvania|43rd Governor of Pennsylvania]] from 1995 to 2001. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].\n\nRidge was born in [[Munhall, Pennsylvania]] and raised in veterans' public housing in [[Erie, Pennsylvania]]. After graduating from [[Harvard College|Harvard University]] with honors, Ridge served in the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] during the [[Vietnam War]] where he was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]]. He then returned to Pennsylvania and completed his [[Juris Doctor]] (J.D.) degree at the [[Dickinson School of Law]], graduating in 1972, and entered private practice.\n\nAs assistant district attorney in Erie, Ridge ran for Congress [[Pennsylvania's 21st congressional district|in his district]], where he served six terms. He then ran for governor in [[1994 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1994]], despite being little-known outside of northwest Pennsylvania. He won the election, and was reelected in [[1998 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1998]] with the most votes for a Republican governor in Pennsylvania (where Democrats outnumber Republicans by almost 500,000) in more than half a century.<ref name=\"Online NewsHour\">{{cite web |title=Pennsylvania's Tom Ridge Appointed to Bush Cabinet |date=September 20, 2001 |publisher=[[Online NewsHour]] |access-date=May 22, 2005 |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/september01/ridge_bio.html}}</ref> As Governor of Pennsylvania, Ridge is credited for statewide advances in economic development, education, health care and the environment. {{As of|2019}}, Ridge is the last Republican to win re\u00eblection as Pennsylvania's governor.\n\nFollowing the [[September 11, 2001, attacks|September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks]], U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] named Ridge the first director of the newly created [[Office of Homeland Security]]. In January 2003, the Office of Homeland Security became an official [[United States Cabinet|Cabinet]]-level Department, the [[Department of Homeland Security]], and Ridge became the first [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security|Secretary of Homeland Security]]. He served in these roles for Bush's first term as president, then retired and returned to the private sector.\n\nSince re-entering the private sector, Ridge has served on the boards of [[The Home Depot]], [[The Hershey Company]] and [[Exelon Corporation]] and as a senior advisor to [[Deloitte & Touche]], and TechRadium. Ridge is also the founder and CEO of Ridge Global, LLC, a Washington, D.C.-based security consulting firm. Ridge spent time campaigning with Senator [[John McCain]] during his 2008 bid for the presidency and was believed by some to have been on the short list of potential running mates.<ref name=the-trail /><ref name=\"Veep predictions\">{{cite web |last=Wedd |first=Justin |authorlink=Justin Webb |title=Veep predictions |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=BBC |date=August 20, 2008 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thereporters/justinwebb/2008/08/veep_predictions.html |doi= |access-date=August 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRidge was born in [[Munhall, Pennsylvania]] in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]]'s [[Steel Valley (Pittsburgh)|Steel Valley]], the eldest of three children. His parents were Laura (n\u00e9e Sudimack) and Thomas Regis Ridge, who was a traveling salesman and [[United States Navy|Navy]] [[veteran]]. Ridge's maternal grandparents were [[Rusyns|Rusyn]] immigrants<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.simkovich.org/famouscarpathorussians.htm/|title=A FEW FAMOUS CARPATHO-RUSSIANS|publisher=|access-date=July 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623212052/http://www.simkovich.org/famouscarpathorussians.htm|archive-date=2015-06-23|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> from the former [[Czechoslovakia]] (now [[Slovakia]]), and his paternal great-grandparents emigrated from [[Great Britain]].<ref name=\"growingup\">{{cite news |last=Palattella |first=Ed |author2=Scott Wescott |title=Growing Up: Ridge's journey begins |date=January 21, 2003 |work=[[Erie Times-News]] |url=http://www.goerie.com/risingson/growing_up.html |access-date=August 20, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827223906/http://www.goerie.com/risingson/growing_up.html |archivedate=August 27, 2008 |df= }}</ref> Ridge was raised in veterans' public housing in [[Erie, Pennsylvania]]. He was educated at St. Andrews Elementary School and [[Cathedral Preparatory School]] and did well both academically and in sports. He attended [[Harvard College]], where he paid his way through with construction work, played [[intramural sports|intramural]] baseball and football,<ref name=\"growingup\"/> and graduated with honors in 1967. In 1968, after his first year at the [[Dickinson School of Law]], he was drafted into the [[United States Army]].\n\n===Military service===\n{{BLP sources section|date=June 2017}}\nIn November 1969, Ridge arrived as a sergeant in [[South Vietnam]] where he would serve for six months as a [[Staff sergeant#United States Military|staff sergeant]] with Bravo Company, [[20th Infantry Regiment (United States)|1st Battalion, 20th Infantry]], [[11th Infantry Brigade (United States)|11th Infantry Brigade]], [[23rd Infantry Division (United States)|23rd Infantry Division]] (Americal Division)<ref>[http://www.militaryvetshop.com/History/americal.html History of the 23rd Infantry Division], Militaryvetshop.com; retrieved July 12, 2013.</ref> during the [[Vietnam War]].\n\nIn May 1970, a ruptured [[Vermiform appendix|appendix]] cut short his tour of duty in Vietnam and he was sent home; his service also aggravated a childhood [[ear infection]] which caused him afterwards to have a [[hearing aid]] in his left ear.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Orin |first1=Deborah |title=TOM\u2019S TREMENDOUS TASK |url=https://nypost.com/2001/09/22/toms-tremendous-task/ |website=nypost.com |publisher=NYP HOLDINGS, INC. |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nFor his service in Vietnam, Ridge received the [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]] with [[\"V\" Device]], [[National Defense Service Medal]], [[Vietnam Service Medal]], [[Vietnam Gallantry Cross|Republic of Vietnam Gallantry Cross with palm]], [[Vietnam Gallantry Cross|Republic of Vietnam Gallantry Cross Unit Citation with Palm]], [[Vietnam Campaign Medal|Republic of Vietnam Campaign Medal]], and the [[Combat Infantryman Badge]]. He was later offered a commission as an [[Military officer|officer]] but turned it down.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nAfter returning to [[Pennsylvania]], he completed his [[Juris Doctor]] (J.D.) degree at the Dickinson School of Law, graduating in 1972, and entered private practice.<ref>{{cite web |title=First Homeland Security secretary to deliver Dickinson Law Commencement address |url=https://news.psu.edu/story/564732/2019/03/21/first-homeland-security-secretary-deliver-dickinson-law-commencement-address |website=psu.edu |publisher=The Pennsylvania State University |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Public Service in Pennsylvania ==\n\n[[File:Congressman Tom Ridge.jpg|thumb|right|Congressman Ridge during the [[104th Congress]]]]\n\n[[File:Reagan Contact Sheet C45187 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Ridge with [[President of the United States|President]] [[Ronald Reagan]] in 1988]]\n\n[[File:Bush Contact Sheet P16288 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Ridge with [[President of the United States|President]] [[George H. W. Bush]] and [[United States Senator]] [[John McCain]] in 1990]]\n\nRidge became assistant district attorney in [[Erie County, Pennsylvania]] in 1980 and prosecuted 86 cases in two years. In 1982 he won a seat in Congress from [[Pennsylvania's 21st congressional district|northwestern Pennsylvania]] by the margin of only 729 votes,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Barone |first1=Michael |author-link1=Michael Barone (pundit) |last2=Ujifusa |first2=Grant |title=[[The Almanac of American Politics]] 1988|publisher=[[National Journal]] |year=1987 |page=1054}}</ref> and was re-elected six times. Ridge was notable as the first enlisted [[Vietnam]] combat veteran elected to the U.S. House. Ridge never lost an election for public office.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nIn [[1994 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1994]], despite being little-known outside of northwest Pennsylvania, Ridge ran for [[List of governors of Pennsylvania|Governor]]. He won the election as a [[pro-choice]] [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]. He was re\u00eblected in [[1998 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1998]] with 57 percent of the vote in a four-way race. His share of the vote in that election was the highest for a Republican governor in Pennsylvania (where Democrats outnumber Republicans by almost 500,000) in more than half a century.<ref name=\"Online NewsHour\"/> Ridge served as governor until his resignation to become the Director of Homeland Security in 2001.<ref name=\"chooses\">{{cite web |last1=Marquis |first1=Christopher |title=A Nation Challenged: Homeland Security; Bush Chooses Old Ally For Cabinet-Level Post |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/21/us/nation-challenged-homeland-security-bush-chooses-old-ally-for-cabinet-level-post.html |website=nytimes.com |publisher=The New York Times Company |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOne of Ridge's more controversial actions as governor was his nomination of [[Peter J. Jannetta]] to be the [[Pennsylvania Department of Health|State Secretary of Health]]. Jannetta had previously been accused of committing perjury, with the [[Pennsylvania Superior Court|State's Superior Court]] stating, \"We have little difficulty in concluding that Dr. Jannetta's testimony at deposition was different than, or inconsistent with, the testimony at trial\". Jannetta was not, however, ever convicted of perjury.<ref>Levy v Jannetta, CCP Allegheny County, GD 81-7689; appeal -J. A370017/92 Levy v Jannetta et al., No. 00150 Pittsburgh, 1992. Settled, 1995.\"</ref> Jannetta served as Health Secretary for six months.<ref>[http://cnsnews.com/news/article/grand-jury-under-pro-abort-gop-governor-pennsylvania-stopped-annual-inspections \"Grand Jury: Under Pro-Abort GOP Governor, Pennsylvania Stopped Annual Inspections of Abortion Clinics\"], ''CNS News'', April 16, 2013.</ref>\n\nDuring his time as governor, Ridge promoted \"[[law and order (politics)|law and order]]\" policies, supporting a [[three-strikes law]] and a faster [[capital punishment|death penalty]] process. A death penalty supporter,<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Ridge on the Issues |publisher=[[On the Issues]]|year=2000|access-date=February 28, 2008|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Tom_Ridge.htm}}</ref> Ridge signed more than 224 execution warrants<ref>{{cite web|title=Execution Warrants Issued by Governor (1985 to Present)|publisher=[[Pennsylvania Department of Corrections]]|format=PDF|date=August 19, 2008|access-date=February 28, 2008|url=http://www.cor.state.pa.us/portal/lib/portal/Warrants_by_Governor.pdf}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 five times the number signed over a 25-year period by the two previous governors&nbsp;\u2013 but [[List of people executed in Pennsylvania|only three voluntary executions were carried out]]. On social issues, he opposed [[gay marriage]] but is [[pro-choice]] on [[abortion]] issues.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tom Ridge on the Issues |url=https://www.ontheissues.org/Tom_Ridge.htm |website=ontheissues.org |publisher=OnTheIssues.org |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOver Ridge's tenure, the Commonwealth's budget grew by two to three percent per fiscal year and combined tax reductions totaled over $2 billion. Ridge created and grew a \"Rainy Day\" Fund balance to over $1 billion to be utilized during an economic downturn or recession.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ridge |url=https://www.ausa.org/sites/default/files/Ridge.pdf |website=ausa.org |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nRidge pushed for legislation permitting competition among electric utilities and enhanced federal and state support for the Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP). He separated the Commonwealth's environmental regulatory and conservation programs into two new agencies; the Department of Environmental Protection and the Department of Conservation and Natural Resources.<ref>{{cite web |title=Conservation and Natural Resources Act, House Bill 1400, Regular Session 1995\u20131996 |url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/billinfo/billinfo.cfm?syear=1995&sind=0&body=H&type=B&bn=1400 |website=Pennsylvania General Assembly |access-date=December 1, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nRidge proposed the creation of public [[charter schools]] in Pennsylvania and in establishing alternate schools for disruptive students. He launched new academic standards that established academic expectations for what students were expected to know in different grades. He proposed a school choice demonstration program.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nRidge oversaw a number of e-government projects including renewing drivers' licenses and vehicle registrations to viewing historical documents and library catalogs. The Commonwealth's portal won several national awards. One of the nation's first electronic grant systems was put into place at the Pennsylvania Department of Education. He created the [http://www.l2l.org/ Link-to-Learn] initiative to increase the effective use of technology in public schools and universities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ridge |url=https://www.ausa.org/sites/default/files/Ridge.pdf |website=ausa.org |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, he was named runner up \"Politician of the Year\" by [[PoliticsPA]].<ref name=poloftheyear2001>{{cite web|title=Sy Snyder's Politician of the Year 2001|work=[[PoliticsPA]]|publisher=The Publius Group|year=2001|url=http://www.politicspa.com/FEATURES/pol_of_the_year.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020803100256/http://www.politicspa.com/FEATURES/pol_of_the_year.htm|archive-date=August 3, 2002|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2002 [[PoliticsPA]] [[Feature story]] designating politicians with [[Yearbook|yearbook superlatives]], he was named the \"Most Popular.\"<ref name=yearbook>{{cite web|title=Keystone State Yearbook Committee|work=[[PoliticsPA]]|publisher=The Publius Group|year=2001|url=http://www.politicspa.com/yearbookcommittee.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020803170058/http://www.politicspa.com/yearbookcommittee.htm|archive-date=August 3, 2002|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nRidge signed two death warrants for African-American civil rights activist [[Mumia Abu-Jamal]], who was convicted of killing a police officer at a traffic stop.<ref>{{cite web | last=Yohn | first=William H., Jr. | title=Memorandum and Order | work=Mumia Abu-Jamal, Petitioner, vs. Martin Horn, Commissioner, Pennsylvania Department of Corrections, et al., Respondents | publisher=US District Court for the Eastern District of Philadelphia |date=December 2001 | url=http://www.paed.uscourts.gov/documents/opinions/01D0951P.pdf | format=PDF | access-date=2008-01-22}}</ref>\n\n==2000 Presidential election==\n[[File:President George W. Bush shakes hands with Governor Tom Ridge.jpg|thumb|right|Ridge greeting [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]] in 2001]]\nRidge was a potential running mate for [[1996 United States presidential election#gopvp|Bob Dole in 1996]], and served as a close advisor to GOP presidential nominee [[George W. Bush]], a close friend from their simultaneous tenures as governors, during the 2000 presidential campaign. In return, Bush named Ridge to his short list for possible running mates, along with [[Governor of New York|New York Governor]] [[George Pataki]], [[List of governors of Michigan|Michigan Governor]] [[John Engler]], [[Governor of Oklahoma|Oklahoma Governor]] [[Frank Keating]], former Missouri Senator [[John Danforth]], and former [[American Red Cross]] President [[Elizabeth Dole]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Starr|first=Alexandra|title=Running Mates: Who will be on the ticket in 2000?|date=July\u2013August 1999|journal=[[Washington Monthly]]|volume=31|issue=7|access-date=September 22, 2005|url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/1999/9907.starr.campaign.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000305010318/http://washingtonmonthly.com/features/1999/9907.starr.campaign.html|archivedate=March 5, 2000|df=}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[September 11, 2001, attacks|September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks]], U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] created the [[Office of Homeland Security]] within the White House, and named Ridge to head it. The charge to the nation's new director of homeland security was to develop and coordinate a comprehensive national strategy to strengthen the United States against terrorist threats or attacks. Ridge formally resigned as Pennsylvania's governor on October 5, 2001.<ref name=\"chooses\" />\n\nIn January 2003 and after the passage of the Homeland Security Act of 2002, the Office of Homeland Security split into a [[United States Cabinet|Cabinet]]-level Department, the [[Department of Homeland Security]], and the White House [[Homeland Security Advisory Council]]. Ridge left the White House and became the first [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security|Secretary of Homeland Security]]. The department's mission \"is to (A) prevent terrorist attacks within the United States; (B) reduce the vulnerability of the United States to terrorism; and (C) minimize the damage, and assist in the recovery, from terrorist attacks that do occur within the United States\" (From H.R. 5005-8 the Homeland Security Act of 2002). The newly created Department was the most comprehensive reorganization of the Federal government since the [[National Security Act of 1947]].\n\nThe Department of Homeland Security consolidates 22 agencies and 180,000 employees, unifying once-fragmented Federal functions in a single agency dedicated to protecting America from terrorism. Ridge worked with the employees from combined agencies to strengthen borders, provide for intelligence analysis and infrastructure protection, improve the use of science and technology to counter weapons of mass destruction, and to create a comprehensive response and recovery division.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/1556612.stm Profile of Tom Ridge], bbc.co.uk, November 9, 2004.</ref><ref>[https://www.npr.org/news/specials/response/home_front/features/2001/oct/ridge.html Security Chief Ridge: 'The Task is Enormous'], NPR.org, October 8, 2001.</ref><ref>[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/fedagencies/jan-june02/ridge_5-9.html Newsmaker: Tom Ridge], Online NewsHour, May 9, 2002.</ref><ref>[http://www.time.com/time/pow/article/0,8599,393066,00.html Person of the Week: Tom Ridge. Now for the hard part: After a week in which the Senate gave him a cabinet-level position, the Homeland Security chief is preparing to take on the toughest job in Washington], Time.com, November 22, 2002.</ref><ref>[http://www.goerie.com/risingson Ridge's journey to the national stage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040101142617/http://www.goerie.com/risingson/ |date=2004-01-01 }}, goerie.com; updated January 21, 2003.</ref>\n\nIn January 2004, Ridge was named among others in a lawsuit filed by a Syrian-born Canadian [[Maher Arar]] who said he was tortured in Syria after being deported by American authorities.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian sues US over deportation|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/3421743.stm|date=January 23, 2004|work=news.bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC News|access-date=September 13, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn November 30, 2004, Ridge submitted his resignation to the President, saying, \"After more than 22 consecutive years of public service, it is time to give personal and family matters a higher priority.\"<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,3-1382726,00.html Anti-terror supremo is latest to quit Bush team], timesonline.co.uk, December 1, 2004.</ref>\n\nIn his book ''The Test of Our Times: America Under Siege...and How We Can Be Safe Again'', Ridge says his resignation was due to an effort by senior Bush administration officials to raise the nation's terror alert level in the days before the 2004 presidential vote.<ref name=\"cnnticker\">{{cite news|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/08/20/ridge-i-fought-raising-security-level-before-04-vote|title=Ridge: I fought raising security level before '04 vote|date=August 20, 2009|work=Political Ticker|publisher=CNN|access-date=August 21, 2009}}</ref><ref name=Bedard>Bedard, Paul. \"[https://www.usnews.com/blogs/washington-whispers/2009/08/19/tom-ridge-on-national-security-after-911.html Tom Ridge on National Security After 9/11]\", U.S. News & World Report, August 19, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Work in the private sector==\nRidge is the founder and CEO of Ridge Global, an advisory firm in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite news|first=Katherine|last=Walsh|title=Five Things Tom Ridge Has Learned About Risk|url=http://www.cio.com/article/149601/Five_Things_Tom_Ridge_Has_Learned_About_Risk|work=CIO magazine|publisher=[[CXO Media]]|date=October 29, 2007|access-date=November 10, 2007}}</ref>\n\nRidge served on a state-appointed incident review panel that investigated the [[Virginia Tech shooting]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Va. Tech gunman was 'well-prepared' to continue shooting spree|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2007-05-21-va-tech-probe_N.htm|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=May 21, 2007|access-date=November 10, 2007}}</ref>\n\nRidge also sits on the [https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/ Atlantic Council's]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/about/board-of-directors/|title=Board of Directors|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> Board of Directors. \n\n===RIDGE-LANE Limited Partners===\nRidge is a co-founder, along with investment banker R. Brad Lane,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ridge-lane.com/team/r-brad-lane|title=R. Brad Lane|publisher=RIDGE-LANE Limited Partners|access-date=January 23, 2018}}</ref> of RIDGE-LANE Limited and RIDGE-LANE Capital, a merchant-bank that sponsors [[urban development]] projects, [[public\u2013private partnership]]s (P3) and [[economic development]] programs, as well as [[corporate development]] services for private technology companies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ridge-lane.com|publisher=RIDGE-LANE Limited Partners|access-date=April 17, 2017|title=RIDGE-LANE Limited Partners|website=ridge-lane.com}}</ref>\n\n===Ridge Policy Group===\nIn 2010, Ridge's two former Chiefs of Staff, Mark Campbell and Mark Holman, opened a lobbying firm after Ridge lent the firm his name.  The full-service government affairs firm has offices in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, and Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mcall.com/news/nationworld/pennsylvania/mc-pa-wolf-dc-lobbying-firm-20150603-story.html |title= PA Gov. Tom Wolf administration hires new D.C. lobbying firm |date=June 3, 2015 |first=Laura |last=Olson |newspaper=The Morning Call }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Former Gov. Ridge lending name, clout to new Harrisburg-D.C. lobbying firm|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/harrisburg_politics/Former_Gov_Ridge_lending_name_clout_to_new_Harrisburg-DC_lobbying_firm.html|publisher=philly.com|access-date=January 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, companies seeking to use [[hydraulic fracturing]] to extract [[natural gas]] from the [[Marcellus Formation|Marcellus Shale formation]] engaged Ridge and Ridge Policy Group at $75,000 a month to help them gain support.<ref>{{cite web|last=Associated Press|authorlink=Associated Press|title=Ex-Homeland Security boss joins gas drilling group|publisher=[[Google News]]|date=July 30, 2010|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5iYhHpjTFHgYX9J7VAxVs2oAyQc3wD9H9IGA80|access-date=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Home Depot===\nIn February 2005, Tom Ridge was named to the board of [[Home Depot]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Company News; Home Depot Names Tom Ridge a Director|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F04E1D6173DF936A15751C0A9639C8B63&n=Top/News/Business/Companies/Home%20Depot%20Inc. |newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 25, 2005|access-date=November 10, 2007}}</ref> Ridge's compensation was expected to be about $100,000 per annum for this position.<ref>{{cite news|title=Board work can be rewarding|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2003/10/13/story7.html?page=2|publisher=Atlanta Business Chronicle|date=October 10, 2003|access-date=November 10, 2007|first=Meredith|last=Jordan}}</ref> Since April 2005, Ridge served on the board of [[Savi Technology]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Ridge Joins Savi Technology Board of Directors|url=http://www.rfidupdate.com/articles/index.php?id=844 |publisher=RFID Update|date=April 8, 2005|access-date=November 10, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071003163736/http://www.rfidupdate.com/articles/index.php?id=844|archive-date=October 3, 2007}}</ref> the primary technology provider for the wireless cargo-monitoring network for the [[United States Department of Defense]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.savi.com/company/ov.fact.shtml|title=Savi Fact Sheet|access-date=November 10, 2007|work=Corporate website|publisher=Savi Technology|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012200425/http://savi.com/company/ov.fact.shtml|archive-date=October 12, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Exelon Corporation===\nIn April, 2005, Ridge's appointment to the board of the Illinois/Pennsylvania/New Jersey electric utility was announced, with starting director compensation of $35,000 annual retainer plus a $1,500 meeting fee or per diem fee. Directors were also granted $60,000 in deferred stock units each year at that time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/news.pl?id=16295 |title=Ex-Homeland Sec. joins Exelon board |first=Gregory |last=Meyer |newspaper=[[Crain's Chicago Business]] |date=April 27, 2005 |access-date=February 19, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, it was reported that Ridge had appeared on [[MSNBC]] ''Hardball With [[Chris Matthews]]'' promoting [[Nuclear power|nuclear energy]] as part of a \"green agenda [to] ... create jobs, create exports,\" without any revelation by him or the [[cable channel]] of his Exelon position. In the report, his cumulative Exelon-derived compensation was put at $530,659; and it was said that, as of March 2009, he held an estimated $248,299 in Exelon stock, according to SEC filings. Exelon was described as \"the nation's largest nuclear power company.\"<ref>Sebastian Jones, [http://www.thenation.com/doc/20100301/jones/print \"The Media-Lobbying Complex\"], ''The Nation'', February 11, 2010 (March 1, 2010 edition of magazine)</ref><ref>[http://www.fair.org/index.php?page=4017 Radio interview with SJones], fair.org, February 19, 2010.</ref>\n\n===Deloitte LLP===\nIn November 2006, Tom Ridge was announced as a senior advisor for [[Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu|Deloitte & Touche]] USA LLP.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fcw.com/articles/2006/11/02/ridge-joins-deloitte.aspx |title=Ridge joins Deloitte |access-date=March 13, 2014 |date=November 2, 2006 |work=Federal Computer Week |publisher=Media, Inc. }}</ref>\n\n===The Hershey Company===\nIn November 2007, Ridge was named to serve on [[The Hershey Company]]'s Executive Board. The Hershey Trust, the primary shareholder of Hershey, asked for a change in board composition after several years of poor stock performance. The board named Ridge to the board for his knowledge of economics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/patriotnews/article294464.ece|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120910042853/http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/patriotnews/article294464.ece|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 10, 2012|title=Big changes at Hershey|publisher=|access-date=July 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===TechRadium Inc===\nAnnounced in January 2008, Tom Ridge will serve as a senior advisor to TechRadium, Inc., a Texas-based security technology company that provides its patented alert and notification\nsystem, IRIS (Immediate Response Information System), to a wide range of users\nincluding municipalities, public schools and universities, utilities, and military programs.<ref>{{cite news|first= |last= |authorlink= |title=Tom Ridge to Advise TechRadium On 'IRIS' Technology |url=http://www.securityinfowatch.com/article/10545958/tom-ridge-to-advise-techradium-on-iris-technology |publisher=Security InfoWatch |date=January 9, 2008 |access-date=April 25, 2016 |agency=PRNewswire }}</ref>\n\n===PURE Bioscience===\nIn September 2009, PURE Bioscience, creator of a patented [[antimicrobial]], announced Ridge would serve on its advisory board along with former [[Governor of Wisconsin|Wisconsin governor]] [[Tommy Thompson]].<ref>{{cite news |title=PURE Bioscience Forms Advisory Panel Tom Ridge, Tommy G. Thompson Among Inaugural Members |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/PURE-Bioscience-Forms-bw-3403647171.html?x=0&.v=1 |website=Finance.yahoo.com |date=September 1, 2009 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n\n==Political activity==\n\n===2008 Presidential election===\nTom Ridge served as a senior aide to Republican Presidential candidate Senator [[John McCain]] of Arizona,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebulletin.us/site/news.cfm?newsid=19241247&BRD=2737&PAG=461&dept_id=618959&rfi=6 |title=Ridge A Leading Candidate For McCain VP Role? |publisher=The Bulletin |access-date=January 31, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207233444/http://www.thebulletin.us/site/news.cfm?newsid=19241247&BRD=2737&PAG=461&dept_id=618959&rfi=6 |archivedate=February 7, 2016 |df= }}</ref> and was considered by some as a possible running mate for McCain.<ref name=the-trail>{{cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/the-trail/2008/08/11/mccain_campaigns_with_ridge_as.html |title=McCain Campaigns with Ridge as VP Speculation Intensifies |access-date=August 12, 2008 |work=The Trail |publisher=The Washington Post |date=August 11, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Veep predictions\" /> [[File:TomRidgePodium-McCainRallyWashingtonPA2008.jpg|thumb|alt=Ridge at McCain Palin rally |Tom Ridge at rally for John McCain]]\n\n===Possible 2010 Senate candidacy===\nAccording to [[Fox News]], many Republicans hoped Ridge would run for the [[United States Senate]] against the newly turned Democrat [[Arlen Specter]], who stated he would seek [[United States Senate election in Pennsylvania, 2010|re-election in 2010]] in the Democratic primary.  Already seeking the Republican nomination was former [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] [[Pat Toomey]], who narrowly lost to Specter in the Republican primary in 2004. Some Republicans thought Ridge would have a better chance against Specter than would Toomey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lehighvalleylive.com/jessica-coomes/index.ssf/2009/05/poll_arlen_specter_would_top_p.html|title=Poll: Arlen Specter would top Pat Toomey, Tom Ridge in general election|publisher=|access-date=July 1, 2017}}</ref> A [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute]] poll conducted between April 30, 2009 and May 3, 2009 placed Ridge within three points of Specter in a hypothetical matchup between the two men.<ref>{{cite news |title=Poll says Specter holds 20-point edge over Toomey: A run by former Gov. Ridge would boost GOP's chances|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/09124/967593-100.stm|work=post-gazette.com |publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=May 4, 2009|access-date=June 19, 2009}}</ref>\n\nSome Toomey supporters criticized the idea of a Ridge candidacy because, although Ridge was still registered to vote in Pennsylvania, he was actually living in [[Chevy Chase, Maryland]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Micek| first=John L.|title=Whither Tom Ridge?| newspaper=[[The Morning Call]]|date=May 7, 2009|url=http://blogs.mcall.com/capitol_ideas/2009/05/whither-tom-ridge.html|access-date=May 7, 2009}}</ref> On May 7, 2009, Ridge announced that he would not be a candidate for the U.S. Senate in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ridge Says He Won't Seek Specter's Senate Seat|publisher=[[WFMZ-TV]]|date=May 7, 2009|url=http://wfmz.com/view/?id=893773|archive-url=https://archive.today/20110809102716/http://wfmz.com/view/?id=893773|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 9, 2011|access-date=May 7, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===2012 Presidential election===\nRidge originally endorsed former [[List of governors of Utah|Utah Governor]] [[Jon Huntsman, Jr.|Jon Huntsman]] for president, in September 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/tom-ridge-jon-huntsman-new-hampshire-mitt-romney-2012-election_n_1185985 |title=Jon Huntsman Backer Tom Ridge Sets High Bar For Mitt Romney In New Hampshire |newspaper=HuffPost |first=Sam |last=Stein |date=January 5, 2012 |access-date=August 27, 2019 }}</ref> [[Mitt Romney]] announced an endorsement from Ridge on March 14, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/03/14/tom-ridge-endorses-mitt-romney_n_1344252.html|title=Tom Ridge Endorses Mitt Romney|newspaper=The Huffington Post|first=Elise|last=Foley|date=March 14, 2012|access-date=March 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Supreme Court brief===\nIn 2013, Ridge was a signatory to an ''[[amicus curiae]]'' brief submitted to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] in support of [[same-sex marriage]] during the ''[[Hollingsworth v. Perry]]'' case.<ref>[http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/02/28/the-pro-freedom-republicans-are-coming-131-sign-gay-marriage-brief.html The Pro-Freedom Republicans Are Coming: 131 Sign Gay Marriage Brief]. The Daily Beast (February 28, 2013). Retrieved on July 12, 2013.</ref>\n\n===Support for the People's Mujahedin of Iran===\nRidge spoke at a conference in support of the removal of the [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]] (MEK, also PMOI, MKO) from the [[United States State Department list of Foreign Terrorist Organizations]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mojahedin.org/linksen/1541 |website=mojahedi.org |title=Governor Tom Ridge call on Obama to protect Iranian dissidents in Iraq |access-date=July 1, 2017 |date=November 21, 2013 }}</ref> The group was listed on the State Department list from 1997 until September 2012. They were placed on the list for killing six Americans in Iran during the 1970s and attempting to attack the Iranian mission to the United Nations in 1992.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/09/28/politics/mek-terror-delisting/index.html|title=Iranian exile group removed from U.S. terror list|author=CNN Wire Staff|publisher=CNN|access-date=July 1, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929031444/http://www.cnn.com/2012/09/28/politics/mek-terror-delisting/index.html|archive-date=September 29, 2012|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2012/09/198443.htm |title=Delisting of the Mujahedin-e Khalq |publisher=U.S. Department of State |date=September 28, 2012 }}</ref> Ridge, along with other former government officials and politicians [[Ed Rendell]], [[R. James Woolsey]], [[Porter Goss]], [[Louis Freeh]], [[Michael Mukasey]], [[James L. Jones]], [[Rudy Giuliani]], and [[Howard Dean]], were criticized for their involvement with the group. Some were subpoenaed during an inquiry about who was paying the prominent individuals' speaking fees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/13/us/us-supporters-of-iranian-group-mek-face-scrutiny.html|title=U.S. Supporters of Iranian Group M.E.K. Face Scrutiny|first=Scott|last=Shane|date=March 13, 2012|publisher=|access-date=July 1, 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Ridge and others wrote an article for the conservative publication ''[[National Review]]'' stating their position that the group should not be classified as a terrorist organization, raising the point that, at the time, only the United States and Iran still listed it as a terrorist group.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/256689/mek-not-terrorist-group-michael-b-mukasey-tom-ridge-and-frances-fragos-townsend |title=MEK is Not a Terrorist Group |date=January 1, 2011 |magazine=National Review |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111174147/http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/256689/mek-not-terrorist-group-michael-b-mukasey-tom-ridge-and-frances-fragos-townsend |archive-date=January 11, 2011 |last1=Mukasey |first1=Michael B |author-link1=Michael Mukasey |last2=Ridge |first2=Tom |last3=Giuliani |first3=Rudolph W |author-link3=Rudy Giuliani |last4=Townsend |first4=Frances Fragos |author-link4=Frances Townsend}}</ref>\n\n===2015 Blue Ribbon Commission===\n[[File:Shalala, Ridge, Lieberman, Wainstein, Greenwood at the Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense.jpg|thumb|[[Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense]] (Ridge 2nd from left)]]\nIn 2015, Ridge served as co-chair of the [[Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense]], a commission that recommended changes to U.S. policy regarding biodefense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biodefensestudy.org/|title=Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense|website=www.biodefensestudy.org|access-date=January 20, 2017}}</ref> In order to address biological threats facing the nation, the Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense created a 33-step initiative for the U.S. Government to implement. Tom Ridge headed the organization with former Senator Joe Lieberman, and the Study Panel assembled in Washington D.C. for four meetings concerning current biodefense programs. The Study Panel concluded that the federal government had little to no defense mechanisms in case of a biological event. The Study Panel's final report, ''The National Blueprint for Biodefense'', proposes a string of solutions and recommendations for the U.S. Government to take, including items such as giving the vice president authority over biodefense responsibilities and merging the entire biodefense budget. These solutions represent the Panel's call to action in order to increase awareness and activity for pandemic related issues.\n\n===2016 Presidential election===\nIn 2016, Ridge endorsed [[Jeb Bush]] and subsequently [[John Kasich]] after Bush's withdrawal from the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 Republican presidential primaries]]. Ridge stated he would not endorse [[Donald Trump]], following Trump becoming the [[presumptive nominee]], or [[Hillary Clinton]] in the general election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Struck|first1=Jules|title=Ridge Refuses to Support Trump|url=http://www.politicspa.com/ridge-refuses-to-support-trump/75505/|access-date=May 18, 2016|agency=PoliticsPA|date=May 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Memoir==\nTom Ridge's book ''The Test of Our Times'' was published in September 2009.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Test of Our Times |last=Ridge |first=Tom |author2=Bloom, Larry |year=2009 |publisher=Thomas Dunne Books |isbn=978-0-312-53487-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/testofourtimesam00ridg |access-date=February 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |df= |url-access=registration }}</ref> Written with Larry Bloom, it concerns Ridge's time as the head of the Department of Homeland Security. He explains the challenges and decision making processes of the newly formed department, and gives his own views as to the future of the security of the United States of America. The book further discusses\n\n{{quote|the infighting he saw that frustrated his attempts to build a smooth-running department. Among the headlines promoted by publisher [[Thomas Dunne Books]]: Ridge was never invited to sit in on National Security Council meetings; was 'blindsided' by the FBI in morning Oval Office meetings because the agency withheld critical information from him; found his urgings to block [[Michael D. Brown|Michael Brown]] from being named head of the emergency agency blamed for the Hurricane Katrina disaster ignored; and was pushed to raise the security alert on the eve of President Bush's re-election, something he saw as politically motivated and worth resigning over.<ref name=Bedard/>}}\n\nRidge wrote in his memoir that then-Secretary of Defense [[Donald Rumsfeld]] and then-Attorney General [[John Ashcroft]] pressured him to raise the [[Homeland Security Advisory System|terror alert level]], running up to the 2004 elections, because of a pre-election message critical of President Bush from [[Osama bin Laden|Osama Bin Laden]].<ref name=cnnticker/>\n\n==Recognition==\n{{BLP sources section|date=June 2017}}\n[[File:DHS celebrates 15 years (39848640424).jpg|thumb|Ridge with [[Kirstjen Nielsen]], [[John F. Kelly|John Kelly]], and [[Michael Chertoff]] in 2018]]\n* Presented with the [[Woodrow Wilson Awards|Woodrow Wilson Award]] by the [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ridge |url=https://www.ausa.org/sites/default/files/Ridge.pdf |website=ausa.org |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Erie International Airport]] was co-named ''Tom Ridge Field'' in honor of Ridge.\n* The [[Tom Ridge Environmental Center]] at [[Presque Isle State Park]] in [[Erie, Pennsylvania]] is named after the former governor. Ridge was instrumental in securing funds for the center.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ridge |url=https://www.ausa.org/sites/default/files/Ridge.pdf |website=ausa.org |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n* His picture hangs in the [[moot court]] room at the [[The Pennsylvania State University&nbsp;\u2014 Dickinson School of Law|Penn State Dickinson School of Law]] in [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania]].\n* [[Presque Isle Downs]] in [[Erie, Pennsylvania]] runs the $100,000 Tom Ridge Stakes every meet.\n* [[Mercyhurst University]] named its Tom Ridge College of Intelligence Studies and Applied Science after the first U.S. Secretary of Homeland Security.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mercyhurst.edu/news/mercyhurst-dedicates-new-intel-school-named-after-gov-tom-ridge|title=Mercyhurst dedicates new intel school named after Gov. Tom Ridge|date=April 11, 2014|access-date=May 25, 2015|publisher=Mercyhurst University }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTom's wife, Michele Ridge, is the former executive director of the [[Erie County, Pennsylvania|Erie County]] Library System. Married since 1979, they have two children: Lesley and Tommy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Profile: Tom Ridge|author=BBC News|work=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/1556612.stm|date=November 9, 2004}}</ref>\n\nRidge was hospitalized in critical condition in Texas after a cardiac event on November 16, 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/11/16/ex-homeland-security-secretary-tom-ridge-hospitalized.html |title=Ex-Homeland Security Secretary Tom Ridge hospitalized |date=November 16, 2017 |access-date=November 16, 2017 |publisher=Fox News |agency=Associated Press }}</ref>\n\n==Gubernatorial electoral history==\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1994 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1994 Pennsylvania Gubernatorial Election]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1994&off=5&elect=0&fips=42&f=0|title=US Election Atlas: 1994|publisher=|access-date=July 1, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Tom Ridge\n  |votes      = 1,627,976\n  |percentage = 45.40\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = [[Mark Singel]]\n  |votes      = 1,430,099\n  |percentage = 39.89\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Constitution Party (US)\n  |candidate  = [[Peg Luksik]]\n  |votes      = 460,269\n  |percentage = 12.84\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1998 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1998 Pennsylvania Gubernatorial Election]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1998&fips=42&f=0&off=5&elect=0|title=US Election Atlas: 1998|publisher=|access-date=July 1, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Tom Ridge (incumbent)\n  |votes      = 1,736,844\n  |percentage = 57.42\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = [[Ivan Itkin]]\n  |votes      = 938,745\n  |percentage = 31.03\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Constitution Party (US)\n  |candidate  = [[Peg Luksik]]\n  |votes      = 315,761\n  |percentage = 10.44\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Libertarian Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Ken V. Krawchuk\n  |votes      = 33,591\n  |percentage = 1.10\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n{{CongLinks |congbio = R000243}}\n* {{C-SPAN|thomasridge}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Donald A. Bailey|Donald Bailey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Pennsylvania|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br />from [[Pennsylvania's 21st congressional district]]|years=1983\u20131995}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Phil English]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Barbara Hafer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of governors of Pennsylvania|Governor of Pennsylvania]]|years=[[1994 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1994]], [[1998 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1998]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[D. Michael Fisher|Michael Fisher]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Gilmore]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Republican Governors Association]]|years=2001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John G. Rowland]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert P. Casey|Robert Casey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of governors of Pennsylvania|Governor of Pennsylvania]]|years=1995\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mark S. Schweiker|Mark Schweiker]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|rows=2|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Homeland Security Advisor]]|years=2001\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John A. Gordon|John Gordon]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of Homeland Security]]|years=2003\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michael Chertoff]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors and Presidents of Pennsylvania}}\n{{USSecDHS}}\n{{Home Depot}}\n{{GW Bush cabinet}}\n{{Homeland Security Advisors}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 98th\u2013103rd [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[United States congressional delegations from Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]]}}\n{{USCongRep/PA/98}}\n{{USCongRep/PA/99}}\n{{USCongRep/PA/100}}\n{{USCongRep/PA/101}}\n{{USCongRep/PA/102}}\n{{USCongRep/PA/103}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ridge, Tom}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:American people of British descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Rusyn descent]]\n[[Category:Dickinson School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:George W. Bush administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Governors of Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Harvard Institute of Politics]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Republicans]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Chevy Chase, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Erie, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Munhall, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:The Home Depot people]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of Homeland Security]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Thomas Ridge}}\n{{short description|American politician, Pennsylvania governor and Secretary of Homeland Security}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Tom Ridge\n|image        = Tom Ridge.jpg{{!}}border\n|office       = 1st [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security]]\n|president    = [[George W. Bush]]\n|term_start   = January 24, 2003\n|term_end     = February 1, 2005\n|predecessor  = Position established\n|successor    = [[Michael Chertoff]]\n|office1      = 1st [[United States Homeland Security Advisor]]\n|president1   = [[George W. Bush]]\n|term_start1  = September 20, 2001\n|term_end1    = January 24, 2003\n|predecessor1 = Position established\n|successor1   = [[John A. Gordon]]\n|order2       = 43rd [[List of governors of Pennsylvania|Governor of Pennsylvania]]\n|lieutenant2  = Mark Schweiker <!-- Don't add link per MOS:OVERLINK. -->\n|term_start2  = January 17, 1995\n|term_end2    = October 5, 2001\n|predecessor2 = [[Bob Casey Sr.]]\n|successor2   = [[Mark Schweiker]]\n|state3       = [[Pennsylvania]]\n|district3    = {{ushr|PA|21|21st}}\n|term_start3  = January 3, 1983\n|term_end3    = January 3, 1995\n|predecessor3 = [[Donald A. Bailey|Donald Bailey]]\n|successor3   = [[Phil English]]\n|birth_name   = Thomas Joseph Ridge\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1945|8|26|mf=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Munhall, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Michele Ridge\n|children     = 2\n|education    = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|AB]])<br />[[Penn State Dickinson Law]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{army|United States}}\n|rank         = [[File:Army-USA-OR-06.svg|18px|link=|alt=]] [[Staff sergeant]]\n|unit         = Bravo Company, [[20th Infantry Regiment (United States)|1st Battalion, 20th Infantry Regiment]], [[11th Infantry Brigade (United States)|11th Infantry Brigade]], [[23rd Infantry Division (United States)|23rd Infantry Division]]\n|battles      = [[Vietnam War]]\n|mawards      = [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]] (with [[\"V\" device|valor]])<br />[[Vietnam Gallantry Cross|Republic of Vietnam Gallantry Cross with Palm]]\n}}\n'''Thomas Joseph Ridge''' (born August 26, 1945) is an American politician and author who served as the [[Assistant to the President for Homeland Security]] from 2001 to 2003, and the first [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security]] from 2003 to 2005. Prior to this, Ridge was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1983 to 1995 and the [[List of governors of Pennsylvania|43rd Governor of Pennsylvania]] from 1995 to 2001. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].\n\nRidge was born in [[Munhall, Pennsylvania]] and raised in veterans' public housing in [[Erie, Pennsylvania]]. After graduating from [[Harvard College|Harvard University]] with honors, Ridge served in the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] during the [[Vietnam War]] where he was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]]. He then returned to Pennsylvania and completed his [[Juris Doctor]] (J.D.) degree at the [[Dickinson School of Law]], graduating in 1972, and entered private practice.\n\nAs assistant district attorney in Erie, Ridge ran for Congress [[Pennsylvania's 21st congressional district|in his district]], where he served six terms. He then ran for governor in [[1994 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1994]], despite being little-known outside of northwest Pennsylvania. He won the election, and was reelected in [[1998 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1998]] with the most votes for a Republican governor in Pennsylvania (where Democrats outnumber Republicans by almost 500,000) in more than half a century.<ref name=\"Online NewsHour\">{{cite web |title=Pennsylvania's Tom Ridge Appointed to Bush Cabinet |date=September 20, 2001 |publisher=[[Online NewsHour]] |access-date=May 22, 2005 |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/september01/ridge_bio.html}}</ref> As Governor of Pennsylvania, Ridge is credited for statewide advances in economic development, education, health care and the environment. {{As of|2019}}, Ridge is the last Republican to win reelection as Pennsylvania's governor.\n\nFollowing the [[September 11, 2001, attacks|September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks]], U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] named Ridge the first director of the newly created [[Office of Homeland Security]]. In January 2003, the Office of Homeland Security became an official [[United States Cabinet|Cabinet]]-level Department, the [[Department of Homeland Security]], and Ridge became the first [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security|Secretary of Homeland Security]]. He served in these roles for Bush's first term as president, then retired and returned to the private sector.\n\nSince re-entering the private sector, Ridge has served on the boards of [[The Home Depot]], [[The Hershey Company]] and [[Exelon Corporation]] and as a senior advisor to [[Deloitte & Touche]], and TechRadium. Ridge is also the founder and CEO of Ridge Global, LLC, a Washington, D.C.-based security consulting firm. Ridge spent time campaigning with Senator [[John McCain]] during his 2008 bid for the presidency and was believed by some to have been on the short list of potential running mates.<ref name=the-trail /><ref name=\"Veep predictions\">{{cite web |last=Wedd |first=Justin |authorlink=Justin Webb |title=Veep predictions |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=BBC |date=August 20, 2008 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thereporters/justinwebb/2008/08/veep_predictions.html |doi= |access-date=August 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRidge was born in [[Munhall, Pennsylvania]] in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]]'s [[Steel Valley (Pittsburgh)|Steel Valley]], the eldest of three children. His parents were Laura (n\u00e9e Sudimack) and Thomas Regis Ridge, who was a traveling salesman and [[United States Navy|Navy]] [[veteran]]. Ridge's maternal grandparents were [[Rusyns|Rusyn]] immigrants<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.simkovich.org/famouscarpathorussians.htm/|title=A FEW FAMOUS CARPATHO-RUSSIANS|publisher=|access-date=July 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623212052/http://www.simkovich.org/famouscarpathorussians.htm|archive-date=2015-06-23|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> from the former [[Czechoslovakia]] (now [[Slovakia]]), and his paternal great-grandparents emigrated from [[Great Britain]].<ref name=\"growingup\">{{cite news |last=Palattella |first=Ed |author2=Scott Wescott |title=Growing Up: Ridge's journey begins |date=January 21, 2003 |work=[[Erie Times-News]] |url=http://www.goerie.com/risingson/growing_up.html |access-date=August 20, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827223906/http://www.goerie.com/risingson/growing_up.html |archivedate=August 27, 2008 |df= }}</ref> Ridge was raised in veterans' public housing in [[Erie, Pennsylvania]]. He was educated at St. Andrews Elementary School and [[Cathedral Preparatory School]] and did well both academically and in sports. He attended [[Harvard College]], where he paid his way through with construction work, played [[intramural sports|intramural]] baseball and football,<ref name=\"growingup\"/> and graduated with honors in 1967. In 1968, after his first year at the [[Dickinson School of Law]], he was drafted into the [[United States Army]].\n\n===Military service===\n{{BLP sources section|date=June 2017}}\nIn November 1969, Ridge arrived as a sergeant in [[South Vietnam]] where he would serve for six months as a [[Staff sergeant#United States Military|staff sergeant]] with Bravo Company, [[20th Infantry Regiment (United States)|1st Battalion, 20th Infantry]], [[11th Infantry Brigade (United States)|11th Infantry Brigade]], [[23rd Infantry Division (United States)|23rd Infantry Division]] (Americal Division)<ref>[http://www.militaryvetshop.com/History/americal.html History of the 23rd Infantry Division], Militaryvetshop.com; retrieved July 12, 2013.</ref> during the [[Vietnam War]].\n\nIn May 1970, a ruptured [[Vermiform appendix|appendix]] cut short his tour of duty in Vietnam and he was sent home; his service also aggravated a childhood [[ear infection]] which caused him afterwards to have a [[hearing aid]] in his left ear.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Orin |first1=Deborah |title=TOM\u2019S TREMENDOUS TASK |url=https://nypost.com/2001/09/22/toms-tremendous-task/ |website=nypost.com |publisher=NYP HOLDINGS, INC. |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nFor his service in Vietnam, Ridge received the [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]] with [[\"V\" Device]], [[National Defense Service Medal]], [[Vietnam Service Medal]], [[Vietnam Gallantry Cross|Republic of Vietnam Gallantry Cross with palm]], [[Vietnam Gallantry Cross|Republic of Vietnam Gallantry Cross Unit Citation with Palm]], [[Vietnam Campaign Medal|Republic of Vietnam Campaign Medal]], and the [[Combat Infantryman Badge]]. He was later offered a commission as an [[Military officer|officer]] but turned it down.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nAfter returning to [[Pennsylvania]], he completed his [[Juris Doctor]] (J.D.) degree at the Dickinson School of Law, graduating in 1972, and entered private practice.<ref>{{cite web |title=First Homeland Security secretary to deliver Dickinson Law Commencement address |url=https://news.psu.edu/story/564732/2019/03/21/first-homeland-security-secretary-deliver-dickinson-law-commencement-address |website=psu.edu |publisher=The Pennsylvania State University |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Public service in Pennsylvania==\n[[File:Congressman Tom Ridge.jpg|thumb|right|Congressman Ridge during the [[104th Congress]]]]\n[[File:Reagan Contact Sheet C45187 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Ridge with [[President of the United States|President]] [[Ronald Reagan]] in 1988]]\n[[File:Bush Contact Sheet P16288 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Ridge with [[President of the United States|President]] [[George H. W. Bush]] and [[United States Senator]] [[John McCain]] in 1990]]\nRidge became assistant district attorney in [[Erie County, Pennsylvania]] in 1980 and prosecuted 86 cases in two years. In 1982 he won a seat in Congress from [[Pennsylvania's 21st congressional district|northwestern Pennsylvania]] by the margin of only 729 votes,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Barone |first1=Michael |author-link1=Michael Barone (pundit) |last2=Ujifusa |first2=Grant |title=[[The Almanac of American Politics]] 1988|publisher=[[National Journal]] |year=1987 |page=1054}}</ref> and was re-elected six times. Ridge was notable as the first enlisted [[Vietnam]] combat veteran elected to the U.S. House. Ridge never lost an election for public office.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nIn [[1994 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1994]], despite being little-known outside of northwest Pennsylvania, Ridge ran for [[List of governors of Pennsylvania|Governor]]. He won the election as a [[pro-choice]] [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]. He was reelected in [[1998 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1998]] with 57 percent of the vote in a four-way race. His share of the vote in that election was the highest for a Republican governor in Pennsylvania (where Democrats outnumber Republicans by almost 500,000) in more than half a century.<ref name=\"Online NewsHour\"/> Ridge served as governor until his resignation to become the Director of Homeland Security in 2001.<ref name=\"chooses\">{{cite web |last1=Marquis |first1=Christopher |title=A Nation Challenged: Homeland Security; Bush Chooses Old Ally For Cabinet-Level Post |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/21/us/nation-challenged-homeland-security-bush-chooses-old-ally-for-cabinet-level-post.html |website=nytimes.com |publisher=The New York Times Company |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOne of Ridge's more controversial actions as governor was his nomination of [[Peter J. Jannetta]] to be the [[Pennsylvania Department of Health|State Secretary of Health]]. Jannetta had previously been accused of committing perjury, with the [[Pennsylvania Superior Court|State's Superior Court]] stating, \"We have little difficulty in concluding that Dr. Jannetta's testimony at deposition was different than, or inconsistent with, the testimony at trial\". Jannetta was not, however, ever convicted of perjury.<ref>Levy v Jannetta, CCP Allegheny County, GD 81-7689; appeal -J. A370017/92 Levy v Jannetta et al., No. 00150 Pittsburgh, 1992. Settled, 1995.\"</ref> Jannetta served as Health Secretary for six months.<ref>[http://cnsnews.com/news/article/grand-jury-under-pro-abort-gop-governor-pennsylvania-stopped-annual-inspections \"Grand Jury: Under Pro-Abort GOP Governor, Pennsylvania Stopped Annual Inspections of Abortion Clinics\"], ''CNS News'', April 16, 2013.</ref>\n\nDuring his time as governor, Ridge promoted \"[[law and order (politics)|law and order]]\" policies, supporting a [[three-strikes law]] and a faster [[capital punishment|death penalty]] process. A death penalty supporter,<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Ridge on the Issues |publisher=[[On the Issues]]|year=2000|access-date=February 28, 2008|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Tom_Ridge.htm}}</ref> Ridge signed more than 224 execution warrants<ref>{{cite web|title=Execution Warrants Issued by Governor (1985 to Present)|publisher=[[Pennsylvania Department of Corrections]]|format=PDF|date=August 19, 2008|access-date=February 28, 2008|url=http://www.cor.state.pa.us/portal/lib/portal/Warrants_by_Governor.pdf}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 five times the number signed over a 25-year period by the two previous governors&nbsp;\u2013 but [[List of people executed in Pennsylvania|only three voluntary executions were carried out]]. On social issues, he opposed [[gay marriage]] but is [[pro-choice]] on [[abortion]] issues.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tom Ridge on the Issues |url=https://www.ontheissues.org/Tom_Ridge.htm |website=ontheissues.org |publisher=OnTheIssues.org |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOver Ridge's tenure, the Commonwealth's budget grew by two to three percent per fiscal year and combined tax reductions totaled over $2 billion. Ridge created and grew a \"Rainy Day\" Fund balance to over $1 billion to be utilized during an economic downturn or recession.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ridge |url=https://www.ausa.org/sites/default/files/Ridge.pdf |website=ausa.org |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nRidge pushed for legislation permitting competition among electric utilities and enhanced federal and state support for the Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP). He separated the Commonwealth's environmental regulatory and conservation programs into two new agencies; the Department of Environmental Protection and the Department of Conservation and Natural Resources.<ref>{{cite web |title=Conservation and Natural Resources Act, House Bill 1400, Regular Session 1995\u20131996 |url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/billinfo/billinfo.cfm?syear=1995&sind=0&body=H&type=B&bn=1400 |website=Pennsylvania General Assembly |access-date=December 1, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nRidge proposed the creation of public [[charter schools]] in Pennsylvania and in establishing alternate schools for disruptive students. He launched new academic standards that established academic expectations for what students were expected to know in different grades. He proposed a school choice demonstration program.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nRidge oversaw a number of e-government projects including renewing drivers' licenses and vehicle registrations to viewing historical documents and library catalogs. The Commonwealth's portal won several national awards. One of the nation's first electronic grant systems was put into place at the Pennsylvania Department of Education. He created the [http://www.l2l.org/ Link-to-Learn] initiative to increase the effective use of technology in public schools and universities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ridge |url=https://www.ausa.org/sites/default/files/Ridge.pdf |website=ausa.org |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, he was named runner up \"Politician of the Year\" by [[PoliticsPA]].<ref name=poloftheyear2001>{{cite web|title=Sy Snyder's Politician of the Year 2001|work=[[PoliticsPA]]|publisher=The Publius Group|year=2001|url=http://www.politicspa.com/FEATURES/pol_of_the_year.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020803100256/http://www.politicspa.com/FEATURES/pol_of_the_year.htm|archive-date=August 3, 2002|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2002 [[PoliticsPA]] [[Feature story]] designating politicians with [[Yearbook|yearbook superlatives]], he was named the \"Most Popular.\"<ref name=yearbook>{{cite web|title=Keystone State Yearbook Committee|work=[[PoliticsPA]]|publisher=The Publius Group|year=2001|url=http://www.politicspa.com/yearbookcommittee.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020803170058/http://www.politicspa.com/yearbookcommittee.htm|archive-date=August 3, 2002|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nRidge signed two death warrants for African-American civil rights activist [[Mumia Abu-Jamal]], who was convicted of killing a police officer at a traffic stop.<ref>{{cite web | last=Yohn | first=William H., Jr. | title=Memorandum and Order | work=Mumia Abu-Jamal, Petitioner, vs. Martin Horn, Commissioner, Pennsylvania Department of Corrections, et al., Respondents | publisher=US District Court for the Eastern District of Philadelphia |date=December 2001 | url=http://www.paed.uscourts.gov/documents/opinions/01D0951P.pdf | format=PDF | access-date=2008-01-22}}</ref>\n\n==2000 Presidential election==\n[[File:President George W. Bush shakes hands with Governor Tom Ridge.jpg|thumb|right|Ridge greeting [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]] in 2001]]\nRidge was a potential running mate for [[1996 United States presidential election#gopvp|Bob Dole in 1996]], and served as a close advisor to GOP presidential nominee [[George W. Bush]], a close friend from their simultaneous tenures as governors, during the 2000 presidential campaign. In return, Bush named Ridge to his short list for possible running mates, along with [[Governor of New York|New York Governor]] [[George Pataki]], [[List of governors of Michigan|Michigan Governor]] [[John Engler]], [[Governor of Oklahoma|Oklahoma Governor]] [[Frank Keating]], former Missouri Senator [[John Danforth]], and former [[American Red Cross]] President [[Elizabeth Dole]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Starr|first=Alexandra|title=Running Mates: Who will be on the ticket in 2000?|date=July\u2013August 1999|journal=[[Washington Monthly]]|volume=31|issue=7|access-date=September 22, 2005|url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/1999/9907.starr.campaign.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000305010318/http://washingtonmonthly.com/features/1999/9907.starr.campaign.html|archivedate=March 5, 2000|df=}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[September 11, 2001, attacks|September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks]], U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] created the [[Office of Homeland Security]] within the White House, and named Ridge to head it. The charge to the nation's new director of homeland security was to develop and coordinate a comprehensive national strategy to strengthen the United States against terrorist threats or attacks. Ridge formally resigned as Pennsylvania's governor on October 5, 2001.<ref name=\"chooses\" />\n\nIn January 2003 and after the passage of the Homeland Security Act of 2002, the Office of Homeland Security split into a [[United States Cabinet|Cabinet]]-level Department, the [[Department of Homeland Security]], and the White House [[Homeland Security Advisory Council]]. Ridge left the White House and became the first [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security|Secretary of Homeland Security]]. The department's mission \"is to (A) prevent terrorist attacks within the United States; (B) reduce the vulnerability of the United States to terrorism; and (C) minimize the damage, and assist in the recovery, from terrorist attacks that do occur within the United States\" (From H.R. 5005-8 the Homeland Security Act of 2002). The newly created Department was the most comprehensive reorganization of the Federal government since the [[National Security Act of 1947]].\n\nThe Department of Homeland Security consolidates 22 agencies and 180,000 employees, unifying once-fragmented Federal functions in a single agency dedicated to protecting America from terrorism. Ridge worked with the employees from combined agencies to strengthen borders, provide for intelligence analysis and infrastructure protection, improve the use of science and technology to counter weapons of mass destruction, and to create a comprehensive response and recovery division.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/1556612.stm Profile of Tom Ridge], bbc.co.uk, November 9, 2004.</ref><ref>[https://www.npr.org/news/specials/response/home_front/features/2001/oct/ridge.html Security Chief Ridge: 'The Task is Enormous'], NPR.org, October 8, 2001.</ref><ref>[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/fedagencies/jan-june02/ridge_5-9.html Newsmaker: Tom Ridge], Online NewsHour, May 9, 2002.</ref><ref>[http://www.time.com/time/pow/article/0,8599,393066,00.html Person of the Week: Tom Ridge. Now for the hard part: After a week in which the Senate gave him a cabinet-level position, the Homeland Security chief is preparing to take on the toughest job in Washington], Time.com, November 22, 2002.</ref><ref>[http://www.goerie.com/risingson Ridge's journey to the national stage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040101142617/http://www.goerie.com/risingson/ |date=2004-01-01 }}, goerie.com; updated January 21, 2003.</ref>\n\nIn January 2004, Ridge was named among others in a lawsuit filed by a Syrian-born Canadian [[Maher Arar]] who said he was tortured in Syria after being deported by American authorities.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian sues US over deportation|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/3421743.stm|date=January 23, 2004|work=news.bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC News|access-date=September 13, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn November 30, 2004, Ridge submitted his resignation to the President, saying, \"After more than 22 consecutive years of public service, it is time to give personal and family matters a higher priority.\"<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,3-1382726,00.html Anti-terror supremo is latest to quit Bush team], timesonline.co.uk, December 1, 2004.</ref>\n\nIn his book ''The Test of Our Times: America Under Siege...and How We Can Be Safe Again'', Ridge says his resignation was due to an effort by senior Bush administration officials to raise the nation's terror alert level in the days before the 2004 presidential vote.<ref name=\"cnnticker\">{{cite news|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/08/20/ridge-i-fought-raising-security-level-before-04-vote|title=Ridge: I fought raising security level before '04 vote|date=August 20, 2009|work=Political Ticker|publisher=CNN|access-date=August 21, 2009}}</ref><ref name=Bedard>Bedard, Paul. \"[https://www.usnews.com/blogs/washington-whispers/2009/08/19/tom-ridge-on-national-security-after-911.html Tom Ridge on National Security After 9/11]\", U.S. News & World Report, August 19, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Work in the private sector==\nRidge is the founder and CEO of Ridge Global, an advisory firm in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite news|first=Katherine|last=Walsh|title=Five Things Tom Ridge Has Learned About Risk|url=http://www.cio.com/article/149601/Five_Things_Tom_Ridge_Has_Learned_About_Risk|work=CIO magazine|publisher=[[CXO Media]]|date=October 29, 2007|access-date=November 10, 2007}}</ref>\n\nRidge served on a state-appointed incident review panel that investigated the [[Virginia Tech shooting]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Va. Tech gunman was 'well-prepared' to continue shooting spree|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2007-05-21-va-tech-probe_N.htm|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=May 21, 2007|access-date=November 10, 2007}}</ref>\n\nRidge also sits on the [https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/ Atlantic Council's]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/about/board-of-directors/|title=Board of Directors|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> Board of Directors. \n\n===RIDGE-LANE Limited Partners===\nRidge is a co-founder, along with investment banker R. Brad Lane,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ridge-lane.com/team/r-brad-lane|title=R. Brad Lane|publisher=RIDGE-LANE Limited Partners|access-date=January 23, 2018}}</ref> of RIDGE-LANE Limited and RIDGE-LANE Capital, a merchant-bank that sponsors [[urban development]] projects, [[public\u2013private partnership]]s (P3) and [[economic development]] programs, as well as [[corporate development]] services for private technology companies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ridge-lane.com|publisher=RIDGE-LANE Limited Partners|access-date=April 17, 2017|title=RIDGE-LANE Limited Partners|website=ridge-lane.com}}</ref>\n\n===Ridge Policy Group===\nIn 2010, Ridge's two former Chiefs of Staff, Mark Campbell and Mark Holman, opened a lobbying firm after Ridge lent the firm his name.  The full-service government affairs firm has offices in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, and Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mcall.com/news/nationworld/pennsylvania/mc-pa-wolf-dc-lobbying-firm-20150603-story.html |title= PA Gov. Tom Wolf administration hires new D.C. lobbying firm |date=June 3, 2015 |first=Laura |last=Olson |newspaper=The Morning Call }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Former Gov. Ridge lending name, clout to new Harrisburg-D.C. lobbying firm|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/harrisburg_politics/Former_Gov_Ridge_lending_name_clout_to_new_Harrisburg-DC_lobbying_firm.html|publisher=philly.com|access-date=January 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, companies seeking to use [[hydraulic fracturing]] to extract [[natural gas]] from the [[Marcellus Formation|Marcellus Shale formation]] engaged Ridge and Ridge Policy Group at $75,000 a month to help them gain support.<ref>{{cite web|last=Associated Press|authorlink=Associated Press|title=Ex-Homeland Security boss joins gas drilling group|publisher=[[Google News]]|date=July 30, 2010|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5iYhHpjTFHgYX9J7VAxVs2oAyQc3wD9H9IGA80|access-date=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Home Depot===\nIn February 2005, Tom Ridge was named to the board of [[Home Depot]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Company News; Home Depot Names Tom Ridge a Director|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F04E1D6173DF936A15751C0A9639C8B63&n=Top/News/Business/Companies/Home%20Depot%20Inc. |newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 25, 2005|access-date=November 10, 2007}}</ref> Ridge's compensation was expected to be about $100,000 per annum for this position.<ref>{{cite news|title=Board work can be rewarding|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2003/10/13/story7.html?page=2|publisher=Atlanta Business Chronicle|date=October 10, 2003|access-date=November 10, 2007|first=Meredith|last=Jordan}}</ref> Since April 2005, Ridge served on the board of [[Savi Technology]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Ridge Joins Savi Technology Board of Directors|url=http://www.rfidupdate.com/articles/index.php?id=844 |publisher=RFID Update|date=April 8, 2005|access-date=November 10, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071003163736/http://www.rfidupdate.com/articles/index.php?id=844|archive-date=October 3, 2007}}</ref> the primary technology provider for the wireless cargo-monitoring network for the [[United States Department of Defense]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.savi.com/company/ov.fact.shtml|title=Savi Fact Sheet|access-date=November 10, 2007|work=Corporate website|publisher=Savi Technology|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012200425/http://savi.com/company/ov.fact.shtml|archive-date=October 12, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Exelon Corporation===\nIn April, 2005, Ridge's appointment to the board of the Illinois/Pennsylvania/New Jersey electric utility was announced, with starting director compensation of $35,000 annual retainer plus a $1,500 meeting fee or per diem fee. Directors were also granted $60,000 in deferred stock units each year at that time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/news.pl?id=16295 |title=Ex-Homeland Sec. joins Exelon board |first=Gregory |last=Meyer |newspaper=[[Crain's Chicago Business]] |date=April 27, 2005 |access-date=February 19, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, it was reported that Ridge had appeared on [[MSNBC]] ''Hardball With [[Chris Matthews]]'' promoting [[Nuclear power|nuclear energy]] as part of a \"green agenda [to] ... create jobs, create exports,\" without any revelation by him or the [[cable channel]] of his Exelon position. In the report, his cumulative Exelon-derived compensation was put at $530,659; and it was said that, as of March 2009, he held an estimated $248,299 in Exelon stock, according to SEC filings. Exelon was described as \"the nation's largest nuclear power company.\"<ref>Sebastian Jones, [http://www.thenation.com/doc/20100301/jones/print \"The Media-Lobbying Complex\"], ''The Nation'', February 11, 2010 (March 1, 2010 edition of magazine)</ref><ref>[http://www.fair.org/index.php?page=4017 Radio interview with SJones], fair.org, February 19, 2010.</ref>\n\n===Deloitte LLP===\nIn November 2006, Tom Ridge was announced as a senior advisor for [[Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu|Deloitte & Touche]] USA LLP.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fcw.com/articles/2006/11/02/ridge-joins-deloitte.aspx |title=Ridge joins Deloitte |access-date=March 13, 2014 |date=November 2, 2006 |work=Federal Computer Week |publisher=Media, Inc. }}</ref>\n\n===The Hershey Company===\nIn November 2007, Ridge was named to serve on [[The Hershey Company]]'s Executive Board. The Hershey Trust, the primary shareholder of Hershey, asked for a change in board composition after several years of poor stock performance. The board named Ridge to the board for his knowledge of economics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/patriotnews/article294464.ece|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120910042853/http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/patriotnews/article294464.ece|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 10, 2012|title=Big changes at Hershey|publisher=|access-date=July 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===TechRadium Inc===\nAnnounced in January 2008, Tom Ridge will serve as a senior advisor to TechRadium, Inc., a Texas-based security technology company that provides its patented alert and notification\nsystem, IRIS (Immediate Response Information System), to a wide range of users\nincluding municipalities, public schools and universities, utilities, and military programs.<ref>{{cite news|first= |last= |authorlink= |title=Tom Ridge to Advise TechRadium On 'IRIS' Technology |url=http://www.securityinfowatch.com/article/10545958/tom-ridge-to-advise-techradium-on-iris-technology |publisher=Security InfoWatch |date=January 9, 2008 |access-date=April 25, 2016 |agency=PRNewswire }}</ref>\n\n===PURE Bioscience===\nIn September 2009, PURE Bioscience, creator of a patented [[antimicrobial]], announced Ridge would serve on its advisory board along with former [[Governor of Wisconsin|Wisconsin governor]] [[Tommy Thompson]].<ref>{{cite news |title=PURE Bioscience Forms Advisory Panel Tom Ridge, Tommy G. Thompson Among Inaugural Members |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/PURE-Bioscience-Forms-bw-3403647171.html?x=0&.v=1 |website=Finance.yahoo.com |date=September 1, 2009 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n\n==Political activity==\n\n===2008 Presidential election===\nTom Ridge served as a senior aide to Republican Presidential candidate Senator [[John McCain]] of Arizona,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebulletin.us/site/news.cfm?newsid=19241247&BRD=2737&PAG=461&dept_id=618959&rfi=6 |title=Ridge A Leading Candidate For McCain VP Role? |publisher=The Bulletin |access-date=January 31, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207233444/http://www.thebulletin.us/site/news.cfm?newsid=19241247&BRD=2737&PAG=461&dept_id=618959&rfi=6 |archivedate=February 7, 2016 |df= }}</ref> and was considered by some as a possible running mate for McCain.<ref name=the-trail>{{cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/the-trail/2008/08/11/mccain_campaigns_with_ridge_as.html |title=McCain Campaigns with Ridge as VP Speculation Intensifies |access-date=August 12, 2008 |work=The Trail |publisher=The Washington Post |date=August 11, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Veep predictions\" /> [[File:TomRidgePodium-McCainRallyWashingtonPA2008.jpg|thumb|alt=Ridge at McCain Palin rally |Tom Ridge at rally for John McCain]]\n\n===Possible 2010 Senate candidacy===\nAccording to [[Fox News]], many Republicans hoped Ridge would run for the [[United States Senate]] against the newly turned Democrat [[Arlen Specter]], who stated he would seek [[United States Senate election in Pennsylvania, 2010|re-election in 2010]] in the Democratic primary.  Already seeking the Republican nomination was former [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] [[Pat Toomey]], who narrowly lost to Specter in the Republican primary in 2004. Some Republicans thought Ridge would have a better chance against Specter than would Toomey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lehighvalleylive.com/jessica-coomes/index.ssf/2009/05/poll_arlen_specter_would_top_p.html|title=Poll: Arlen Specter would top Pat Toomey, Tom Ridge in general election|publisher=|access-date=July 1, 2017}}</ref> A [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute]] poll conducted between April 30, 2009 and May 3, 2009 placed Ridge within three points of Specter in a hypothetical matchup between the two men.<ref>{{cite news |title=Poll says Specter holds 20-point edge over Toomey: A run by former Gov. Ridge would boost GOP's chances|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/09124/967593-100.stm|work=post-gazette.com |publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=May 4, 2009|access-date=June 19, 2009}}</ref>\n\nSome Toomey supporters criticized the idea of a Ridge candidacy because, although Ridge was still registered to vote in Pennsylvania, he was actually living in [[Chevy Chase, Maryland]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Micek| first=John L.|title=Whither Tom Ridge?| newspaper=[[The Morning Call]]|date=May 7, 2009|url=http://blogs.mcall.com/capitol_ideas/2009/05/whither-tom-ridge.html|access-date=May 7, 2009}}</ref> On May 7, 2009, Ridge announced that he would not be a candidate for the U.S. Senate in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ridge Says He Won't Seek Specter's Senate Seat|publisher=[[WFMZ-TV]]|date=May 7, 2009|url=http://wfmz.com/view/?id=893773|archive-url=https://archive.today/20110809102716/http://wfmz.com/view/?id=893773|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 9, 2011|access-date=May 7, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===2012 Presidential election===\nRidge originally endorsed former [[List of governors of Utah|Utah Governor]] [[Jon Huntsman, Jr.|Jon Huntsman]] for president, in September 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/tom-ridge-jon-huntsman-new-hampshire-mitt-romney-2012-election_n_1185985 |title=Jon Huntsman Backer Tom Ridge Sets High Bar For Mitt Romney In New Hampshire |newspaper=HuffPost |first=Sam |last=Stein |date=January 5, 2012 |access-date=August 27, 2019 }}</ref> [[Mitt Romney]] announced an endorsement from Ridge on March 14, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/03/14/tom-ridge-endorses-mitt-romney_n_1344252.html|title=Tom Ridge Endorses Mitt Romney|newspaper=The Huffington Post|first=Elise|last=Foley|date=March 14, 2012|access-date=March 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Supreme Court brief===\nIn 2013, Ridge was a signatory to an ''[[amicus curiae]]'' brief submitted to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] in support of [[same-sex marriage]] during the ''[[Hollingsworth v. Perry]]'' case.<ref>[http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/02/28/the-pro-freedom-republicans-are-coming-131-sign-gay-marriage-brief.html The Pro-Freedom Republicans Are Coming: 131 Sign Gay Marriage Brief]. The Daily Beast (February 28, 2013). Retrieved on July 12, 2013.</ref>\n\n===Support for the People's Mujahedin of Iran===\nRidge spoke at a conference in support of the removal of the [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]] (MEK, also PMOI, MKO) from the [[United States State Department list of Foreign Terrorist Organizations]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mojahedin.org/linksen/1541 |website=mojahedi.org |title=Governor Tom Ridge call on Obama to protect Iranian dissidents in Iraq |access-date=July 1, 2017 |date=November 21, 2013 }}</ref> The group was listed on the State Department list from 1997 until September 2012. They were placed on the list for killing six Americans in Iran during the 1970s and attempting to attack the Iranian mission to the United Nations in 1992.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/09/28/politics/mek-terror-delisting/index.html|title=Iranian exile group removed from U.S. terror list|author=CNN Wire Staff|publisher=CNN|access-date=July 1, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929031444/http://www.cnn.com/2012/09/28/politics/mek-terror-delisting/index.html|archive-date=September 29, 2012|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2012/09/198443.htm |title=Delisting of the Mujahedin-e Khalq |publisher=U.S. Department of State |date=September 28, 2012 }}</ref> Ridge, along with other former government officials and politicians [[Ed Rendell]], [[R. James Woolsey]], [[Porter Goss]], [[Louis Freeh]], [[Michael Mukasey]], [[James L. Jones]], [[Rudy Giuliani]], and [[Howard Dean]], were criticized for their involvement with the group. Some were subpoenaed during an inquiry about who was paying the prominent individuals' speaking fees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/13/us/us-supporters-of-iranian-group-mek-face-scrutiny.html|title=U.S. Supporters of Iranian Group M.E.K. Face Scrutiny|first=Scott|last=Shane|date=March 13, 2012|publisher=|access-date=July 1, 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Ridge and others wrote an article for the conservative publication ''[[National Review]]'' stating their position that the group should not be classified as a terrorist organization, raising the point that, at the time, only the United States and Iran still listed it as a terrorist group.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/256689/mek-not-terrorist-group-michael-b-mukasey-tom-ridge-and-frances-fragos-townsend |title=MEK is Not a Terrorist Group |date=January 1, 2011 |magazine=National Review |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111174147/http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/256689/mek-not-terrorist-group-michael-b-mukasey-tom-ridge-and-frances-fragos-townsend |archive-date=January 11, 2011 |last1=Mukasey |first1=Michael B |author-link1=Michael Mukasey |last2=Ridge |first2=Tom |last3=Giuliani |first3=Rudolph W |author-link3=Rudy Giuliani |last4=Townsend |first4=Frances Fragos |author-link4=Frances Townsend}}</ref>\n\n===2015 Blue Ribbon Commission===\n[[File:Shalala, Ridge, Lieberman, Wainstein, Greenwood at the Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense.jpg|thumb|[[Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense]] (Ridge 2nd from left)]]\nIn 2015, Ridge served as co-chair of the [[Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense]], a commission that recommended changes to U.S. policy regarding biodefense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biodefensestudy.org/|title=Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense|website=www.biodefensestudy.org|access-date=January 20, 2017}}</ref> In order to address biological threats facing the nation, the Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense created a 33-step initiative for the U.S. Government to implement. Tom Ridge headed the organization with former Senator Joe Lieberman, and the Study Panel assembled in Washington D.C. for four meetings concerning current biodefense programs. The Study Panel concluded that the federal government had little to no defense mechanisms in case of a biological event. The Study Panel's final report, ''The National Blueprint for Biodefense'', proposes a string of solutions and recommendations for the U.S. Government to take, including items such as giving the vice president authority over biodefense responsibilities and merging the entire biodefense budget. These solutions represent the Panel's call to action in order to increase awareness and activity for pandemic related issues.\n\n===2016 Presidential election===\nIn 2016, Ridge endorsed [[Jeb Bush]] and subsequently [[John Kasich]] after Bush's withdrawal from the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 Republican presidential primaries]]. Ridge stated he would not endorse [[Donald Trump]], following Trump becoming the [[presumptive nominee]], or [[Hillary Clinton]] in the general election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Struck|first1=Jules|title=Ridge Refuses to Support Trump|url=http://www.politicspa.com/ridge-refuses-to-support-trump/75505/|access-date=May 18, 2016|agency=PoliticsPA|date=May 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Memoir==\nTom Ridge's book ''The Test of Our Times'' was published in September 2009.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Test of Our Times |last=Ridge |first=Tom |author2=Bloom, Larry |year=2009 |publisher=Thomas Dunne Books |isbn=978-0-312-53487-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/testofourtimesam00ridg |access-date=February 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |df= |url-access=registration }}</ref> Written with Larry Bloom, it concerns Ridge's time as the head of the Department of Homeland Security. He explains the challenges and decision making processes of the newly formed department, and gives his own views as to the future of the security of the United States of America. The book further discusses\n\n{{quote|the infighting he saw that frustrated his attempts to build a smooth-running department. Among the headlines promoted by publisher [[Thomas Dunne Books]]: Ridge was never invited to sit in on National Security Council meetings; was 'blindsided' by the FBI in morning Oval Office meetings because the agency withheld critical information from him; found his urgings to block [[Michael D. Brown|Michael Brown]] from being named head of the emergency agency blamed for the Hurricane Katrina disaster ignored; and was pushed to raise the security alert on the eve of President Bush's re-election, something he saw as politically motivated and worth resigning over.<ref name=Bedard/>}}\n\nRidge wrote in his memoir that then-Secretary of Defense [[Donald Rumsfeld]] and then-Attorney General [[John Ashcroft]] pressured him to raise the [[Homeland Security Advisory System|terror alert level]], running up to the 2004 elections, because of a pre-election message critical of President Bush from [[Osama bin Laden|Osama Bin Laden]].<ref name=cnnticker/>\n\n==Recognition==\n{{BLP sources section|date=June 2017}}\n[[File:DHS celebrates 15 years (39848640424).jpg|thumb|Ridge with [[Kirstjen Nielsen]], [[John F. Kelly|John Kelly]], and [[Michael Chertoff]] in 2018]]\n* Presented with the [[Woodrow Wilson Awards|Woodrow Wilson Award]] by the [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ridge |url=https://www.ausa.org/sites/default/files/Ridge.pdf |website=ausa.org |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Erie International Airport]] was co-named ''Tom Ridge Field'' in honor of Ridge.\n* The [[Tom Ridge Environmental Center]] at [[Presque Isle State Park]] in [[Erie, Pennsylvania]] is named after the former governor. Ridge was instrumental in securing funds for the center.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ridge |url=https://www.ausa.org/sites/default/files/Ridge.pdf |website=ausa.org |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n* His picture hangs in the [[moot court]] room at the [[The Pennsylvania State University&nbsp;\u2014 Dickinson School of Law|Penn State Dickinson School of Law]] in [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania]].\n* [[Presque Isle Downs]] in [[Erie, Pennsylvania]] runs the $100,000 Tom Ridge Stakes every meet.\n* [[Mercyhurst University]] named its Tom Ridge College of Intelligence Studies and Applied Science after the first U.S. Secretary of Homeland Security.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mercyhurst.edu/news/mercyhurst-dedicates-new-intel-school-named-after-gov-tom-ridge|title=Mercyhurst dedicates new intel school named after Gov. Tom Ridge|date=April 11, 2014|access-date=May 25, 2015|publisher=Mercyhurst University }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTom's wife, Michele Ridge, is the former executive director of the [[Erie County, Pennsylvania|Erie County]] Library System. Married since 1979, they have two children: Lesley and Tommy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Profile: Tom Ridge|author=BBC News|work=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/1556612.stm|date=November 9, 2004}}</ref>\n\nRidge was hospitalized in critical condition in Texas after a cardiac event on November 16, 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/11/16/ex-homeland-security-secretary-tom-ridge-hospitalized.html |title=Ex-Homeland Security Secretary Tom Ridge hospitalized |date=November 16, 2017 |access-date=November 16, 2017 |publisher=Fox News |agency=Associated Press }}</ref>\n\n==Gubernatorial electoral history==\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1994 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1994 Pennsylvania Gubernatorial Election]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1994&off=5&elect=0&fips=42&f=0|title=US Election Atlas: 1994|publisher=|access-date=July 1, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Tom Ridge\n  |votes      = 1,627,976\n  |percentage = 45.40\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = [[Mark Singel]]\n  |votes      = 1,430,099\n  |percentage = 39.89\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Constitution Party (US)\n  |candidate  = [[Peg Luksik]]\n  |votes      = 460,269\n  |percentage = 12.84\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1998 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|1998 Pennsylvania Gubernatorial Election]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1998&fips=42&f=0&off=5&elect=0|title=US Election Atlas: 1998|publisher=|access-date=July 1, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Tom Ridge (incumbent)\n  |votes      = 1,736,844\n  |percentage = 57.42\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = [[Ivan Itkin]]\n  |votes      = 938,745\n  |percentage = 31.03\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Constitution Party (US)\n  |candidate  = [[Peg Luksik]]\n  |votes      = 315,761\n  |percentage = 10.44\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Libertarian Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Ken V. Krawchuk\n  |votes      = 33,591\n  |percentage = 1.10\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{