ackground:#efefef;\"| {{Nowrap|[[Players Championship Finals]]}}\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"|Not held\n| colspan=\"10\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"|Non-PDC\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2019 Players Championship Finals|3R]]\n|\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:78%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! colspan=\"9\"|Performance Table Legend\n|-\n|  style=\"color:#ccc; text-align:center; width:30px;\"|PDC\n|  As a New PDC member, no longer plays BDO events\n|  style=\"color:#ccc; text-align:center; width:30px;\"|DNP\n| Did not play at the event\n|  style=\"color:#ccc; text-align:center; width:30px;\"|DNQ\n| Did not qualify for the event\n|  style=\"color:#ccc; text-align:center; width:30px;\"|NYF\n| Not yet founded\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|#R\n| lost in the early rounds of the tournament<br />(WR = Wildcard round, RR = Round robin)\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#ffebcd;\"|QF\n| lost in the quarter-finals\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:yellow;\"|SF\n| lost in the semi-finals\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:thistle;\"|F\n| lost in the final\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#0f0;\"|'''W'''\n| won the tournament\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Dartsdatabase|id=80|name=Glen Durrant}}\n\n{{World Darts Championship (BDO)}}\n{{PDC Top 20}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Durrant, Glen}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:English darts players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Middlesbrough]]\n[[Category:British Darts Organisation players]]\n[[Category:Professional Darts Corporation players]]\n[[Category:BDO world darts champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English darts player}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP primary sources|date=January 2017}}\n{{lead too short|date=January 2017}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox darts player\n| name = Glen Durrant\n| image = Glen Durrant 6-3 Cody Harris - Glen Durrant - 2019250150321 2019-09-07 PDC European Darts Matchplay - 0446 - B70I6816.jpg\n| caption = Durrant in 2019\n| fullname =\n| nickname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|11|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Middlesbrough]], [[North Riding of Yorkshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =  \n| hometown = [[Middlesbrough]]\n| homecountry = [[England]]\n| since = 1985\n| darts = Glen Durrant 24 Gram Target Signature\n| laterality = Right-handed\n| music = \"[[Pump It Up!|Pump It Up]]\" by [[Danzel|Endor]]\n| BDO = 2004\u20132019\n| PDC = 2019\u2013\n| currentrank = 20\n| BDO World = {{nowrap|'''Winner (3)''': [[2017 BDO World Darts Championship|2017]], [[2018 BDO World Darts Championship|2018]], [[2019 BDO World Darts Championship|2019]]}}\n| World Masters = '''Winner (2)''': [[2015 World Masters (darts)|2015]], [[2016 World Masters (darts)|2016]]\n| World Darts Trophy = '''Winner (1)''': [[2018 BDO World Trophy|2018]]\n| Zuiderduin Masters = '''Winner (3)''': 2015, 2016, 2018\n| PDC World = Quarter Final: [[2020 PDC World Darts Championship|2020]]\n| Matchplay = Semi Final: [[2019 World Matchplay (darts)|2019]]\n| Grand Prix = Semi Final: [[2019 World Grand Prix (darts)|2019]]\n| UK Open = Last 64: [[2020 UK Open|2020]]\n| Grand Slam = Semi Final: [[2019 Grand Slam of Darts|2019]]\n| European =  Last 32: [[2019 European Championship (darts)|2019]]\n| Premier League = [[2020 Premier League Darts|2020]]\n| PC Finals = Last 16: [[2019 Players Championship Finals|2019]]\n| results = {{aligned table|leftright=y|fullwidth=y|class=nowrap\n| '''BDO Gold Cup'''|2016\n| '''Belgium Open'''|2018\n|''' British Classic'''|2016\n| '''Denmark Masters'''|2016, 2017\n| '''Denmark Open'''|2015\n| '''England Classic'''|2012, 2013, 2015\n| '''England Masters'''|2016\n| '''England Matchplay'''|{{nowrap|2015, 2016, 2017, 2018}}\n| '''England Open'''|2016\n| '''European Darts Open'''|2016\n| '''Isle Of Man Classic'''|2015\n| '''Isle Of Man Open'''|2018\n| '''Jersey Open'''|2012\n| '''Northern Ireland Open'''|2013, 2014\n| '''Swedish Open'''|2016\n| '''Welsh Open'''|2015, 2017\n| '''{{nowrap|Winmau Wolverhampton Classic}}'''|2017\n| '''WDF Europe Cup Team'''|2016\n| '''WDF World Cup Team'''|2015\n}}\n'''''Players Championships'''''\n{{aligned table|leftright=y|fullwidth=y|class=nowrap\n| '''Players Championship ([[Wigan|WIG]])'''| [[2019 PDC Pro Tour#Players Championships|2019]]\n| '''Players Championship ([[Barnsley|BAR]])'''| [[2019 PDC Pro Tour#Players Championships|2019]]\n}}\n\n| achievement = Lazenby Open '''2014'''<br>Middlebeck Open '''2014'''<br>Northumberland Open '''2012'''<br>Staithes Open '''2009'''<br>Teesside Open '''2011'''<br>Thornaby Open '''2009'''\n}}\n\n'''Glen Durrant''' (born 24 November 1970 in [[Middlesbrough]]) is a professional [[England|English]] [[darts]] player. He currently plays in [[Professional Darts Corporation]] events. He won the [[BDO World Darts Championship]] three times consecutively from 2017 to 2019. He is also a 2-time [[World Masters (darts)|World Masters]] and 3-time [[Finder Darts Masters]] champion.\n\n==Darts career==\n\n===Early career===\nAlthough he began playing in 1985, Durrant's first major appearance was in the 2004 [[Winmau World Masters]], where he lost out in the early stages to [[Dietmar Burger]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dartsdatabase.co.uk/EventResults.aspx?EventKey=274|title=2004 World Masters Results|publisher=|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref>  He would have more success the following year however.   Two consecutive 3-0 wins put him in the last 32 and this was followed by a 3-1 win over Anthony Miera, to set up a last 16 match against [[Martin Adams]]. Durrant almost pulled off a famous victory but lost out 2-3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dartsdatabase.co.uk/EventResults.aspx?EventKey=131|title=2005 World Masters Results|publisher=|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nDurrant has appeared in the PDC's [[UK Open (darts)|UK Open]] on three occasions.  In [[2005 UK Open|2005]] he won his opening match against Darren Moulsley before losing a deciding leg against [[Ray Cornibert]] in the last 64.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dartsdatabase.co.uk/EventResults.aspx?EventKey=45|title=2005 UK Open Results|publisher=|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref>  In [[2009 UK Open|2009]] Durrant defeated Graham Usher and John McGuirk before losing out to [[Terry Jenkins]] 1-9.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dartsdatabase.co.uk/EventResults.aspx?EventKey=1957|title=2009 UK Open Results|publisher=|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref> Durrant also qualified for the PDC's UK Open in [[2012 UK Open|2012]] by winning the Riley's qualifier in Middlesbrough.   He drew a fellow Riley's qualifier in Stephen Bunting and lost 0-4 in the preliminary round.\n\n===2011-2014===\nIn 2011 he made his third appearance in the Winmau World Masters.  Four consecutive wins and dropping only 3 legs put him into the televised stages of the tournament, where he defeated Craig Baxter 3-2 in sets in the last 24.  In the last 16 he faced 2000 world champion [[John Walton (darts player)|John Walton]].  A 3-1 win in sets saw an emotional Durrant set up a rematch against Martin Adams, where Adams won 3-1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dartsdatabase.co.uk/EventResults.aspx?EventKey=3305|title=2011 World Masters Results|publisher=|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nDurrant came within one match of qualifying for the World Championship in 2012, but was beaten in the final round by [[Alan Norris (darts player)|Alan Norris]] who went on to reach the quarter-finals.\n\nDurrant is a dominant force locally in his own Teesside area and has won the Teesside darts championship 3 times in the last 4 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freewebs.com/teesdarts/ |title=Home - Teesside Darts |website=Freewebs.com |date= |accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe threw his first competitive 9 dart finish in the England Darts Organisations Grosvenor Casino Tyneside Classic.    This was part of a dramatic comeback from 0-4, to win 5-4, against England teammate Garry Thompson in the last 16.<ref name=\"duzzadarts.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.duzzadarts.com/index.php/duzza-news|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120234154/http://www.duzzadarts.com/index.php/duzza-news|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-11-20|title=Glenn Durrant news}}</ref>\n\nThe first major International open tournament win for Durrant came in September 2012, when he recorded victories against Martin Adams, [[Robbie Green]] and [[Martin Atkins (darts player)|Martin Atkins]], amongst others, before defeating [[Scott Waites]] in the final to win the 2012 EDO England Classic and the \u00a33000 first prize.  At the same tournament he \"did the double\" by winning the pairs competition with his playing partner [[Tony Eccles]] and also was runner up in the inaugural EDO England Matchplay.<ref name=\"duzzadarts.com\"/>  After adding the 2012 Jersey Open, Durrant retained the England Classic in 2013.<ref name=\"duzzadarts.com\"/>\n\nDurrant made his debut at the World Championship in 2014 as a seeded player. He defeated qualifier [[Mike Day (darts player)|Mike Day]] 3-0 in the first round before losing 4-1 to Norris.\n\nDurrant reached the semi-finals of the Masters in 2014. He survived six match darts en route including four against [[Scott Mitchell (darts player)|Scott Mitchell]] in the quarter-finals (the other two were against [[Brian Dawson (darts player)|Brian Dawson]] in a previous round), before losing in a deciding leg against eventual champion [[Martin Phillips (darts player)|Martin Phillips]] having missed one match dart at the bullseye. Durrant then lost to Mitchell in the final of the Jersey Open, televised on Eurosport, having led 5-3 in a race to six and missed three match darts.\n\n===2015-2019===\nDurrant's reached the last four of the 2015 World Championship, maintaining a 90+ average in each of his first three wins over [[Karel Sedl\u00e1\u010dek]], [[Jamie Hughes (darts player)|Jamie Hughes]] and [[Darryl Fitton]]. In the semi-final, [[Martin Adams]] defeated Durrant 6-5, despite Durrant having led 5-4 and missing one match dart to win 6-4, and then leading the deciding set 2-0 in legs and missing two further match darts. The match was lauded as one of the best in the history of the tournament as Durrant averaged 99.57 to Adams` 97.92 and they hit 12 ton+ finishes between them. After the world championships Glen approached renowned sports mind coach Stephen McKibben from Northern Ireland, who was accredited with leading Scott Mitchell to world glory. He has worked with Stephen ever since and it has enabled him to win his majors and dominate the BDO world tour.\n\nDurrant had a fine 2015 on the BDO Circuit and has picked up the English Classic, English Matchplay, Welsh Open, Denmark Open and Isle of Man classic titles, and was finalist in the Scottish Open, Isle of Man Open, English Open and British Classic. He also helped his country to win the WDF World Cup team title.\n\nDurrant won his first major title with the [[2015 World Masters (darts)|2015 World Masters]] title, after showing superb form throughout the tournament. He defeated the former [[World Matchplay (darts)|World Matchplay]] champion, [[Larry Butler (darts player)|Larry Butler]], 7-3 in the final. Glen mentioned about how much working with Stephen has changed him from a nearly man to a major winner.\n\nHis second major BDO title came in December when he won the 2015 [[Zuiderduin Masters]], beating [[Martin Adams]] 5-2 in sets in the final and averaging 100.69.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.findermasters.nl/?p=533 |title=Finder Darts Masters kampioenen, Glen Durrant, Fallon Sherrock en Justin van Tergouw &#124; Finder Darts Masters |website=Findermasters.nl |date=6 December 2015 |accessdate=15 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104021624/http://www.findermasters.nl/?p=533 |archive-date=4 January 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDurrant entered the 2016 World Championship as the favourite to win the tournament, and won his first two matches without dropping a set, defeating [[Dean Reynolds (darts player)|Dean Reynolds]] and [[Larry Butler (darts player)|Larry Butler]]. In the quarter final, the 2013 world champion and eventual winner, [[Scott Waites]], defeated Durrant 5-4, despite Durrant leading 3-1 and 4-2 in sets and being 2-0 up in legs during the seventh set.\n\nDurrant entered the [[2017 BDO World Darts Championship]] as the number 1 seed and won the tournament for the first time, beating [[Danny Noppert]] in the final 7-3. Glen had a pressure filled tournament, and contacted his mind coach Stephen McKibben after a near miss against [[Paul Hogan (darts player)|Paul Hogan]]. Durrant excelled in the rest of the tournament, dominating his remaining games.\n\nDurrant experienced his most successful season to date as he reached final of every major, successfully defending the [[2018 BDO World Darts Championship|BDO World Darts Championship]]. Through the year he won the [[2018 BDO World Trophy|BDO World Trophy]] for the first time, lost in the final of the [[2018 World Masters (darts)|Winmau World Masters]] and won the [[Finder Darts Masters]].\n\nDespite being the reigning Lakeside champion. Durrant was seeded number 2 for the [[2019 BDO World Darts Championship]] and defeated [[Mark McGrath (darts player)|Mark McGrath]], [[Scott Baker (darts player)|Scott Baker]], [[Kyle McKinstry]], [[Jim Williams (darts player)|Jim Williams]] and [[Scott Waites]] in the final to once again retain the championship. He is the only player since [[Eric Bristow]] to win the championship 3 years in a row.\n\n==PDC==\n\n===2019-present===\n\nDurrant announced on 15 November 2018 his intentions to enter the PDC Q-School in January regardless of his performance in the [[2019 BDO World Darts Championship|BDO World Championship]] due to there being no penalties from the BDO, unlike previous years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/12/11/glen-durrant-one-eye-pdc-q-school-ahead-lakeside-plenty-bdo-stars-8234234/ |title=Glen Durrant has one eye on PDC Q School ahead of Lakeside, and so do plenty more BDO stars |website=Metro |date=11 December 2018}}</ref> He lost in the last 128 round at the first two days of Q School to Darren Herewini and Vince Tipple, collecting two points on the Q School Order or Merit. Durrant did better on the third day, but lost at the final hurdle to [[Reece Robinson (darts player)|Reece Robinson]].\n\nOn Sunday 21 January, Durrant survived match darts from [[Matthew Dennant]] before going on to reach the last 32 and seal his two-year PDC Tour Card via the UK Q-School Order of Merit.\n\nFollowing [[Gary Anderson (darts player)|Gary Anderson]]'s withdrawal from the [[2019 Premier League Darts|2019 Premier League]], Durrant was selected as one of nine 'contenders' to replace him. He would play a one-off match against [[Daryl Gurney]] on night two in [[Glasgow]] which he lost 7-3.\n\nAt the second PDC Players Championship event in 2019, Durrant made his first PDC final after he beat [[Joe Cullen (darts player)|Joe Cullen]] 7\u20134 in the Semi-Final. He hit a 170 checkout to stay in the match against [[Dave Chisnall]], but eventually lost the final 8\u20137. The following week, Durrant would claim his first PDC title in just his fourth Pro Tour event, dispatching [[Dimitri Van den Bergh]] 8-3 in the final. On 18 May 2019, Durrant clinched his second PDC title at Players Championship 15 after a series of impressive performances on the day, beating [[Darius Labanauskas]] 8-1 in the final, having already dismissed World number 1 [[Michael van Gerwen]] 7-2 in the semi final. At the [[2019 World Matchplay (darts)|World Matchplay]] in July, Durrant advanced to the semi-finals, a run which included wins over [[Adrian Lewis]], van Gerwen and [[James Wade]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/darts/news/12288/11769226/glen-durrant-beats-michael-van-gerwen-to-reach-world-matchplay-quarter-final|work=Sky Sports|date=25 July 2019|accessdate=4 January 2020|title=Glen Durrant beats Michael van Gerwen to reach World Matchplay quarter-final}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/darts/49124821|work=BBC Sport|date=26 July 2019|accessdate=4 January 2020|title=PDC World Matchplay: Glen Durrant beats James Wade to reach semi-finals}}</ref> He lost his semi-final 17\u201310 to [[Michael Smith (darts player)|Michael Smith]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pdc.tv/news/2019/07/28/frustration-durrant-after-smith-defeat|work=pdc.tv|date=28 July 2019|accessdate=4 January 2020|title=Frustration For Durrant After Smith Defeat\n}}</ref>\n\n==World Championship results ==\n\n===BDO===\n\n* 2014: Second round (lost to [[Alan Norris (darts player)|Alan Norris]] 1\u20134)\n* 2015: Semi-finals (lost to [[Martin Adams]] 5\u20136)\n* 2016: Quarter-finals (lost to [[Scott Waites]] 4\u20135)\n* 2017: '''Winner''' (beat [[Danny Noppert]] 7\u20133)\n* 2018: '''Winner''' (beat [[Mark McGeeney]] 7\u20136)\n* 2019: '''Winner''' (beat [[Scott Waites]] 7\u20133)\n\n===PDC===\n* 2020: Quarter-finals (lost to [[Gerwyn Price]] 1\u20135)\n\n==Career finals==\n\n===BDO major finals: 10 (9 titles, 1 runner-up)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n|'''Legend'''\n|- style=\"background:#e5d1cb;\"\n| World Championship (3\u20130)\n|- style=\"background:#dfe2e9;\"\n|  Winmau World Masters (2\u20131)\n|- style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n|  Zuiderduin Masters (3\u20130)\n|- style=\"background:#ffc;\"\n|  BDO World Trophy (1\u20130)\n|}\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"width:80px;\" |'''Outcome'''\n| style=\"width:20px;\" |'''No.'''\n| style=\"width:50px;\" |'''Year'''\n| style=\"width:250px;\" |'''Championship'''\n| style=\"width:200px;\" |'''Opponent in the final'''\n| style=\"width:70px;\" |'''Score'''<ref group=N na